meaning: Feminine form of the Late Latin name Clarus which meant "clear, bright, famous". The name Clarus was borne by a few early saints. The feminine form was popularized by the 13th-century Saint Clare of Assisi (called Chiara in Italian), a friend and follower of Saint Francis, who left her wealthy family to found the order of nuns known as the Poor Clares. As an English name it has been in use since the Middle Ages, originally in the form Clare, though the Latinate spelling Clara became more popular in the 19th century.
name: CLARA
origin: [Italian, German, Spanish, Portuguese, Catalan, Romanian, English, Swedish, Danish, Late Roman]

meaning: From the Latin title Clarensis which belonged to members of the British royal family. The title ultimately derives from the name of the town of Clare in Suffolk. As a given name it has been in use since the 19th century.
name: CLARENCE

meaning: Medieval vernacular form of the Late Latin name Claritia, which was a derivative of CLARA.
name: CLARICE

meaning: Simply means "clarity, lucidity" from the English word, ultimately from Latin clarus "clear".
name: CLARITY

meaning: Masculine Latin form of CLARA. This was the name of several early saints.
name: CLARUS

meaning: French masculine and feminine form of CLAUDIUS. In France the masculine name has been common since the Middle Ages due to the 7th-century Saint Claude of Besançon. It was imported to Britain in the 16th century by the aristocratic Hamilton family, who had French connections. A famous bearer of this name was the French impressionist painter Claude Monet (1840-1926).
name: CLAUDE

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from various English place names, all meaning "clay settlement" in Old English.
name: CLAYTON

meaning: French feminine form of Clementius (see CLEMENT).
name: CLÉMENCE

meaning: Medieval variant of CLEMENCE. It can also simply mean "clemency, mercy" from the English word, ultimately from Latin clemens "merciful".
name: CLEMENCY

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of Clemens (see CLEMENT).
name: CLEMENTE

meaning: Latinized form of Κλεων (Kleon), a Greek name derived from κλεος (kleos) "glory".
name: CLEON

meaning: From the Greek name Κλεοπατρα (Kleopatra) which meant "glory of the father", derived from κλεος (kleos) "glory" combined with πατηρ (pater) "father" (genitive πατρος), This was the name of queens of Egypt from the Ptolemaic royal family, including Cleopatra VII, the mistress of both Julius Caesar and Mark Antony. After being defeated by Augustus she committed suicide by allowing herself to be bitten by an asp. Shakespeare's tragedy 'Antony and Cleopatra' (1606) is based on her.
name: CLEOPATRA

meaning: Short form of ANACLETUS. This name is sometimes used to refer to the third pope, Saint Anacletus. It can also function an an Anglicized form of KLEITOS.
name: CLETUS

meaning: From a surname which was derived from an Old English place name meaning "hilly land". This was the surname of American president Grover Cleveland (1837-1908). It is also the name of an American city, which was founded by surveyor Moses Cleaveland (1754-1806).
name: CLEVELAND

meaning: Short form of CLIFFORD or CLIFTON.
name: CLIFF

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "settlement by a cliff" in Old English.
name: CLIFTON

meaning: Short form of CLINTON. A notable bearer is American actor Clint Eastwood (1930-), who became famous early in his career for his western movies.
name: CLINT

meaning: From a surname meaning "cliff" in Old English, originally belonging to a person who lived near a cliff.
name: CLIVE

meaning: Portuguese form and French variant of CHLOE.
name: CLOÉ

meaning: From the name of a district in London, originally derived from Old English and meaning "landing place for chalk or limestone". It has been in general use as an English given name since the 1970s.
name: CHELSEA

meaning: Short form of CHERYL. In the case of the American musician Cher (1946-), it is short for her real name CHERILYN.
name: CHER

meaning: Derived from French chérie meaning "darling". In America, Cherie came into use shortly after the variant Sherry, and has not been as common.
name: CHERIE

meaning: Means "the black god" from Slavic cherno "black" and bogu "god". Chernobog was the Slavic god of darkness, evil and grief.
name: CHERNOBOG

meaning: Simply means "cherry" from the name of the fruit. It can also be a diminutive of CHARITY. It has been in use since the late 19th century.
name: CHERRY

meaning: Elaboration of CHERIE, perhaps influenced by BERYL. This name was not used before the 20th century.
name: CHERYL

meaning: From a surname that was originally from a place name meaning "camp meadow" in Old English.
name: CHESLEY

meaning: Derived from the Dakota word shahiyena meaning "red speakers". This is the name of a Native American people of the Great Plains. The name was supposedly given to the Cheyenne by the Dakota because their language was unrelated to their own. As a given name, it has been in use since the 1950s.
name: CHEYENNE

meaning: Means "god, spirtual being" in Igbo, referring to the personal spiritual guardian that each person is believed to have. Christian Igbo people use it as a name for the personal Christian god. This can also be a short form of the many Igbo names that begin with this element.
name: CHI  (2)

meaning: Means "God has performed great deeds" in Igbo.
name: CHIEMEKA

meaning: Means "God holds my life" in Igbo.
name: CHIJINDUM

meaning: From Japanese 千 (chi) meaning "thousand", 智 (chi) meaning "wisdom, intellect" or 散 (chi) meaning "scatter" combined with 佳 (ka) meaning "good, beautiful" or 花 (ka) meaning "flower". Other kanji combinations are also possible.
name: CHIKA  (2)

meaning: From the name of the Asian country, ultimately derived from Qin, the name of a dynasty that ruled there in the 3rd century BC.
name: CHINA

meaning: From Japanese 千 (chi) meaning "thousand" and 夏 (natsu) meaning "summer", as well as other kanji combinations.
name: CHINATSU

meaning: Means "God owns" in Igbo. It is also a short form of Igbo names beginning with Chinwe.
name: CHINWE

meaning: From Japanese 千 (chi) meaning "thousand" and 代 (yo) meaning "generation" and 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other combinations of kanji characters are possible.
name: CHIYOKO

meaning: Means "green shoot" in Greek, referring to new plant growth in the spring. This was an epithet of the Greek goddess Demeter. The name is also mentioned by Paul in one of his epistles in the New Testament. As an English name, Chloe has been in use since the Protestant Reformation.
name: CHLOE
origin: [English, Biblical, Biblical Latin, Biblical Greek, Ancient Greek, Greek Mythology]

meaning: Derived from Greek χλωρος (chloros) meaning "pale green". Chloris, in Greek mythology, was a minor goddess of vegetation.
name: CHLORIS

meaning: From Japanese 蝶 (chou) meaning "butterfly" and 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other kanji combinations can be possible.
name: CHOUKO

meaning: Combination of CHRISTINA and the name suffix bel. This name occurs in medieval literature, and was later used by Samuel Coleridge in his poem 'Christabel' (1800).
name: CHRISTABEL

meaning: Swedish and Danish diminutive of CHRISTIAN.
name: CHRISTER

meaning: French form of CHRISTINA, as well as a variant in other languages.
name: CHRISTINE
origin: [French, English, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Dutch]

meaning: From the Late Greek name Χριστοφορος (Christophoros) meaning "bearing CHRIST", derived from Χριστος (Christos) combined with φερω (phero) "to bear, to carry". Early Christians used it as a metaphorical name, expressing that they carried Christ in their hearts. In the Middle Ages, literal interpretations of the name's etymology led to legends about a Saint Christopher who carried the young Jesus across a river. He has come to be regarded as the patron saint of travellers.... [more]
name: CHRISTOPHER

meaning: Shortened form of the word chrysanthemum, the name of a flowering plant, which means "golden flower" in Greek.
name: CHRYSANTA

meaning: Modern Greek feminine form of CHRYSANTHOS.
name: CHRYSANTHI

meaning: Patronymic derived from CHRYSES. In Greek legend she was the daughter of Chryses, a priest of Apollo. After she was taken prisoner by the Greeks besieging Troy, Apollo sent a plague into their camp, forcing the Greeks to release her.
name: CHRYSEIS

meaning: Diminutive of Igbo names beginning with the element Chukwu meaning "God".
name: CHUKS

meaning: Variant of CHIDI, using Chukwu as the first element, which is the extended form of Chi meaning "God".
name: CHUKWUDI

meaning: Variant of CHIMA, using Chukwu as the first element, which is the extended form of Chi meaning "God".
name: CHUKWUMA

meaning: From Chinese 春 (chūn) meaning "spring (the season)" or other characters with a similar pronunciation.
name: CHUN

meaning: Means "ancient" in Gaelic. This was the name of the mythical ancestor of the Cianachta in Irish legend. Cian was also the name of a son-in-law of Brian Boru.
name: CIAN

meaning: Feminine form of CIAR. Saint Ciara was an Irish nun who established a monastery at Kilkeary in the 7th century.
name: CIARA  (1)

meaning: Diminutive of CIAR. This was the name of two Irish saints: Saint Ciarán the Elder, the patron of the Kingdom of Munster, and Saint Ciarán of Clonmacnoise, the founder of a monastery in the 6th century.
name: CIARÁN

meaning: Means "sky" in French. It is not used as a given name in France itself.
name: CIEL

meaning: Probably from Gaelic ceall "church" combined with a diminutive suffix. This was the name of a 7th-century Irish saint who evangelized in Franconia. He was martyred in Würzburg.
name: CILLIAN

meaning: Means "born of fire" in Gaelic. This was the name of the first king of the Scots and Picts (9th century). It is often Anglicized as Kenneth.
name: CINÁED

meaning: Latinized form of Greek Κιρκη (Kirke), which possibly meant "bird". In Greek mythology Circe was a sorceress who changed Odysseus's crew into hogs but was forced by him to change them back.
name: CIRCE

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of CYRIACUS.
name: CIRIACO

meaning: Means "image" in Indonesian, ultimately from Sanskrit चित्र (chitra).
name: CITRA

meaning: From the Irish surname Mac Fhlannchaidh which means "son of Flannchadh". The Gaelic name Flannchadh means "red warrior".
name: CLANCY

meaning: Medieval English form of CLARA. This is also the name of an Irish county, which was originally named for the Norman invader Richard de Clare (known as Strongbow), whose surname was derived from the name of an English river.
name: CLARE

meaning: Combination of CLARA and the popular name suffix bel. This name was used by Edmund Spenser in his poem 'The Faerie Queene' (in the form Claribell) and by Shakespeare in his play 'The Tempest' (1611). Alfred Lord Tennyson also wrote a poem entitled 'Claribel' (1830).
name: CLARIBEL

meaning: Combination of CLARA and the popular name suffix inda. It was first used by Edmund Spenser in his epic poem 'The Faerie Queene' (1590).
name: CLARINDA

meaning: Latinate form of CLARICE. This was the name of the title character in a 1748 novel by Samuel Richardson. In the novel Clarissa is a virtuous woman who is tragically exploited by her family and her lover.
name: CLARISSA

meaning: From an English surname meaning "cleric" or "scribe", from Old English clerec which originally meant "priest". A famous bearer of the surname was William Clark (1770-1838), an explorer of the west of North America. It was also borne by the American actor Clark Gable (1901-1960).
name: CLARK

meaning: Feminine form of CLAUDIUS. It is mentioned briefly in the New Testament. As a Christian name it was very rare until the 16th century.
name: CLAUDIA
origin: [English, German, Dutch, Italian, Spanish, Romanian, Biblical, Ancient Roman]

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of CLAUDIUS.
name: CLAUDIO

meaning: From a Roman family name which was possibly derived from Latin claudus meaning "lame, crippled". This was the name of a patrician family prominent in Roman politics. The ancestor of the family was said to have been a 6th-century BC Sabine leader named Attius Clausus, who adopted the name Appius Claudius upon becoming a Roman citizen. The family produced several Roman emperors of the 1st century, including the emperor known simply as Claudius. He was poisoned by his wife Agrippina in order to bring her son Nero (Claudius's stepson) to power. The name was later borne by several early saints, including a 7th-century bishop of Besançon.
name: CLAUDIUS

meaning: From an English surname that originally referred to a person who lived near or worked with clay. This name can also be a short form of CLAYTON.
name: CLAY

meaning: Derived from the Welsh element caled "rough" combined with gwyn "white, fair, blessed".
name: CLEDWYN

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Κλεισθενης (Kleisthenes), derived from κλεος (kleos) "glory" and σθενος (sthenos) "strength". This was the name of a 5th-century BC Athenian statesman and reformer. He helped establish democracy in Athens.
name: CLEISTHENES

meaning: From the English word for a type of flowering vine, ultimately derived from Greek κλημα (klema) "twig, branch".
name: CLEMATIS

meaning: Feminine form of Clementius (see CLEMENT). It has been in use since the Middle Ages, though it became rare after the 17th century.
name: CLEMENCE

meaning: Original Latin form of CLEMENT, as well as the German, Dutch and Scandinavian form.
name: CLEMENS
origin: [German, Dutch, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Late Roman]

meaning: English form of the Late Latin name Clemens (or sometimes of its derivative Clementius) which meant "merciful, gentle". This was the name of 14 popes, including Saint Clement I, the third pope, one of the Apostolic Fathers. Another saint by this name was Clement of Alexandria, a 3rd-century theologian and church father who attempted to reconcile Christian and Platonic philosophies. It has been in general as a given name in Christian Europe (in various spellings) since early times. In England it became rare after the Protestant Reformation, though it was revived in the 19th century.
name: CLEMENT

meaning: Feminine form of Clemens or Clementius (see CLEMENT).
name: CLEMENTIA

meaning: Shortened form of the Greek name Kleopatros (see CLEOPATRA). In the New Testament Cleopas is a disciple who sees Jesus after his resurrection.
name: CLEOPAS

meaning: Form of CLOPAS used in several versions of the New Testament.
name: CLEOPHAS

meaning: From a surname which was originally from a place name meaning "ford by a cliff" in Old English.
name: CLIFFORD

meaning: Spanish form of Climacus, derived from Greek κλιμαξ (klimax) "ladder". The 7th-century monk Saint John Climacus (also known as John of the Ladder) acquired this name because he wrote a book called 'The Ladder of Divine Ascent'.
name: CLÍMACO

meaning: From a surname which was originally from an Old English place name meaning "settlement on the River Glyme". A famous bearer of the surname was American president Bill Clinton (1946-).
name: CLINTON

meaning: Possibly means "shapely" in Irish Gaelic. In Irish legend this was the name of a beautiful goddess. She fell in love with a mortal named Ciabhan and left the Land of Promise with him, but when she arrived on the other shore she was swept to sea by a great wave.
name: CLÍODHNA

meaning: From the name of a river in Tipperary, Ireland.
name: CLODAGH

meaning: Spanish and Italian form of CHLOE.
name: CLOE

meaning: Feminine form of CLOELIUS. In Roman legend Cloelia was a maiden who was given to an Etruscan invader as a hostage. She managed to escape by swimming across the Tiber, at the same time helping some of the other captives to safety.
name: CLOELIA

meaning: Roman family name of unknown meaning.
name: CLOELIUS

meaning: French form of the Germanic name Chlotichilda which was composed of the elements hlud "fame" and hild "battle". Saint Clotilde was the wife of the Frankish king Clovis, whom she converted to Christianity.
name: CLOTILDE

meaning: Shortened form of Clodovicus, a Latinized form of Chlodovech (see LUDWIG). Clovis was a Frankish king who united France under his rule in the 5th century.
name: CLOVIS

meaning: Latinized form of Greek Κλυταιμνηστρα (Klytaimnestra), from κλυτος (klytos) "famous, noble" and μνηστηρ (mnester) "courter, wooer". In Greek legend Clytemnestra was the wife of Agamemnon and the mother of Orestes and Electra. While her husband was away during the Trojan War she took a lover, and upon his return she had him murdered. She was subsequently killed by Orestes.
name: CLYTEMNESTRA

meaning: Masculine or feminine diminutive of JACOB.
name: COBY

meaning: From a common Jewish surname which was derived from Hebrew כֹּהֵן (kohen) meaning "priest". This surname was traditionally associated with the hereditary priests who claimed descent from the biblical Aaron.
name: COHEN

meaning: Derived from Gaelic caoin "handsome". It is often Anglicized as Kenneth.
name: COINNEACH

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from a Norman form of the Germanic name COLOBERT.
name: COLBERT

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from the Old English byname COLA.
name: COLE

meaning: Short form of NICOLETTE. Saint Colette was a 15th-century French nun who gave her money to the poor. This was also the pen name of the French author Sidonie-Gabrielle Colette (1873-1954).
name: COLETTE

meaning: Medieval diminutive of Col, a short form of NICHOLAS.
name: COLIN  (2)

meaning: Derived from the Irish word cailín meaning "girl". It is not commonly used in Ireland itself, but has been used in America since the early 20th century.
name: COLLEEN

meaning: Diminutive of Colm (see COLUM). This was the name of a large number of Irish saints.
name: COLMÁN

meaning: From an English surname which was originally from a place name meaning "COLA's town".
name: COLTON

meaning: Late Latin name meaning "dove". The dove is a symbol of the Holy Spirit in Christianity. This was the name of several early saints both masculine and feminine, most notably the 6th-century Irish monk Saint Columba (or Colum) who established a monastery on the island of Iona off the coast of Scotland. He is credited with the conversion of Scotland to Christianity.
name: COLUMBA

meaning: This name can be viewed as a derivative of COLUMBA or a Latinized form of COLUMBAN, both derivations being approximately equivalent. This is the name of Saint Columban in Latin sources.
name: COLUMBANUS

meaning: From the name of a river in northern Wales.
name: COLWYN

meaning: From the English word comfort, ultimately from Latin confortare "to strengthen greatly", a derivative of fortis "strong". It was used as a given name after the Protestant Reformation.
name: COMFORT

meaning: Means "joint pledge" from Irish comh "together" and gall "pledge".
name: COMHGHALL

meaning: Means "strong wolf" in Gaelic. This is the name of several characters in Irish legend including the hero Conall Cernach ("Conall of the victories"), a member of the Red Branch of Ulster, who avenged Cúchulainn's death by killing Lugaid.
name: CONALL

meaning: Means "conception" in Spanish. This name is given in reference to the Immaculate Conception of the Virgin Mary. A city in Chile bears this name.
name: CONCEPCIÓN

meaning: In the case of American Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice it is derived from the Italian musical term con dolcezza meaning "with sweetness".
name: CONDOLEEZZA

meaning: From Sino-Vietnamese 公 (công) meaning "fair, equitable, public".
name: CÔNG

meaning: Modern form of the old Irish name Conláed, possibly meaning "chaste fire" from Gaelic connla "chaste" and aodh "fire". Saint Conláed was a 5th-century bishop of Kildare.
name: CONLETH

meaning: Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Conchobhar which means "dog lover" or "wolf lover". It has been in use in Ireland for centuries and was the name of several Irish kings. It was also borne by the legendary Ulster king Conchobar mac Nessa, known for his tragic desire for Deirdre.
name: CONOR

meaning: Means "consoled" in Italian. It is taken from the title of the Virgin Mary, María Consolata.
name: CONSOLATA

meaning: Medieval form of CONSTANTIA. The Normans introduced this name to England (it was the name of a daughter of William the Conqueror).
name: CONSTANCE

meaning: Late Latin name meaning "constant, steadfast". This was the name of a 4th-century Roman emperor, a son of Constantine the Great.
name: CONSTANS

meaning: Possibly derived from Latin conserere meaning "to sow, to plant". Consus was a Roman god of the harvest and grain.
name: CONSUS

meaning: From a surname meaning "barrel maker" in Middle English.
name: COOPER

meaning: Latinized form of KORE. It was not used as a given name in the English-speaking world until after it was employed by James Fenimore Cooper for a character in his novel 'The Last of the Mohicans' (1826). In some cases it may be a short form of CORDULA, CORINNA or other names beginning with a similar sound.
name: CORA

meaning: Either a French form of KORALIA, or a derivative of Latin corallium "coral" (see CORAL).
name: CORALIE

meaning: From a surname meaning "maker of cord" or "seller of cord" in Middle English.
name: CORDELL

meaning: Diminutive of CORA. It was borne by Coretta Scott King (1927-2006), the wife of Martin Luther King.
name: CORETTA

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Κοριννα (Korinna), which was derived from κορη (kore) "maiden". This was the name of a Greek lyric poet of the 5th century BC. The Roman poet Ovid used it for the main female character in his book 'Amores'. In the modern era it has been in use since the 17th century, when Robert Herrick used it in his poem 'Corinna's going a-Maying'.
name: CORINNA

meaning: Possibly derived from Irish Gaelic corb "raven" or "wheel" and mac "son". This was the name of a 3rd-century king of Ireland.
name: CORMAC

meaning: Spanish and Italian form of CORNELIUS.
name: CORNELIO

meaning: From a surname which was derived from the given name CORNELIUS.
name: CORNELL

meaning: Means "little spear", derived from Irish corradh "spear" and a diminutive suffix.
name: CORRAIDHÍN

meaning: From French chosette meaning "little thing". This is the nickname of the illegitimate daughter of Fantine in Victor Hugo's novel 'Les Misérables' (1862). Her real name is Euphrasie, though it is seldom used. In the novel young Cosette is the ward of the cruel Thénardiers until she is retrieved by Jean Valjean.
name: COSETTE

meaning: Italian variant of COSMAS. A famous bearer was Cosimo de' Medici, the 15th-century founder of Medici rule in Florence, who was a patron of the Renaissance and a successful merchant. Other members of the Medici family have also borne this name.
name: COSIMO

meaning: Portuguese and French form of COSMAS.
name: COSME

meaning: From a surname which meant "quiet, shy, coy" from Middle English coi.
name: COY

meaning: From a surname which was derived from a place name meaning "crow ford" in Old English.
name: CRAWFORD

meaning: From a surname which was derived from a place name, originally from Gaelic crioch "border" combined with Old English tun "town".
name: CREIGHTON

meaning: Latin name which was derived from crescere "to grow". This name is mentioned briefly in one of Paul's epistles in the New Testament.
name: CRESCENS

meaning: Latin name which was a derivative of the name CRESCENS. Saint Crescentius was a child martyred in Rome during the persecutions of emperor Diocletian in the early 4th century.
name: CRESCENTIUS

meaning: Medieval form of CHRYSEIS. Various medieval tales describe her as a woman of Troy, daughter of Calchus, who leaves her Trojan lover Troilus for the Greek hero Diomedes. Shakespeare's play 'Troilus and Cressida' (1602) was based on these tales.
name: CRESSIDA

meaning: From the Roman cognomen Crispinus which was derived from the name CRISPUS. Saint Crispin was a 3rd-century Roman who was martyred with his twin brother Crispinian in Gaul. They are the patrons of shoemakers. They were popular saints in England during the Middle Ages, and the name has occasionally been used since that time.
name: CRISPIN

meaning: Roman cognomen which meant "curly-haired" in Latin.
name: CRISPUS

meaning: Italian and Portuguese form of CHRISTINA.
name: CRISTIANA

meaning: Italian, Spanish, Portuguese and Romanian form of CHRISTINA.
name: CRISTINA

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek Κρονος (Kronos), possibly derived from the Indo-European root *ker- meaning "to cut". Cronus was the Titan who fathered the Greek gods. As his wife Rhea gave birth to the gods, Cronus swallowed them fearing the prophecy that he would be overthrown by one of his children. However Rhea hid Zeus, her last child, who eventually forced his father to disgorge his siblings. Cronus and the rest of the Titans were then defeated by the gods and exiled.
name: CRONUS

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements črt "hatred" and miru "peace, world". This is the name of the hero in the Slovene national epic 'Baptism on the Savica' (1835) by France Prešeren.
name: ČRTOMIR

meaning: Possibly derived from Hungarian cseng meaning "to ring, to clang".
name: CSENGE

meaning: Means "little wolf" or "little hound" from the Irish element cú "wolf, hound" combined with a diminutive suffix.
name: CUÁN

meaning: Means "hiding place of the pig" in Welsh. In Welsh legend he was the lover of Olwen the daughter of the giant Yspaddaden. Before the giant would allow Culhwch to marry his daughter, he insisted that Culhwch complete a series of extremely difficult tasks. Culhwch managed to complete them, and he returned to marry Olwen and kill the giant. This tale appears in the Mabinogion, a collection of tales from Welsh myth.
name: CULHWCH

meaning: Possibly means "hound of Belenus" from the old Celtic element koun "hound" combined with the name of the god BELENUS. This was the name of a 1st-century king of southeast Britain.
name: CUNOBELINUS

meaning: Either a variant of KURT or short form of CURTIS.
name: CURT

meaning: From the English word meaning "greenish blue", ultimately derived from Greek κυανος (kyanos).
name: CYAN

meaning: Variant of SIBYL. This name was borne by actress Cybill Shepherd (1950-), who was named after her grandfather Cy and her father Bill.
name: CYBILL

meaning: Form of CUNOBELINUS used by Shakespeare in his play 'Cymbeline' (1609).
name: CYMBELINE

meaning: Derived from Welsh cyn "chief" and bel "war".
name: CYNBEL

meaning: Derived from Old English cyne "royal" and beald "bold".
name: CYNEBALD

meaning: Means "royal peace" from Old English cyne "royal" and friþ "peace".
name: CYNEFRIÐ

meaning: Derived from Old English cyne "royal" and mær "famous".
name: CYNEMÆR

meaning: Derived from Old English cyne "royal" and sige "victory".
name: CYNESIGE

meaning: Latinized form of Greek Κυνθια (Kynthia) which means "woman from Kynthos". This was an epithet of the Greek moon goddess Artemis, given because Kynthos was the mountain on Delos on which she and her twin brother Apollo were born. It was not used as a given name until the Renaissance, and it did not become common in the English-speaking world until the 19th century.
name: CYNTHIA

meaning: From the Roman family name Cyprianus which meant "from Cyprus" in Latin. Saint Cyprian was a 3rd-century bishop of Carthage and a martyr under the emperor Valerian.
name: CYPRIAN

meaning: Possibly derived from the name of the ancient Greek city of Cyrene, which was located in North Africa. Edmond Rostand used this name in his play 'Cyrano de Bergerac' (1897). He based his character upon a real person, Savinien Cyrano de Bergerac, a French satirist of the 17th century.
name: CYRANO

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Κυριακος (Kyriakos), which meant "of the lord" (derived from Greek κυριος (kyrios) "lord"). This was the name of a few early saints.
name: CYRIACUS

meaning: From the Greek name Κυριλλος (Kyrillos) which was derived from Greek κυριος (kyrios) "lord", a word used frequently in the Greek Bible to refer to God or Jesus.... [more]
name: CYRIL

meaning: French form of CYRIL, sometimes used as a feminine form.
name: CYRILLE

meaning: From Κυρος (Kyros), the Greek form of the Persian name Kūrush, which may mean "far sighted" or "young". The name is sometimes associated with Greek κυριος (kyrios) "lord". It was borne by several kings of Persia, including Cyrus the Great, who conquered Babylon. He is famous in the Old Testament for freeing the captive Jews and allowing them to return to Israel. As an English name, it first came into use among the Puritans after the Protestant Reformation.
name: CYRUS

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements chisti "honour" and slava "glory".
name: CZESŁAW

meaning: From Chinese 达 (dá) meaning "achieve, arrive at, intelligent" (which is usually only masculine), 大 (dà) meaning "big, great, vast, high", or other characters with a similar pronunciation.
name: DA

meaning: Derived from Dacia, the old Roman name for the region which is now Romania and Moldova.
name: DACIANA

meaning: Meaning unknown, probably of Aramaic origin. In the New Testament Clopas is mentioned briefly as the husband of one of the women who witnessed the crucifixion, sometimes identified with Alphaeus.
name: CLOPAS

meaning: From the English word for the wild flower, ultimately deriving from Old English clafre.
name: CLOVER

meaning: From the name of the River Clyde in Scotland, which is of unknown origin. It became a common given name in America in the middle of the 19th century, perhaps in honour of Sir Colin Campbell (1792-1863) who was given the title Baron Clyde in 1858.
name: CLYDE

meaning: Diminutive of names beginning with Co, influenced by the word cocoa. However, this was not the case for French fashion designer Coco Chanel (real name Gabrielle), whose nickname came from the name of a song she performed while working as a cabaret singer.
name: COCO

meaning: From the Gaelic surname Ó Cuidighthigh, which means "descendant of CUIDIGHTHEACH". A famous bearer of the surname was the American frontiersman and showman Buffalo Bill Cody (1846-1917).
name: CODY

meaning: Old English byname meaning "charcoal", originally given to a person with dark features.
name: COLA

meaning: From a surname, originally from various English place names, derived from the Old Norse nickname Koli (meaning "coal, dark") and býr "town".
name: COLBY

meaning: Anglicized form of CAILEAN or COILEAN.
name: COLIN  (1)

meaning: Germanic name composed of the elements col, possibly meaning "helmet", and beraht meaning "bright".
name: COLOBERT

meaning: Italian feminine diminutive of COLUMBA. In traditional Italian pantomimes this is the name of a stock character, the female counterpart of Arlecchino (also called Harlequin). This is also the Italian word for the columbine flower.
name: COLOMBINA

meaning: Irish form of COLUMBA. This is also an Old Irish word meaning "dove", derived from Latin columba.
name: COLUM

meaning: Possibly an Irish diminutive of COLUMBA. Alternatively, it may be derived from Old Irish colum "dove" and bán "white". The 7th-century Saint Columban of Leinster was the founder of several monasteries in Europe.
name: COLUMBAN

meaning: From the name of a variety of flower. It is also an English form of COLOMBINA, the pantomime character.
name: COLUMBINE

meaning: Means "born together" from Irish comh "together" and gan "born".
name: COMHGHÁN

meaning: Means "little wolf" or "little hound" from Gaelic cú "wolf, hound" combined with a diminutive suffix. Sir Arthur Conan Doyle was the author who wrote the Sherlock Holmes mystery stories.
name: CONAN

meaning: Diminutive of CONCEPCIÓN. This name can also mean "seashell" in Spanish.
name: CONCHA

meaning: Means "harmony" in Latin. This was the name of the Roman goddess of harmony and peace.
name: CONCORDIA

meaning: Anglicized form of the Chinese name Kong Fuzi. The surname 孔 (Kong) means "hole, opening" and the title 夫子 (Fuzi) means "master". This was the name of a 6th-century BC Chinese philosopher. His given name was Qiu.
name: CONFUCIUS

meaning: Possibly derived from Gaelic conn "chief" and flaith "lord". This was the name of several characters in Irish legend including a son of Cúchulainn who was accidentally killed by his father.
name: CONLAOCH

meaning: From an Irish surname, an Anglicized form of Ó Conaill meaning "descendant of CONALL".
name: CONNELL

meaning: Diminutive of CONSTANCE and other names beginning with Con. It is occasionally a masculine name, a diminutive of CORNELIUS or CONRAD.
name: CONNIE

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements kuoni "brave" and rad "counsel". This was the name of a 10th-century saint and bishop of Konstanz, in southern Germany. It was also borne by several medieval German kings and dukes. In England it was occasionally used during the Middle Ages, but has only been common since the 19th century when it was reintroduced from Germany.
name: CONRAD

meaning: From the Late Latin name CONSTANS. It was also used by the Puritans as a vocabulary name, from the English word constant.
name: CONSTANT

meaning: Feminine form of the Late Latin name Constantius, which was itself derived from CONSTANS.
name: CONSTANTIA

meaning: Romanian and French form of Constantinus (see CONSTANTINE).
name: CONSTANTIN

meaning: From the Latin name Constantinus, a derivative of CONSTANS. Constantine the Great (272-337) was the first Roman emperor to adopt Christianity. He moved the capital of the empire from Rome to Byzantium, which he renamed Constantinople (modern Istanbul).
name: CONSTANTINE

meaning: Late Latin name which was a derivative of CONSTANS.
name: CONSTANTIUS

meaning: Means "consolation" in Spanish. It is taken from the title of the Virgin Mary, Nuestra Señora del Consuelo, meaning "Our Lady of Consolation".
name: CONSUELO

meaning: From a surname which was derived from the name of the River Conwy, which possibly means "holy water" in Welsh.
name: CONWAY

meaning: From the English and Spanish word coral for the underwater skeletal deposits which can form reefs. It is ultimately derived (via Old French and Latin) from Greek κοραλλιον (korallion).
name: CORAL

meaning: From a French surname which was derived from corbeau "raven", originally denoting a person who had dark hair. The name was probably popularized in America by actor Corbin Bernsen (1954-).
name: CORBIN

meaning: From Cordeilla, possibly a Celtic name of unknown meaning. According to Geoffrey of Monmouth, Cordeilla was the youngest of the three daughters of King Lear and the only one to remain loyal to her father. When adapting the character for his play 'King Lear' (1606), Shakespeare altered the spelling to Cordelia.
name: CORDELIA

meaning: Late Latin name meaning "heart" from Latin cor, cordis. Saint Cordula was one of the 4th-century companions of Saint Ursula.
name: CORDULA

meaning: Possibly means "hurricane" in Breton. This was the name of a 5th-century bishop of Quimper in Brittany.
name: CORENTIN

meaning: From a surname which was derived from the Old Norse given name Kóri, of unknown meaning. This name became popular in the 1960s due to the character Corey Baker on the television series 'Julia'.
name: COREY

meaning: From the name of the spice, also called cilantro, which may ultimately be of Phoenician origin (via Latin and Greek).
name: CORIANDER

meaning: French form of CORINNA. The French-Swiss author Madame de Staël used it for her novel 'Corinne' (1807).
name: CORINNE

meaning: Feminine form of CORNELIUS. In the 2nd century BC it was borne by Cornelia Scipionis Africana (the daughter of the military hero Scipio Africanus), the mother of the two reformers known as the Gracchi. After her death she was regarded as an example of the ideal Roman woman. The name was revived in the 18th century.
name: CORNELIA
origin: [German, Romanian, Italian, Dutch, English, Ancient Roman]

meaning: Roman family name which possibly derives from the Latin element cornu "horn". In Acts in the New Testament Cornelius is a centurion who is directed by an angel to seek Peter. After speaking with Peter he converts to Christianity, and he is traditionally deemed the first gentile convert. The name was also borne by a few early saints, including a 3rd-century pope. In England it came into use in the 16th century, partly due to Dutch influence.
name: CORNELIUS

meaning: Means "crown" in Latin, as well as Italian and Spanish. This was the name of a 2nd-century saint who was martyred with her companion Victor.
name: CORONA

meaning: Italian form of CONRAD. This was a 14th-century saint from Piacenza, Italy.
name: CORRADO

meaning: Diminutive of CORINNA, CORA, CORNELIA and other names starting with Cor. Since the 1970s it has also been used as a feminine form of COREY.
name: CORRIE

meaning: From an English surname, derived from Old French cordoan "leather", ultimately from the name of the Spanish city of Cordova.
name: CORWIN

meaning: From the Greek name Κοσμας (Kosmas), which was derived from κοσμος (kosmos) meaning "order, decency". Saint Cosmas was martyred with his twin brother Damian in the 4th century. They are the patron saints of physicians.
name: COSMAS

meaning: English form of COSMAS. It was introduced to Britain in the 18th century by the second Scottish Duke of Gordon, who named his son and successor after his friend Cosimo III de' Medici.
name: COSMO

meaning: From an aristocratic English surname which was derived either from the French place name Courtenay (originally a derivative of the personal name Curtenus, itself derived from Latin curtus "short") or else from a Norman nickname meaning "short nose". As a feminine name in America, it first became popular during the 1970s.
name: COURTNEY

meaning: Means "little child" in Ojibwe. This was the name of a late 19th-century chief of the Saulteaux.
name: COWESSESS

meaning: From a Scottish surname which was derived from Gaelic creag meaning "crag" or "rocks", originally indicating a person who lived near a crag.
name: CRAIG

meaning: From the name of a Native American tribe of central Canada. Their name derives via French from the Cree word kiristino.
name: CREE

meaning: Italian and Portuguese form of CHRISTIAN. A famous bearer is Portuguese soccer player Cristiano Ronaldo (1985-).
name: CRISTIANO

meaning: From a surname which was derived from a place name meaning "town with a small enclosed field" in Old English.
name: CROFTON

meaning: Derived from the Slavic element dragu meaning "precious".
name: DRAGICA

meaning: Derived from the Slavic element dragu meaning "precious" combined with miru meaning "peace, world".
name: DRAGOMIR
origin: [Serbian, Croatian, Romanian, Bulgarian, Slovene, Medieval Slavic]

meaning: Originally a short form of Slavic names beginning with the element dragu "precious", such as DRAGOMIR. This was the name of a 14th-century ruler of Moldavia.
name: DRAGOȘ

meaning: Czech and Slovak feminine form of DRAGOMIR.
name: DRAHOMÍRA

meaning: Czech and Slovak feminine form of DRAGOSLAV.
name: DRAHOSLAVA

meaning: Means "daughter of DRUPADA" in Sanskrit. In the Hindu epic the 'Mahabharata' this is the name of the daughter of king Drupada. She married all of the Pandavas, the five sons of Pandu.
name: DRAUPADI

meaning: Derived from the Slavic element dragu meaning "precious".
name: DRAŽEN

meaning: Norman name, possibly derived from Gothic dragen "to carry" or Saxon drog "ghost". Alternatively, it could be from the Slavic element dragu "precious, dear". The Normans introduced this name to England.
name: DROGO

meaning: From a Scottish surname which was derived from various place names, themselves derived from Gaelic druim meaning "ridge".
name: DRUMMOND

meaning: Pictish name probably derived from Celtic drest meaning "riot" or "tumult". This name was borne by several kings of the Picts, including their last king Drust X, who ruled in the 9th century.
name: DRUST

meaning: Roman family name, also sometimes used as a praenomen, or given name, by the Claudia family. Apparently the name was first assumed by a Roman warrior who killed a Gallic chieftain named Drausus in single combat. Drausus possibly derives from a Celtic element meaning "strong".
name: DRUSUS

meaning: Portuguese form of EDWARD. This name was borne by a 15th-century king of Portugal, who was named after his maternal ancestor Edward III of England.
name: DUARTE

meaning: Irish name derived from dubh "dark, black" combined with a diminutive suffix.
name: DUBHÁN

meaning: Old Irish name derived from dubh "dark, black" in combination with a second element of unknown meaning.
name: DUBHTHACH

meaning: From the old Slavic word dubrava meaning "oak grove".
name: DUBRAVKO

meaning: Portuguese diminutive of EDUARDO or EDUARDA.
name: DUDA

meaning: From the Roman name Duilius, which is possibly derived from Latin duellum "war". This was the name of a Roman consul who defeated the Carthaginians in a naval battle.
name: DUILIO

meaning: From the noble title duke, which was originally derived from Latin dux "leader".
name: DUKE

meaning: From Latin dulcis meaning "sweet". It was used in the Middle Ages in the spellings Dowse and Duce, and was recoined in the 19th century.
name: DULCIE

meaning: From the Old English elements dunn "dark" and stan "stone". This name was borne by a 10th-century saint, the archbishop of Canterbury. It was occasionally used in the Middle Ages, though it died out after the 16th century. It was revived by the Tractarian movement in the 19th century.
name: DUNSTAN

meaning: Italian form of the Late Latin name Durans which meant "enduring".
name: DURANTE

meaning: Croatian feminine form of GEORGE. It also means "lily of the valley" in Croatian.
name: ĐURĐICA

meaning: Means "unattainable" in Sanskrit. Durga is a Hindu warrior goddess, the fierce, twelve-armed, three-eyed form of the wife of Shiva. She is considered an incarnation of Parvati.
name: DURGA

meaning: From an occupational surname which meant "door guard" in Middle English.
name: DURWARD

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from the Old Norse given name Þórsteinn (see TORSTEN). The name was popularized by the actor Dustin Hoffman (1937-), who was apparently named after the earlier silent movie star Dustin Farnum (1874-1929).
name: DUSTIN

meaning: From a nickname given to Americans of German descent. It is derived from Deutsch, the German word for the German people.
name: DUTCH

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from the medieval feminine name Diot, a diminutive of Dionysia, the feminine form of DIONYSIUS. In America it was sometimes given in honour of Yale president Timothy Dwight (1752-1817). A famous bearer was the American president Dwight D. Eisenhower (1890-1969).
name: DWIGHT

meaning: From the Welsh elements dy meaning "great" and llanw meaning "tide, flow". In Welsh mythology Dylan was a god or hero associated with the sea. He was the son of Arianrhod and was accidentally slain by his uncle Govannon.... [more]
name: DYLAN

meaning: Anglicized form of DAMHNAIT. This was the name of a 7th-century Irish saint who was martyred by her father. She is the patron saint of the mentally ill.
name: DYMPHNA

meaning: From an English surname which meant "son of DYE".
name: DYSON

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements dobru "good" and milu "gracious, dear".
name: DOBROMIL

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements dobru "good" and slava "glory".
name: DOBROSLAV

meaning: Means "sorrows", taken from the Spanish title of the Virgin Mary María de los Dolores, meaning "Mary of Sorrows". It has been used in the English-speaking world since the 19th century, becoming especially popular in America during the 1920s and 30s.
name: DOLORES

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements domu "home" and gojiti "grow, heal, foster, nurture".
name: DOMAGOJ

meaning: Italian form of DOMINIC. Domenico Veneziano was a Renaissance painter who lived in Florence.
name: DOMENICO

meaning: Original Latin form of DOMINIC, as well as the modern Dutch form.
name: DOMINICUS

meaning: From the Roman cognomen Domitianus, itself derived from the family name DOMITIUS. This was the name of a 1st-century Roman emperor, Titus Flavius Domitianus.
name: DOMITIAN

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of DOMITILLA.
name: DOMITILA

meaning: Continental Germanic cognate of Þórr (see THOR).
name: DONAR

meaning: French, Occitan, Catalan and Polish form of DONATO.
name: DONAT

meaning: Derivative of Donatus (see DONATO). This was the name of a few early saints.
name: DONATIANUS

meaning: From Chinese 东 (dōng) meaning "east", 栋 (dòng) meaning "pillar, beam", or other characters which are pronounced similarly.
name: DONG

meaning: Composed of the Gaelic element donn "brown" combined with dubh "dark" and a diminutive suffix.
name: DONNDUBHÁN

meaning: Short form of DOROTHY, ISIDORA or THEODORA.
name: DORA
origin: [English, Italian, Spanish, Greek, Croatian, Serbian, Dutch]

meaning: Derived from Greek δορκας (dorkas) meaning "gazelle". This is the Greek translation of the name Tabitha in the New Testament (see Acts 9:36).
name: DORCAS

meaning: Portuguese and Galician form of DOLORES.
name: DORES

meaning: Possibly a feminine form of DORIAN or an elaboration of DORA.
name: DORIA

meaning: Combination of DORA and the name suffix inda. It was apparently coined by the English writers John Dryden and William D'Avenant for their play 'The Enchanted Island' (1667). In the play, a loose adaptation of Shakespeare's 'The Tempest', Dorinda is the sister of Miranda.
name: DORINDA

meaning: From the ancient Greek name Δωρις (Doris) which meant "Dorian woman". The Dorians were a Greek tribe who occupied the Peloponnese starting in the 12th century BC. In Greek mythology Doris was a sea nymph, one of the many children of Oceanus and Tethys. It began to be used as an English name in the 19th century. A famous bearer is the American actress Doris Day (1924-).
name: DORIS
origin: [English, German, Croatian, Ancient Greek, Greek Mythology]

meaning: Slovene, Croatian, Serbian and Macedonian form of DOROTHEA.
name: DOROTEJA

meaning: Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Dubhghall, which meant "dark stranger" from dubh "dark" and gall "stranger".
name: DOUGAL

meaning: From the English word for the variety of bird.
name: DOVE

meaning: From Sino-Korean 道 (do) meaning "path, road, way" and 允 (yun) meaning "allow, consent", as well as other hanja character combinations.
name: DO-YUN

meaning: Derived from the Slavic element dragu meaning "precious". It is also a short form of other Slavic names beginning with that element.
name: DRAGO

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements dragu meaning "precious" and slava "glory".
name: DRAGOSLAV

meaning: Derived from the Slavic element dragu meaning "precious".
name: DRAGUTIN

meaning: Czech and Slovak form of DRAGOMIR.
name: DRAHOMÍR

meaning: Czech and Slovak form of DRAGOSLAV.
name: DRAHOSLAV

meaning: From an English surname derived from the Old Norse byname Draki or the Old English byname Draca both meaning "dragon", both via Latin from Greek δρακων (drakon) meaning "dragon, serpent". This name coincides with the unrelated English word drake meaning "male duck".
name: DRAKE

meaning: Diminutive of names containing the Slavic element dragu meaning "precious".
name: DRAŠKO

meaning: From a surname (of unknown meaning) which was used in the movie 'The Crow' (1994).
name: DRAVEN

meaning: From an Irish surname which was an Anglicized form of Ó Eidirsceóil meaning "descendant of the messenger".
name: DRISCOLL

meaning: Form of DRUSILLA used in the Greek New Testament.
name: DROUSILLA

meaning: Means "wooden pillar" or "firm footed" in Sanskrit. In the Hindu epic the 'Mahabharata' this is the name of a king of Panchala, the father of Draupadi and Dhrishtadyumna.
name: DRUPADA

meaning: Feminine diminutive of the Roman family name DRUSUS. In Acts in the New Testament Drusilla is the wife of Felix.
name: DRUSILLA

meaning: Older form of TRISTAN. This name was borne by a 7th-century Scottish saint.
name: DRUSTAN

meaning: From an Irish surname, an Anglicized form of the Gaelic surname Ó Dubhán meaning "descendant of DUBHÁN".
name: DUANE

meaning: Old Irish name derived from dubh "dark, black" and either slán "defiance" or Sláine, the Gaelic name of the River Slaney.
name: DUBHSHLÁINE

meaning: From a surname which was originally from a place name meaning "Dudda's clearing" in Old English. The surname was borne by a British noble family.
name: DUDLEY

meaning: Means "to live long", derived from Nakh duqa "many" and vakha "to live".
name: DUKVAKHA

meaning: From Latin dulcis "sweet" and bella "beautiful". The usual medieval spelling of this name was Dowsabel, and the Latinized form Dulcibella was revived in the 18th century.
name: DULCIBELLA

meaning: Derived from Spanish dulce meaning "sweet". This name was (first?) used by Miguel de Cervantes in his novel 'Don Quixote' (1605), where it belongs to the love interest of the main character, though she never actually appears in the story.
name: DULCINEA

meaning: Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh, derived from Gaelic donn "brown" and cath "battle". This was the name of two kings of Scotland, including the one who was featured in Shakespeare's play 'Macbeth' (1606).
name: DUNCAN

meaning: Means "quince" in the South Slavic languages, a quince being a type of fruit.
name: DUNJA

meaning: Croatian and Serbian form of GEORGE.
name: ĐURO

meaning: Derived from Slavic dusha meaning "soul, spirit".
name: DUŠAN

meaning: Possibly means "destroyer of evil" in Sanskrit. In Hindu legend this is the name of a king who is the husband of Shakuntala and the father of Bharata.
name: DUSHYANTA

meaning: From a nickname originally given to people perceived as being dusty. It is also used a diminutive of DUSTIN. A famous bearer was British singer Dusty Springfield (1939-1999), who acquired her nickname as a child.
name: DUSTY

meaning: Means "two, second" in Indonesian, ultimately from Sanskrit द्वि (dvi).
name: DWI

meaning: Meaning unknown. This was the name of the Celtic god of love.
name: DWYN

meaning: Possibly from Persian گوهر (gohar) "jewel, essence" or جوهر (johar) "essence, ink" (which comes from the same root, but via a loan to Arabic and retransmission to Persian).
name: DZHOKHAR

meaning: Meaning unknown, perhaps from Sumerian meaning "house of water". This was the Akkadian and Babylonian name of the Sumerian water god Enki.
name: EA  (1)

meaning: Short form of names ending in ea.
name: EA  (2)

meaning: Means "brown horse" from Gaelic each "horse" and donn "brown". It was sometimes Anglicized as Hector.
name: EACHANN

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and wig "war". This was the name of a Saxon king of England in the 10th century. The name fell out of use after the Norman conquest.
name: EADWIG

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and wulf "wolf". This name fell out of use after the Norman conquest.
name: EADWULF

meaning: From the Old English elements eald "old" and ræd "counsel". This name was rarely used after the Norman conquest.
name: EALDRÆD

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements ealh "temple" and here "army".
name: EALHHERE

meaning: From the aristocratic title, which derives from Old English eorl "nobleman, warrior". It has been used as a given name since the 19th century.
name: EARL

meaning: From the English name of the Christian festival celebrating the resurrection of Jesus. It was ultimately named for the Germanic spring goddess Eostre. It was traditionally given to children born on Easter, though it is rare in modern times.
name: EASTER

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from place names meaning "east town" in Old English.
name: EASTON

meaning: Diminutive of EBERHARD and other names beginning with the Germanic element ebur meaning "wild boar". In Scandinavia it is also a diminutive of ESBEN.
name: EBBE

meaning: German form of EVERARD. This name was borne by a 9th-century Duke of Friuli.
name: EBERHARD

meaning: Persian form of ABRAHAM. It is also a variant transcription of Arabic IBRAHIM.
name: EBRAHIM

meaning: Short form of EDWARD, EDMUND, and other names beginning with Ed.
name: ED

meaning: Latinized form of ÉTAÍN. This was the name of an early Irish saint.
name: EDANA

meaning: Possibly from Old Norse meaning "great-grandmother". This was the name of two 13th-century Icelandic literary works: the Poetic Edda and the Prose Edda. This is also the name of a character in the Poetic Edda, though it is unclear if her name is connected to the name of the collection.
name: EDDA  (2)

meaning: Diminutive of EDWARD, EDMUND, and other names beginning with Ed.
name: EDDY

meaning: Means "place of pleasure" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament the Garden of Eden was the place where the first people, Adam and Eve, lived before they were expelled.
name: EDEN

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and gar "spear". This was the name of a 10th-century English king, Edgar the Peaceful. The name did not survive long after the Norman conquest, but it was revived in the 18th century, in part due to a character by this name in Sir Walter Scott's novel 'The Bride of Lammermoor' (1819), which tells of the tragic love between Edgar Ravenswood and Lucy Ashton. Famous bearers include author and poet Edgar Allan Poe (1809-1849), French impressionist painter Edgar Degas (1834-1917), and author Edgar Rice Burroughs (1875-1950).
name: EDGAR

meaning: Slovene diminutive of EDVARD and a Croatian diminutive of EDUARD.
name: EDI

meaning: Possibly a Hungarian form of a Germanic name.
name: EDINA

meaning: Hungarian and Swedish form of EDITH.
name: EDIT

meaning: From the Old English name Eadgyð, derived from the elements ead "wealth, fortune" and gyð "war". It was popular among Anglo-Saxon royalty, being borne for example by Saint Eadgyeth;, the daughter of King Edgar the Peaceful. The name remained common after the Norman conquest. It became rare after the 15th century, but was revived in the 19th century.
name: EDITH

meaning: Limburgish form of EDMUND. Its spelling has been influenced by the French pronunciation of Edmond.
name: EDMAO

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of EDMUND.
name: EDMUNDO

meaning: Means "pleasure" in Hebrew. This name appears in the Old Testament Apocrypha in the Book of Tobit.
name: EDNA  (2)

meaning: From the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and ric "rule". After the Norman conquest this Old English name was not commonly used. It has occasionally been revived in modern times.
name: EDRIC
EDUARD
origin: [German, Russian, Czech, Slovak, Croatian, Catalan, Dutch, Estonian, Romanian, Georgian, Armenian]

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of EDWARD.
name: EDUARDO

meaning: Means "snow" in Basque. It is a Basque equivalent of Nieves.
name: EDUR

meaning: Means "rich guard", derived from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and weard "guard". This was the name of several Anglo-Saxon kings, the last being Saint Edward the Confessor shortly before the Norman conquest in the 11th century. He was known as a just ruler, and because of his popularity his name remained in use after the conquest when most other Old English names were replaced by Norman ones. The 13th-century Plantagenet king Henry III named his son and successor after the saint, and seven subsequent kings of England were also named Edward.... [more]
name: EDWARD

meaning: Means "rich friend" from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and wine "friend". This was the name of a 7th-century Northumbrian king, regarded as a saint. After the Norman conquest the name was not popular, but it was eventually revived in the 19th century. A notable bearer was the astronaut Edwin Aldrin (1930-), also known as Buzz, the second man to walk on the moon.
name: EDWIN

meaning: Means "here is my wealth" in Urhobo.
name: EFEMENA

meaning: From the Latin byname Ephesius, which originally belonged to a person who was from the city of Ephesus in Ionia. This was the name of a saint martyred on Sardinia in the 4th century.
name: EFISIO

meaning: Germanic name derived from the elements agil "edge of a sword" and hard "brave, hardy".
name: EGILHARD

meaning: Means "spruce tree" in Lithuanian. In a Lithuanian legend Eglė was a young woman who married a sea snake.
name: EGLĖ

meaning: Derived from the Germanic element ag, which means "edge of a sword".
name: EGON

meaning: Means "united" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of one of the biblical judges. He killed Eglon, the king of Moab, and freed the city of Jericho from Moabite rule.
name: EHUD

meaning: Short form of names beginning with the Germanic element ag "edge".
name: EIKE

meaning: Frisian and Scandinavian form of EGILHARD.
name: EILERT

meaning: Perhaps means "white brow" from Welsh ael "brow" and gwen "white, fair, blessed".
name: EILWEN

meaning: Probably from the Latin name Ennianus, a derivative of Ennius (see ENNIO). It is also a modern Welsh word meaning "anvil". This was the name of a 5th-century Welsh king who is considered a saint in some Christian traditions.
name: EINION

meaning: Means "white snow" from the Welsh elements eira "snow" and gwen "white, blessed".
name: EIRWEN

meaning: Means "kernel, grain" in Irish. This was the name of a 5th-century Irish saint, sister of Saint Fidelma and follower of Saint Patrick.
name: EITHNE

meaning: Means "one, first" in Indonesian, ultimately from Sanskrit एक (eka).
name: EKA  (1)

meaning: Bulgarian and Macedonian form of KATHERINE, and a variant Russian transcription of YEKATERINA.
name: EKATERINA

meaning: Means "all praise to God" in Igbo.
name: EKENEDILICHUKWU

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements ag "edge" and hard "brave, hardy".
name: EKKEHARD

meaning: Means "he says, he does" in Igbo.
name: EKWUEME

meaning: Possibly means either "hidden" or "eternity" in Hebrew. This was the name of several characters in the Old Testament, including a son of Shem who was the ancestor of the Elamite peoples.
name: ELAM

meaning: Possibly a Spanish variant form of ALBA  (3).
name: ELBA

meaning: From Turkic el "country, society" and Persian در (dar) "possessor".
name: ELDAR

meaning: From a surname which was from a place name meaning "Ella's hill" in Old English.
name: ELDON

meaning: Short form of ELEANOR. This was also the name of an ancient Italian town (modern Velia) which is well known for being the home of the philosopher Parmenides and his student Zeno of Elea, who was famous for his paradoxes.
name: ELEA

meaning: From the Hebrew name אֶלְעָזָר ('El'azar) meaning "my God has helped". In the Old Testament this is the name of one of the sons of Aaron.
name: ELEAZAR

meaning: Welsh form of HELEN. This was the name of a 4th-century Welsh saint. It also appears in the Mabinogion, a collection of tales from Welsh myth, belonging to a woman who built the roads in Wales.
name: ELEN

meaning: Georgian and Sardinian form of HELEN.
name: ELENE

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and beorht "bright". This was the name of an 8th-century king of Northumbria and three kings of Kent.
name: EADBERHT

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and burg "fortress".
name: EADBURG

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements eald "old" and gyð "battle".
name: EALDGYÐ

meaning: From the Old English elements eald "old" and wine "friend". This name was rarely used after the Norman conquest.
name: EALDWINE

meaning: Derived from the Old English element ealh "temple" combined with stan "stone".
name: EALHSTAN

meaning: Variant of ÉAMONN. This name was borne by American-born Irish president Éamon de Valera (1882-1975), whose birth name was Edward.
name: ÉAMON

meaning: Derived from the Old English element eard "land" combined with wulf "wolf".
name: EARDWULF

meaning: Variant of ERNEST influenced by the spelling of the English word earnest.
name: EARNEST

meaning: Combination of the English word earth with the feminine name suffix a. It has been used in honour of African-American philanthropist Eartha M. M. White (1876-1974). Another famous bearer was American singer and actress Eartha Kitt (1927-2008).
name: EARTHA

meaning: From the Old English name Æbbe, meaning unknown, perhaps a contracted form of a longer name. Saint Ebba was a 7th-century daughter of king Æthelfrith of Bernicia and the founder of monasteries in Scotland. Another saint Ebba was a 9th-century abbess and martyr who mutilated her own face so that she would not be raped by the invading Danes.
name: EBBA  (2)

meaning: Means "stone of help" in Hebrew. This was the name of a monument erected by Samuel in the Old Testament. Charles Dickens used it for the miserly character Ebenezer Scrooge in his novel 'A Christmas Carol' (1843).
name: EBENEZER

meaning: From the English word ebony for the black wood which comes from the ebony tree. It is ultimately from the Egyptian word hbnj. In America this name is most often used by black parents.
name: EBONY

meaning: Means "paper marbling" in Turkish. Paper marbling is the art of creating colourful patterns on paper.
name: EBRU

meaning: Means "echo" from the word for the repeating reflected sound, which derives from Greek ηχη (eche) "sound". In Greek mythology Echo was a nymph given a speech impediment by Hera, so that she could only repeat what others said. She fell in love with Narcissus, but her love was not returned, and she pined away until nothing remained of her except her voice.
name: ECHO

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly from an Arabic word meaning "reward".
name: ECRİN

meaning: Diminutive of EDWARD, EDMUND, and other names beginning with Ed.
name: EDDIE

meaning: Means "flock" in Hebrew. This was the name of a son of Beriah in the Old Testament.
name: EDER  (1)

meaning: Spanish and Italian form of EDGAR.
name: EDGARDO

meaning: From an English surname which meant either "son of EDA  (2)" or "son of ADAM". A famous bearer of the surname was the inventor Thomas Edison (1847-1931).
name: EDISON

meaning: French form of EDMUND. A notable bearer was the English astronomer Edmond Halley (1656-1742), for whom Halley's comet is named.
name: EDMOND

meaning: From the Old English elements ead "wealth, fortune" and mund "protection". This was the name of two Anglo-Saxon kings of England. It was also borne by two saints, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia who, according to tradition, was shot to death with arrows after refusing to divide his Christian kingdom with an invading pagan Danish leader. This Old English name remained in use after the Norman conquest (even being used by king Henry III for one of his sons), though it became less common after the 15th century.... [more]
name: EDMUND

meaning: Means "red" in Hebrew. According to the Old Testament, Esau was given this name because he traded his birthright for a helping of red broth. The bible goes on to tell that Esau was the founder of the ancient nation of Edom, located to the south of the kingdom of Judah.
name: EDOM

meaning: Variant of ETZEL notably borne by Edsel Ford (1893-1943), the son of the American industrialist Henry Ford.
name: EDSEL
EDVARD
origin: [Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Finnish, Slovene, Czech, Armenian]

meaning: Scandinavian, Finnish, Estonian and Hungarian form of EDWIN.
name: EDVIN

meaning: Finnish form of ERIC. A famous bearer was the architect Eero Saarinen (1910-1961).
name: EERO

meaning: Short form of EFEMENA or other names containing efe "wealth".
name: EFE  (2)

meaning: Means "bright edge" from the Old English elements ecg "edge of a sword" and beorht "bright". This was the name of kings of Kent and Wessex as well as two English saints. The name was rarely used after the Norman conquest but was revived in the 19th century.
name: EGBERT

meaning: From the Old Norse name Egill, a diminutive of names that began with the element agi "awe, terror". This was the name of a semi-legendary Icelandic warrior.
name: EGIL

meaning: Old Norse and Icelandic form of EGIL.
name: EGILL

meaning: From the English word for the flower also known as sweetbrier. It was first used as a given name (in the form Eglentyne) in Geoffrey Chaucer's 14th-century story 'The Prioress's Tale'.
name: EGLANTINE

meaning: Meaning unknown. According to Irish legend this name belonged to two of the sons of Míl, Éibhear Dunn and Éibhear Finn, the first of the Gaels to conquer Ireland.
name: ÉIBHEAR

meaning: Meaning unknown. This was an old Welsh name that was revived in the 19th century.
name: EIFION

meaning: Possibly from the Finnish happy exclamation eijaa.
name: EIJA

meaning: Anglicized form of EIBHLÍN. It is also sometimes considered an Irish form of HELEN. It first became popular in the English-speaking world outside of Ireland near the end of the 19th century.
name: EILEEN

meaning: Diminutive of EILIONOIR, sometimes taken to be a Gaelic form of HELEN.
name: EILIDH

meaning: Irish Gaelic form of ELIZABETH (or sometimes of ALICE).
name: EILÍS

meaning: Possibly means "swift, prompt" in Irish Gaelic.
name: ÉIMHÍN

meaning: From the Old Norse name Einarr, derived from the elements ein "one, alone" and arr "warrior". This name shares the same roots as einherjar, the word for the slain warriors in Valhalla.
name: EINAR

meaning: Derived from the Old Norse name Eindriði, possibly from the elements ein "one, alone" and ríða "to ride".
name: EINDRIDE

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly a Finnish form of a Scandinavian name.
name: EINO

meaning: Means "mercy" in Old Norse. This was the name of a Norse goddess of healing and medicine.
name: EIR

meaning: From Éireann, the genitive case of Gaelic Éire, meaning "Ireland". It is commonly Anglicized as Erin.
name: EIREANN

meaning: Short form of EJIROGHENE or other names containing ejiro "praise".
name: EJIRO

meaning: From a Semitic word meaning "god", perhaps originally derived from a root meaning "power". This was the name of the chief Semitic god, the father of the gods and mankind. In some cases it was used as a title and applied to other gods of the pantheon. It was used by the Hebrews to refer to Yahweh.
name: EL

meaning: Ancient Greek name meaning "newly acquired". This was the name of a 1st-century Greek stoic philosopher.
name: EPIKTETOS

meaning: Means "appearing, manifesting" in Greek. This was an epithet of two 2nd-century BC Hellenistic rulers: the Seleucid king Antiochus IV and the Ptolemaic king Ptolemy V.
name: EPIPHANES

meaning: Derived from Gaulish epos meaning "horse". This was the name of the Celtic goddess of horses.
name: EPONA

meaning: Means "watchful, vigilant" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament he is a grandson of Ephraim.
name: ERAN

meaning: Variant of HARTMANN. It can also be interpreted as meaning "earth man" from German Erde "earth", and thus was sometimes used as a translation of Adam.
name: ERDMANN

meaning: Georgian form of Herakleios (see HERACLIUS). This name was borne by two Georgian kings of the Bagrationi dynasty.
name: EREKLE

meaning: Means "lady of the great earth" in Sumerian. In Sumerian and Babylonian mythology she was the violent goddess of death and the underworld.
name: ERESHKIGAL

meaning: Derived from the Germanic element era "honour, respect" or hari "army" combined with hard "brave, hardy". In some cases it may be a variant of EBERHARD.
name: ERHARD

meaning: German form of ERIC. The German novelist Erich Maria Remarque (1898-1970) was the author of 'All Quiet on the Western Front'.
name: ERICH

meaning: Scandinavian form of ERIC. This was the name of kings of Sweden, Denmark and Norway. King Erik IX of Sweden (12th century) is the patron saint of that country.
name: ERIK
origin: [Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Finnish, Czech, Slovak, Slovene, Croatian, Hungarian, German, Dutch, English]

meaning: Means "strife" in Greek. In Greek mythology Eris was the goddess of discord. She was the sister and companion of Ares.
name: ERIS

meaning: Variant of IRMA. It began to be used in the English-speaking world in the 19th century, along with Irma.
name: ERMA

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements ermen "whole, universal" and linde "soft, tender".
name: ERMELINDA

meaning: From the Germanic elements ermen "whole, universal" and ric "power". Ermenrich (also often called Ermanaric) was a 4th-century Gothic king.
name: ERMENRICH

meaning: English form of ERMENDRUD. It was occasionally used until the 19th century.
name: ERMINTRUDE

meaning: Means "brisk, vigourous, hale" in Old Norse. This was the name of the wife of Jarl in Norse legend.
name: ERNA  (2)

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of ERNEST.
name: ERNESTO

meaning: German, Dutch and Scandinavian form of ERNEST.
name: ERNST

meaning: Hungarian and Croatian form of ERWIN.
name: ERVIN

meaning: Breton form of IVO  (1) or YVES.
name: ERWAN

meaning: Derived from the Germanic name Hariwini, composed of the elements hari "army" and win "friend". It may have merged somewhat with the Germanic name EBURWIN. A notable bearer was Erwin Schrodinger (1887-1961), an Austrian physicist who made contributions to quantum theory.
name: ERWIN

meaning: Hungarian form of ELIZABETH. This is the native name of Saint Elizabeth of Hungary. It was also borne by the infamous Erzsébet Báthory, a 16th-century countess and murderer.
name: ERZSÉBET

meaning: From the Hebrew name עֵשָׂו ('Esaw) which possibly meant "hairy". In the Old Testament Esau is the elder of the twin sons of Isaac and Rebecca. Once when he was very hungry he sold his birthright to his twin Jacob for a bowl of stew. Later Jacob disguised himself as Esau and received the elder son's blessing from the blind Isaac. Esau was the ancestor of the Edomites.
name: ESAU

meaning: Greek form of EZRA. This spelling is used in parts of the Old Testament Apocrypha.
name: ESDRAS

meaning: Means "mercy" in Basque. It is a Basque equivalent of Mercedes.
name: ESKARNE

meaning: Persian form of ISHMAEL. It is also a variant transcription of Arabic ISMA'IL.
name: ESMAIL

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements east "grace" and mund "protection". This Old English name was rarely used after the Norman conquest. It was occasionally revived in the 19th century.
name: ESMOND

meaning: Spanish form of the Late Latin name Sperantia which was derived from sperare "to hope".
name: ESPERANZA

meaning: Possibly a Turkish form of ASRA.
name: ESRA

meaning: From the English word essence which means either "odour, scent" or else "fundamental quality". Ultimately it derives from Latin esse "to be".
name: ESSENCE

meaning: Portuguese and Spanish form of ESTELLE.
name: ESTELA

meaning: From an Old French name which was derived from Latin stella, meaning "star". It was rare in the English-speaking world in the Middle Ages, but it was revived in the 19th century, perhaps due to the character Estella Havisham in Charles Dickens' novel 'Great Expectations' (1860).
name: ESTELLE
ESTER
origin: [Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, Czech, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Icelandic, Finnish]

meaning: Spanish form of STELLA  (1), coinciding with the Spanish word meaning "star".
name: ESTRELLA

meaning: Possibly derived from Old Irish ét "jealousy". In Irish mythology she was a sun and horse goddess who was the lover of Midir.
name: ÉTAÍN

meaning: Probably a Hungarian form of ETZEL.
name: ETELE

meaning: From the Hebrew name אֵיתָן ('Eitan) meaning "solid, enduring, firm". In the Old Testament this name is borne by a few minor characters, including the wise man Ethan the Ezrahite, supposedly the author of Psalm 89.... [more]
name: ETHAN

meaning: Middle English form of ÆÐELBERHT. The name was very rare after the Norman conquest, but it was revived briefly in the 19th century.
name: ETHELBERT

meaning: Middle English form of ÆÐELRÆD. The name was very rare after the Norman conquest, but it was revived briefly in the 19th century.
name: ETHELRED

meaning: Short form of HENRIETTA and other names that end with etta. A famous bearer was the American singer Etta James (1938-2012), who took her stage name from her real given name Jamesetta.
name: ETTA

meaning: Form of Chawwah (see EVE) used in the Greek translation of Old Testament. Chawwah is also translated as Zoe in the Greek Old Testament.
name: EUA

meaning: Derived from Greek ευανθης (euanthes) meaning "blooming, flowery", a derivative of ευ (eu) "good" and ανθος (anthos) "flower". According to some sources, this was the name of the mother of the three Graces or Χαριτες (Charites) in Greek mythology.
name: EUANTHE

meaning: From the Greek name Ευκλειδης (Eukleides), derived from Greek ευ (eu) "good" and κλεος (kleos) "glory" with the patronymic suffix ιδης (ides). This was the name of a 3rd-century BC Greek mathematician from Alexandria who made numerous contributions to geometry.
name: EUCLID

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Ευδοκια (Eudokia), derived from the word ευδοκεω (eudokeo) meaning "to be well pleased, to be satisfied", itself derived from ευ (eu) "good" and δοκεω (dokeo) "to think, to imagine, to suppose".
name: EUDOCIA

meaning: Means "good gift" in Greek, from the elements ευ (eu) "good" and δωρον (doron) "gift". This was the name of a nymph, one of the Hyades, in Greek mythology.
name: EUDORA

meaning: Ancient Greek feminine form of EUGENE.
name: EUGENEIA

meaning: Feminine form of Eugenius (see EUGENE). It was borne by a semi-legendary 3rd-century saint who escaped persecution by disguising herself as a man. The name was occasionally found in England during the Middle Ages, but it was not regularly used until the 19th century.
name: EUGENIA
origin: [Italian, Spanish, Romanian, Polish, English, Ancient Greek (Latinized)]

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of Eugenius (see EUGENE).
name: EUGENIO

meaning: From Sino-Korean 恩 (eun) meaning "kindness, mercy, charity" or 銀 (eun) meaning "silver, money", as well as other hanja characters which are pronounced in the same way. It usually occurs in combination with another character, though it is sometimes used as a stand-alone name.
name: EUN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 恩 (eun) meaning "kindness, mercy, charity" or 慇 (eun) meaning "careful, anxious, attentive" combined with 廷 (jeong) meaning "court" or 婷 (jeong) meaning "pretty, graceful". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: EUN-JEONG

meaning: From Sino-Korean 恩 (eun) meaning "kindness, mercy, charity" and 英 (yeong) meaning "flower, petal, brave, hero". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: EUN-YEONG

meaning: Means "to use words of good omen" from Greek  () "good" and φημι (phemi) "to speak, to declare". Saint Euphemia was an early martyr from Chalcedon.
name: EUPHEMIA

meaning: Derived from Greek ευφραινω (euphraino) meaning "to delight". This was the name of a 4th-century BC Athenian artist.
name: EUPHRANOR

meaning: From a Greek word meaning "good conduct", derived from ευ (eu) "good" and πραξις (praxis) "action, exercise".
name: EUPRAXIA

meaning: Latinized form of Greek Ευρωπη (Europe), which meant "wide face" from ευρυς (eurys) "wide" and ωψ (ops) "face, eye". In Greek mythology Europa was a Phoenician princess who was abducted and taken to Crete by Zeus in the guise of a bull. She became the first queen of Crete, and later fathered Minos by Zeus. The continent of Europe is named for her. This is also the name of a moon of Jupiter.
name: EUROPA

meaning: Derived from Welsh aur "gold" and gwen "white, fair, blessed".
name: EURWEN

meaning: From the Hebrew name חֲנוֹך (Chanokh) meaning "dedicated". In Genesis in the Old Testament this is the name of both the son of Cain and the father of Methuselah, who was the supposed author of the apocryphal Books of Enoch.
name: ENOCH

meaning: Meaning unknown. This name first appeared in the late 19th century.
name: ENOLA

meaning: Means "human being" in Hebrew. He was a son of Seth and a grandson of Adam in the genealogies in Genesis in the Old Testament.
name: ENOSH

meaning: Meaning unknown. She was a blood-thirsty Greek war goddess and a companion of Ares.
name: ENYO

meaning: Derived from the Old English elements eofor "boar" and hild "battle". This name was rarely used after the Norman conquest.
name: EOFORHILD

meaning: Means "horse joy" in Old English. This name was invented by J. R. R. Tolkien who used Old English to represent the Rohirric language. In his novel 'The Lord of the Rings' (1954) Eowyn is the niece of King Theoden of Rohan. She slays the Lord of the Nazgul in the Battle of the Pelennor Fields.
name: ÉOWYN

meaning: Means "lovely, charming", derived from Greek επι (epi) "on" combined with the name of the Greek love goddess APHRODITE.
name: EPAPHRODITOS

meaning: From the Hebrew name אֶפְרָיִם ('Efrayim) which meant "fruitful". In the Old Testament Ephraim is a son of Joseph and Asenath and the founder of one of the twelve tribes of Israel.
name: EPHRAIM

meaning: From the Latin name Epiphanius, which was from the Greek name Επιφανιος (Epiphanios), itself derived from the Greek word επιφανεια (epiphaneia) meaning "appearance, manifestation". This name was borne by a few early saints. It is associated with the event known in English as the Epiphany (Spanish Epifanía, Italian Epifania, Latin Epiphania), the coming of the three Magi to visit the infant Jesus.
name: EPIFANIO

meaning: Derived from Greek επιμηθεια (epimetheia) meaning "hindsight, hindthought". In Greek mythology he was a Titan, the brother of the god of forethought Prometheus.
name: EPIMETHEUS

meaning: From the name of the Christian festival (January 6) which commemorates the visit of the Magi to the infant Jesus. It is also an English word meaning "sudden appearance" or "sudden perception", ultimately deriving from Greek επιφανεια (epiphaneia) "manifestation".
name: EPIPHANY

meaning: Meaning unknown. Victor Hugo used this name in his novel 'Les Misérables' (1862) for a daughter of the Thénardiers. Her mother got her name from a romance novel.
name: EPONINE

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of ERASMUS.
name: ERASMO

meaning: Derived from Greek ερασμιος (erasmios) meaning "beloved". Saint Erasmus, also known as Saint Elmo, was a 4th-century martyr who is the patron saint of sailors. Erasmus was also the name of a Dutch scholar of the Renaissance period.
name: ERASMUS

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Εραστος (Erastos) meaning "beloved". This was the name of an assistant of Paul mentioned in Acts and two epistles in the New Testament.
name: ERASTUS

meaning: Means "lovely" in Greek. In Greek mythology she was one of the nine Muses, the muse of lyric poetry.
name: ERATO

meaning: From Turkish er "brave man" and can "soul, life".
name: ERCAN

meaning: From Turkish er "brave man" and doğan "falcon".
name: ERDOĞAN

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek Ερεβος (Erebos) which means "nether darkness". Erebus was the personification of the primordial darkness in Greek mythology.
name: EREBUS

meaning: From Turkish er "brave man" and han, which is from the title khan meaning "leader".
name: ERHAN

meaning: From the Old Norse name Eiríkr, derived from the elements ei "ever, always" and ríkr "ruler". A notable bearer was Eiríkr inn Rauda (Eric the Red in English), a 10th-century navigator and explorer who discovered Greenland. This was also the name of several early kings of Sweden, Denmark and Norway.... [more]
name: ERIC

meaning: Feminine form of ERIC. It was first used in the 18th century. It also coincides with the Latin word for "heather".
name: ERICA

meaning: Feminine form of ERIK. It also coincides with the word for "heather" in some languages.
name: ERIKA
origin: [Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Finnish, German, Hungarian, Czech, Slovene, Croatian, English, Italian]
