meaning: From Chinese 华 (huá) meaning "splendid, illustrious, Chinese" or 花 (huā) meaning "flower, blossom" (which is usually only feminine). Other Chinese characters can form this name as well.
name: HUA

meaning: From Chinese 煌 (huáng) meaning "bright, shining, luminous" (which is usually only masculine) or 凰 (huáng) meaning "phoenix" (usually only feminine). Other Chinese characters are also possible.
name: HUANG

meaning: From Sino-Vietnamese 慧 (huệ) meaning "bright, intelligent" or 蕙 (huệ) meaning "orchid".
name: HUỆ

meaning: From the Germanic element hug, meaning "heart, mind, spirit". It was common among Frankish and French nobility, being borne by Hugh Capet, a 10th-century king of France who founded the Capetian dynasty. The Normans brought the name to England and it became common there, even more so after the time of the 12th-century bishop Saint Hugh of Lincoln, who was known for his charity. This was also the name of kings of Cyprus and the crusader kingdom of Jerusalem. The name is used in Ireland and Scotland as the Anglicized form of Aodh and Ùisdean.
name: HUGH

meaning: Latinized form of HUGH. As a surname it has belonged to the French author Victor Hugo (1802-1885), the writer of 'The Hunchback of Notre Dame' and 'Les Misérables'.
name: HUGO
origin: [Spanish, Portuguese, Catalan, English, Dutch, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Ancient Germanic (Latinized)]

meaning: From Chinese 慧 (huì) meaning "intelligent, wise" (which is usually only feminine), 辉 (huī) meaning "brightness", besides other characters which are pronounced similarly.
name: HUI

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements hulda "merciful, graceful" and ric "power, rule". It has long been confused with the Germanic name Ulrich.
name: HULDERIC

meaning: Means "bright warrior", derived from the Germanic elements hun "warrior, bear cub" and beraht "bright". The Normans introduced this name to England, though it has always been uncommon there. It was borne by two kings of Italy (called Umberto in Italian), who ruled in the 19th and 20th centuries.
name: HUMBERT

meaning: Derived from the ethnic term Hun, which refers to the nomadic people from Central Asia who expanded into Europe in the 4th century. The word Hun is from Latin Hunnus, which is possibly of Turkic origin.
name: HUNOR

meaning: Means "linen weaver" in Hebrew. This was the name of the father of Abihail in the Old Testament.
name: HURI

meaning: Germanic name, possibly a derivative of hari "army", era "honour", or erla "noble" (or their Old Norse cognates). This was the name of the mother of William the Conqueror, who, according to tradition, was a commoner.
name: HERLEVA

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of a Visigothic name which meant "complete sacrifice" from the Germanic elements ermen "whole, entire" and gild "sacrifice, value". It was borne by a 6th-century saint, the son of Liuvigild the Visigothic king of Hispania.
name: HERMENEGILDO

meaning: Feminine form of HERMES. Shakespeare used this name in his comedy 'A Midsummer Night's Dream' (1595).
name: HERMIA

meaning: Roman name which was possibly of unknown Etruscan origin, but could also be derived from the name of the god HERMES. In Roman legend this was the name of a companion of Aeneas.
name: HERMINIUS

meaning: Means "born of Hermes" from the name of the messenger god HERMES combined with Greek γενης (genes) "born".
name: HERMOGENES

meaning: Means "the people of Hermes" from the name of the messenger god HERMES combined with Greek λαος (laos) "people".
name: HERMOLAOS

meaning: Medieval Spanish form of FERDINAND. A famous bearer of this name was Hernando Cortés (1485-1547), a Spanish conquistador.
name: HERNANDO

meaning: Diminutive of the Greek name Heroides (see HEROD). This name is mentioned briefly in Paul's epistle to the Romans in the New Testament.
name: HERODION
origin: [Biblical, Biblical Latin, Biblical Greek, Ancient Greek]

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name ‘Ηροδοτος (Herodotos), derived from ‘ηρως (heros) "hero, warrior" and δοτος (dotos) "given, granted". Herodotus was a Greek historian of the 5th century BC who wrote about Persian and the Persian Wars. He is known as the Father of History.
name: HERODOTUS

meaning: Medieval English form of HENRY. Unlike Harry, this form is no longer used.
name: HERRY

meaning: Means "deer" in Yiddish. The deer is particularly associated with the tribe of Naphtali (see Genesis 49:21).
name: HERSH

meaning: Meaning unknown. In Roman legend this was the name of a Sabine woman who became the wife of Romulus.
name: HERSILIA

meaning: Form of NERTHUS. The spelling change from N to H resulted from a misreading of Tacitus's text.
name: HERTHA

meaning: From the Greek name ‘Ησιοδος (Hesiodos), which probably means "to throw song" from ‘ιημι (hiemi) "to throw, to speak" and ωιδη (oide) "song, ode". This was the name of an 8th-century BC Greek poet.
name: HESIOD

meaning: Means "evening" in Greek. This was the name of the personification of the Evening Star (the planet Venus) in Greek mythology.
name: HESPEROS

meaning: Derived from Greek ‘εστια (hestia) "hearth, fireside". In Greek mythology Hestia was the goddess of the hearth and domestic activity.
name: HESTIA

meaning: From the Iroquoian name Haio-went-ha meaning "he who combs". This was the name of a 16th-century Mohawk leader who founded the Iroquois Confederacy. He was later the subject of a fictionalized 1855 poem by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow.
name: HIAWATHA

meaning: Frisian short form of names containing the Germanic element hild meaning "battle".
name: HIDDE

meaning: From Japanese 秀 (hide) meaning "excellent, outstanding" or 英 (hide) meaning "excellent, fine" combined with 樹 (ki) meaning "tree". Other kanji combinations can also form this name.
name: HIDEKI

meaning: Latin form of JEROME used in Germany and the Netherlands. Hieronymus Bosch was a 15th-century Dutch painter known for his depictions of the torments of hell.
name: HIERONYMUS

meaning: From Japanese 光 (hikari) meaning "light". Other kanji can also form this name. It is often written ひかり using the hiragana writing system.
name: HIKARI

meaning: Roman name which was derived from Latin hilaris meaning "cheerful". Alternatively, it could be derived from the Greek name ‘Ιλαρος (Hilaros) also meaning "cheerful" (the Greek word ‘ιλαρος was the source of the Latin word hilaris). Saint Hilarius was a 4th-century theologian and bishop of Poitiers. This was also the name of a 5th-century pope.
name: HILARIUS

meaning: Originally a short form of names containing the Germanic element hild "battle". The short form was used for both Old English and continental Germanic names. Saint Hilda of Whitby was a 7th-century English saint and abbess. The name became rare in England during the later Middle Ages, but was revived in the 19th century.
name: HILDA
origin: [English, German, Dutch, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Spanish, Anglo-Saxon (Latinized), Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Means "bright battle" from the Germanic elements hild "battle" and beraht "bright".
name: HILDEBERT

meaning: Old Norse cognate of HILDA. In Norse legend this was the name of a valkyrie.
name: HILDR

meaning: Possibly from the Old English masculine name Hildræd, which was composed of the elements hild "battle" and ræd "counsel". This name was revived in the late 19th century, probably because of its similarity to the popular names Hilda and Mildred.
name: HILDRED

meaning: Variant of HILARY. A famous bearer of the surname was Sir Edmund Hillary (1919-2008), the first man to climb Mount Everest.
name: HILLARY

meaning: Swedish and Finnish form of HEILWIG.
name: HILLEVI

meaning: Means "strength in battle", derived from the Germanic elements hild "battle" and thrud "strength".
name: HILTRUD

meaning: From Japanese 陽 (hi) meaning "light, sun, male" or 日 (hi) meaning "sun, day" combined with 菜 (na) meaning "vegetables, greens". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: HINA

meaning: Possibly means "group of camels" in Arabic. Hind bint Abi Umayyah, also known as Umm Salama, was one of the wives of the Prophet Muhammad. This is also the Arabic name for the country of India.
name: HIND

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of HIPPOLYTOS.
name: HIPÓLITO

meaning: Feminine form of HIPPOLYTOS. In Greek legend Hippolyte was the daughter of Ares, and the queen of the Amazons. She was killed by Herakles in order to obtain her magic girdle.
name: HIPPOLYTE  (1)

meaning: Means "freer of horses" from Greek ‘ιππος (hippos) "horse" and λυω (luo) "to loosen". In Greek legend he was the son of Theseus who was tragically loved by his stepmother Phaedra. This was also the name of a 3rd-century theologian, saint and martyr.
name: HIPPOLYTOS

meaning: From Japanese 拓 (hiraku) meaning "expand, open, support". Other kanji can also form this name.
name: HIRAKU

meaning: From Japanese 大 (hiro) meaning "big, great" and 輝 (ki) meaning "brightness" or 樹 (ki) meaning "tree". Other kanji combinations are also possible.
name: HIROKI

meaning: From Japanese 寛 (hiroshi) meaning "tolerant, generous", 浩 (hiroshi) meaning "prosperous", or other kanji and kanji combinations which are read the same way.
name: HIROSHI

meaning: Means "trinity" in Basque, derived from hiru meaning "three".
name: HIRUNE

meaning: Means "generous" in Arabic, ultimately from hashama "to crush". The meaning derives from the traditional Arab act of crushing bread into crumbs in order to share it. This was the name of an 8th-century caliph of the Umayyad dynasty in Spain.
name: HISHAM

meaning: From the Old Norse name Hjálmarr meaning "helmeted warrior" from the element hjalmr "helmet" combined with arr "warrior".
name: HJALMAR

meaning: Means "sword goddess", derived from Old Norse hjörr "sword" and dís "goddess".
name: HJÖRDÍS

meaning: Modern Danish and Norwegian form of HJÖRDÍS.
name: HJØRDIS

meaning: Means "majesty of YAHWEH" in Hebrew. This is the name of a wife of Ezra in the Old Testament.
name: HODIAH

meaning: Limburgish form of HUBERT. Its spelling has been influenced by the French pronunciation of Hubert.
name: HOEBAER

meaning: Means "cornstalk" in Shawnee. This was the name of an 18th-century Shawnee chief.
name: HOKOLESQUA

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "deep valley" in Old English. This is the name of the main character in J. D. Salinger's novel 'The Catcher in the Rye' (1951), Holden Caufield.
name: HOLDEN

meaning: From the English word for the holly tree, ultimately derived from Old English holen.
name: HOLLY

meaning: From the Greek name ‘Ομηρος (Homeros), derived from ‘ομηρος (homeros) meaning "hostage, pledge". Homer was the Greek epic poet who wrote the 'Iliad', about the Trojan War, and the 'Odyssey', about Odysseus's journey home after the war. There is some debate about when he lived, or if he was even a real person, though most scholars place him in the 8th century BC. In the modern era, Homer has been used as a given name in the English-speaking world (chiefly in America) since the 18th century. This name is borne by the cartoon father on the television series 'The Simpsons'.
name: HOMER

meaning: Simply from the English word honey, ultimately from Old English hunig. This was originally a nickname for a sweet person.
name: HONEY

meaning: From Chinese 虹 (hóng) meaning "rainbow", 弘 (hóng) meaning "enlarge, expand, great" (which is usually only masculine) or 鸿 (hóng) meaning "wild swan, great, vast" (also usually only masculine). Other characters can also form this name.
name: HONG

meaning: Variant of HONOUR, using the American spelling.
name: HONOR

meaning: French form of HONORATUS. It is also sometimes used as a French form of HONORIUS.
name: HONORÉ

meaning: Late Latin name which was a derivative of HONORIUS.
name: HONORINUS

meaning: From the English word honour, which is of Latin origin. This was one of the virtue names adopted by the Puritans in the 17th century. It can also be viewed as a form of HONORIA or HONORATA, which are ultimately derived from the same source.
name: HONOUR

meaning: From the English word hope, ultimately from Old English hopian. This name was first used by the Puritans in the 17th century.
name: HOPE

meaning: English and French form of HORATIUS, and the name by which the Roman poet Quintus Horatius Flaccus is commonly known those languages. In the modern era it has been used as a given name since the Renaissance, in honour of the poet.
name: HORACE

meaning: Variant of HORATIUS. It was borne by the British admiral Horatio Nelson (1758-1805), famous for his defeat of Napoleon's forces in the Battle of Trafalgar, in which he was himself killed. Since his time the name has been occasionally used in his honour.
name: HORATIO

meaning: Roman family name which was possibly derived from Latin hora "hour, time, season", though the name may actually be of Etruscan origin. A famous bearer was Quintus Horatius Flaccus, a Roman lyric poet of the 1st century BC who is better known as Horace in the English-speaking world.
name: HORATIUS

meaning: Means "wood, thicket" in German. Alternatively, it may derive from the Germanic element hros or hors meaning "horse".
name: HORST

meaning: Feminine form of the Roman family name Hortensius, possibly derived from Latin hortus "garden".
name: HORTENSIA

meaning: Latinized form of ‘Ωρος (Horos), the Greek form of Egyptian Hrw (reconstructed as Heru) possibly meaning "falcon" or "high". In Egyptian mythology Horus was the god of light, often depicted as a man with the head of a falcon. The son Osiris and Isis, he avenged his father's murder by killing Seth.
name: HORUS

meaning: Variant transcription of Hoshe'a (see HOSHEA). Hosea is one of the twelve minor prophets of the Old Testament, the author of the Book of Hosea. Written in the northern kingdom, it draws parallels between his relationship with his unfaithful wife and the relationship between God and his people.
name: HOSEA

meaning: From Japanese 星 (hoshi) meaning "star" or other kanji with the same pronunciation.
name: HOSHI

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from Middle English hoit "stick", originally a nickname for a thin person.
name: HOYT

meaning: Bulgarian and Macedonian short form of CHRISTOPHER.
name: HRISTO

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements hrod "fame" and heid "kind, sort, type" (see ROSE).
name: HRODOHAIDIS

meaning: Old English cognate of Hrodger (see ROGER). The name became unused after the Normans introduced Hrodger after their invasion. In the Old English poem 'Beowulf' this is the name of the Danish king.
name: HROÐGAR

meaning: Old Norse cognate of Hrodger (see ROGER).
name: HRÓÐGEIRR

meaning: Old English cognate of Hrodulf (see RUDOLF). This name appears in 'Beowulf' belonging to the nephew of Hroðgar.
name: HROÐULF

meaning: From Chinese 欢 (huān) meaning "happy, pleased", as well as other characters pronounced in a similar way.
name: HUAN

meaning: Means "bright heart", derived from the Germanic elements hug "heart, mind" and beraht "bright". Saint Hubert was an 8th-century bishop of Maastricht who is considered the patron saint of hunters. The Normans brought the name to England, where it replaced an Old English cognate Hygebeorht. It died out during the Middle Ages but was revived in the 19th century.
name: HUBERT
origin: [English, German, Dutch, French, Polish, Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Medieval diminutive of HUGH or possibly RICHARD.
name: HUDDE

meaning: From an English surname which meant "son of HUDDE". A famous bearer of the surname was the English explorer Henry Hudson (1570-1611).
name: HUDSON

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements hug "heart, mind" and hard "brave, hardy".
name: HUGHARD

meaning: Old Norse name derived from hugr "heart, mind, spirit" and leikr "play".
name: HUGLEIKR

meaning: Means "southern hummingbird" or "left-handed hummingbird" in Nahuatl. In Aztec mythology he was the god of the sun and war. He was a patron deity of the city of Tenochtitlan (at the site of modern Mexico City).
name: HUITZILOPOCHTLI

meaning: Derived from Old Norse hulda meaning "hiding, secrecy". This was the name of a sorceress in Norse mythology. As a modern name, it can also derive from archaic Swedish huld meaning "sweet, lovable".
name: HULDA  (1)
origin: [Icelandic, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, German, Norse Mythology]

meaning: Means "weasel, mole" in Hebrew. This name appears in the Old Testament belonging to a prophetess.
name: HULDAH

meaning: Means "red" in Arabic. This was a name given by the Prophet Muhammad to his wife Aisha.
name: HUMAYRA

meaning: Means "peaceful warrior" from the Germanic elements hun "warrior, bear cub" and frid "peace". The Normans introduced this name to England, where it replaced the Old English cognate Hunfrith, and it was regularly used through the Middle Ages. A famous bearer was the American actor Humphrey Bogart (1899-1957), who starred in 'The Maltese Falcon' and 'Casablanca'.
name: HUMPHREY

meaning: From an occupational English surname for a hunter, derived from Old English hunta. A famous bearer was the eccentric American journalist Hunter S. Thompson (1937-2005).
name: HUNTER

meaning: Means "sword" in Arabic, a derivative of the verb حسم (hasama) meaning "to sever, to finish, to decide".
name: HUSAM

meaning: Derived from Arabic حسن (husn) meaning "beauty, excellence, goodness".
name: HUSNI

meaning: From Sino-Korean 煥 (hwan) meaning "shining, brilliant, lustrous" or other characters which are pronounced similarly. It usually occurs in combination with another character.
name: HWAN

meaning: From the name of the flower (or the precious stone which also bears this name), ultimately from Greek ‘υακινθος (hyakinthos).
name: HYACINTH  (2)

meaning: French masculine and feminine form of HYACINTHUS.
name: HYACINTHE

meaning: From Sino-Korean 慧 (hye) meaning "bright, intelligent" or 惠 (hye) meaning "favour, benefit" combined with 珍 (jin) meaning "precious, rare". This name can be formed by a variety of other hanja character combinations as well.
name: HYE-JIN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 賢 (hyeon) meaning "virtuous, worthy, able" or 炫 (hyeon) meaning "shine, glitter" combined with 廷 (jeong) meaning "court" or 貞 (jeong) meaning "virtuous, chaste, loyal". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: HYEON-JEONG

meaning: From Sino-Korean 賢 (hyeon) meaning "virtuous, worthy, able" or 顯 (hyeon) meaning "manifest, clear" combined with 祐 (u) meaning "divine intervention, protection" or 雨 (u) meaning "rain". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: HYEON-U

meaning: Latinized form of ‘Υγινος (Hyginos), a Greek name derived from ‘υγιεινος (hygieinos) meaning "healthy". This was the name of the ninth pope.
name: HYGINUS

meaning: Derived from Greek ‘υπατος (hypatos) meaning "highest, supreme". Hypatia of Alexandria was a 5th-century philosopher and mathematician, daughter of the mathematician Theon.
name: HYPATIA

meaning: Derived from Greek ‘υπερ (hyper) "over". In Greek myth this was the name of a Titan who presided over the sun and light. By Theia he was the father of the sun god Helios, the moon goddess Selene, and the dawn goddess Eos.
name: HYPERION

meaning: Variant of HIRAM. This name was borne by Hyrum Smith (1800-1844), an early leader within the Mormon church.
name: HYRUM

meaning: From Greek Ιακχος (Iakchos), derived from ιαχω (iacho) meaning "to shout". This was the solemn name of the Greek god Dionysos as used in the Eleusinian mysteries.
name: IACCHUS

meaning: Form of JAPHETH used in the Latin Old Testament.
name: IAFETH

meaning: Welsh and Galician form of JACOB. This was the name of two early Welsh kings of Gwynedd. It is also the name of the villain in Shakespeare's tragedy 'Othello' (1603).
name: IAGO

meaning: Form of JAEL used in the Latin Old Testament.
name: IAHEL

meaning: New Testament Greek form of JAIRUS.
name: IAIROS

meaning: Latinized form of IAPETOS. This is the name of one of Saturn's moons.
name: IAPETUS

meaning: Form of JARED used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: IARED

meaning: Means "violet" in Hungarian, ultimately from Latin viola.
name: IBOLYA

meaning: Arabic, Malay and Indonesian form of ABRAHAM.
name: IBRAHIM

meaning: Means "no glory" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament he is the grandson of Eli and the son of Phinehas. This name was also used by Washington Irving for Ichabod Crane, the main character in his short story 'The Legend of Sleepy Hollow' (1820).
name: ICHABOD

meaning: From Japanese 一 (ichi) meaning "one" and 郎 (rou) meaning "son". This was traditionally a name given to the first son. Other combinations of kanji characters are also possible.
name: ICHIROU

meaning: Form of JEDIDAH used in the Latin Old Testament.
name: IDIDA

meaning: Medieval English name, probably a Latinized form of IÐUNN. The spelling may have been influenced by Latin idonea "suitable". It was common in England from the 12th century.
name: IDONEA

meaning: Means "sparkle brilliance" in Sindarin. In the 'Silmarillion' (1977) by J. R. R. Tolkien, Idril was the daughter of Turgon, the king of Gondolin. She escaped the destruction of that place with her husband Tuor and sailed with him into the west.
name: IDRIL

meaning: Possibly means "interpreter" in Arabic. In the Qur'an this is the name of an ancient prophet. He is traditionally equated with the Hebrew prophet Enoch.
name: IDRIS  (1)

meaning: Form of JEDIDAH used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: IEDIDA

meaning: Form of JEPHTHAH used in the Latin Old Testament.
name: IEPTHAE

meaning: Greek form of JOSHUA and JESUS.
name: IESOUS

meaning: Lithuanian and Latvian form of EVE. This is also the Lithuanian and Latvian word for a type of cherry tree (species Prunus padus).
name: IEVA

meaning: From the Roman family name Egnatius, meaning unknown, of Etruscan origin. The spelling was later altered to resemble Latin ignis "fire". This was the name of several saints, including the third bishop of Antioch who was thrown to wild beasts by emperor Trajan, and by Saint Ignatius of Loyola (1491-1556), founder of the Jesuits, whose real birth name was in fact Íñigo.
name: IGNATIUS

meaning: Russian form of Yngvarr (see INGVAR). The Varangians brought it to Russia in the 10th century. It was borne by two Grand Princes of Kiev. Famous bearers include Igor Stravinsky (1882-1971), a Russian composer whose most famous work is 'The Rite of Spring', and Igor Sikorsky (1889-1972), the Russian-American designer of the first successful helicopter.
name: IGOR

meaning: Means "dew" in Basque. It is a Basque equivalent of Rocío.
name: IHINTZA

meaning: Short form of names ending with iina.
name: IINA

meaning: Diminutive of ISAAC. This was the nickname of the American president Dwight D. Eisenhower (1890-1969), based on the initial sound of his surname.
name: IKE

meaning: Means "visitation" in Basque. It is a Basque equivalent of Visitación.
name: IKER

meaning: Russian and Finnish form of HILARIUS.
name: ILARI

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from the Germanic given name HILDEBERT.
name: ILBERT

meaning: From the Mongolian title il-Khan meaning "subordinate Khan", which was first adopted by Genghis Khan's grandson Hulagu, who ruled a kingdom called the Ilkhanate that stretched from modern Iran to eastern Turkey.
name: İLHAN

meaning: Georgian form of ELIJAH. It is also a variant transcription of Russian ILYA or Bulgarian ILIYA.
name: ILIA

meaning: Macedonian, Serbian and Croatian form of ELIJAH, and a Bulgarian variant transcription of ILIYA.
name: ILIJA

meaning: Means "multitude of land" from Welsh il "multitude" and tud "land, people". This was the name of a 6th-century Welsh saint who founded the abbey of Llanilltud in Glamorgan.
name: ILLTYD

meaning: Derived from Finnish ilma "air". In Finnish mythology Ilmatar was a semi-androgynous goddess of the heavens. She was the mother of Ilmarinen, Väinämöinen and Lemminkäinen.
name: ILMATAR

meaning: Hungarian and Czech diminutive of ILONA.
name: ILONKA

meaning: German and Dutch diminutive of ELISABETH.
name: ILSE

meaning: Means "spiritual leader" in Swahili, ultimately from Arabic إمام (Imam).
name: IMAMU

meaning: Means "faith" in Swahili, ultimately of Arabic origin.
name: IMANI

meaning: The name of a princess in the play 'Cymbeline' (1609) by Shakespeare. He based her on a legendary character named Innogen, but the name was printed incorrectly and never corrected. The name Innogen is probably derived from Gaelic inghean meaning "maiden".
name: IMOGEN

meaning: Arabic form of AMRAM. This is the name Muslims traditionally assign to the father of the Virgin Mary (analogous to the Christian Joachim).
name: IMRAN

meaning: Short form of names ending with ina.
name: INA
origin: [English, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Dutch, Limburgish, Croatian]

meaning: Possibly derived from Sumerian (n)in-an-na "lady of the heavens". Inanna was the Sumerian goddess of the earth, love, fertility and war. She descended into the underworld where the ruler of that place, her sister Ereshkigal, had her killed. The god Enki interceded, and Inanna was allowed to leave the underworld as long as her husband Dumuzi took her place.
name: INANNA

meaning: Means "tongue of a bell" in Hebrew.
name: INBAL

meaning: Variant of INDRAJIT used by Sikhs.
name: INDERJIT

meaning: From the name of the country, which is itself derived from the name of the Indus River. The river's name is ultimately from Sanskrit सिन्धु (Sindhu) meaning "body of trembling water, river".
name: INDIA

meaning: From the English word indigo for the purplish-blue dye or the colour. It is ultimately derived from Greek Ινδικον (Indikon) "Indic, from India".
name: INDIGO

meaning: Means "possessing drops of rain" from Sanskrit इन्दु (indu) meaning "a drop" and र (ra) meaning "acquiring, possessing". Indra is the name of the ancient Hindu warrior god of the sky and rain. He is the chief god in the Hindu text the Rigveda.
name: INDRA

meaning: Means "queen of INDRA" in Sanskrit. This is a Hindu goddess of jealousy and beauty, a wife of Indra.
name: INDRANI

meaning: Means "bright drop" in Sanskrit. This is a name for the moon.
name: INDU

meaning: Diminutive of INDIANA. This is the nickname of the hero of the 'Indiana Jones' movies, starring Harrison Ford.
name: INDY

meaning: Italian, Slovene and Croatian form of INÉS.
name: INES

meaning: Diminutive of HASAN. Husayn ibn Ali (also commonly transliterated Hussein) was the son of Ali and the grandson of the Prophet Muhammad. His older brother was named Hasan. The massacre of Husayn and his family was a major event in the split between Shia and Sunni Muslims, which continues to this day. In more recent times this was the name of a king of Jordan (1935-1999).
name: HUSAYN

meaning: Latinate feminine form of HYACINTHUS, used to refer to the 17th-century Italian saint Hyacintha Mariscotti (real name Giacinta).
name: HYACINTHA

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name ‘Υακινθος (Hyakinthos), which was derived from the name of the hyacinth flower. In Greek legend Hyakinthos was accidentally killed by Apollo, who caused a lily to arise from his blood. The name was also borne by several early saints, notably a 3rd-century martyr who was killed with his brother Protus.
name: HYACINTHUS

meaning: From Sino-Korean 慧 (hye) meaning "bright, intelligent" or other characters which are pronounced in the same way. Although it does appear rarely as a single-character name, it is more often used in combination with another character. A notable bearer was a 6th-century king of Baekje.
name: HYE

meaning: From Sino-Korean 賢 (hyeon) meaning "virtuous, worthy, able" or other characters which are pronounced similarly. It usually occurs in combination with another character, though it is sometimes used as a stand-alone name.
name: HYEON

meaning: From Sino-Korean 賢 (hyeon) meaning "virtuous, worthy, able" and 珠 (ju) meaning "jewel, pearl". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: HYEON-JU

meaning: Alteration of HYAM influenced by Yiddish man "man".
name: HYMAN

meaning: Means "eminent" in Welsh. This was the name of a 10th-century king of Wales.
name: HYWEL

meaning: Form of JACHIN used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: IACHIN

meaning: Form of JAEL used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: IAEL

meaning: Variant of Aodhagán, a diminutive of AODH.
name: IAGAN

meaning: Means "moon" in Egyptian. In Egyptian mythology this was the name of a god of the moon, later identified with Thoth.
name: IAH

meaning: Form of JAIR used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: IAIR

meaning: Form of JACOB used in the Greek Bible.
name: IAKOBOS

meaning: Means "violet flower", derived from Greek ιον (ion) "violet" and ανθος (anthos) "flower". This was the name of an ocean nymph in Greek mythology.
name: IANTHE

meaning: Derived from Greek ιαπτω (iapto) "to wound, to pierce". In Greek mythology this was the name of a Titan, the father of Atlas, Prometheus and Epimetheus.
name: IAPETOS

meaning: Form of JAPHETH used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: IAPHETH

meaning: Composed of the Irish elements ior, of unknown meaning, and flaith "lord". Saint Iarfhlaith was a 6th-century bishop from Galway, Ireland.
name: IARFHLAITH
IASON
origin: [Greek Mythology, Ancient Greek, Greek, Biblical Greek, Biblical Latin]

meaning: Chechen and Ossetian form of ABRAHAM.
name: IBRAGIM

meaning: Form of IBRAHIM used in some parts of western Africa.
name: IBRAHIMA

meaning: From the Greek Ικαρος (Ikaros), of unknown meaning. In Greek myth Icarus was the son of Daedalus, locked with his father inside the Labyrinth by Minos. They escaped from the maze using wings devised from wax, but Icarus flew too close to the sun and the wax melted, plunging him to his death.
name: ICARUS

meaning: Derived from the Germanic element id meaning "work, labour". The Normans brought this name to England, though it eventually died out there in the Middle Ages. It was strongly revived in the 19th century, in part due to the heroine in Alfred Lord Tennyson's poem 'The Princess' (1847), which was later adapted into the play 'Princess Ida' (1884) by Gilbert and Sullivan.... [more]
name: IDA
origin: [English, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Dutch, Italian, Spanish, Portuguese, Hungarian, Slovene, Croatian, Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Possibly derived from Old Irish ítu "thirst". This was the name of a 6th-century Irish saint.
name: ÍDE

meaning: Medieval English vernacular form of IDONEA.
name: IDONY

meaning: From the Spanish place name Idoia, possibly meaning "pond" in Basque, an important place of worship of the Virgin Mary.
name: IDOYA

meaning: Means "ardent lord" from Welsh udd "lord, prince" combined with ris "ardent, enthusiastic, impulsive".
name: IDRIS  (2)

meaning: Means "lord of the wall", derived from Welsh udd "lord, prince" combined with gwal "wall, rampart".
name: IDWAL

meaning: Form of JEPHTHAH used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: IEPHTHAE

meaning: Variant of AISHA. It was popularized by the song 'Iesha' (1991) by Another Bad Creation.
name: IESHA

meaning: Hungarian, Czech and Slovak form of IGNATIUS.
name: IGNÁC

meaning: Feminine form of IGON. It is a Basque equivalent of Ascensión.
name: IGONE

meaning: Meaning unknown, from Igerna, the Latinized form of Welsh Eigyr. In Arthurian legend she is the mother of King Arthur by Uther Pendragon and the mother of Morgan le Fay by Gorlois. The Welsh form Eigyr or Eigr was rendered into Latin as Igerna by the 12th-century chronicler Geoffrey of Monmouth.
name: IGRAINE

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements is "ice, iron" and brand "sword".
name: IJSBRAND

meaning: Bulgarian and Macedonian form of HILARION.
name: ILARION

meaning: Spanish form of the Visigothic name Hildefons, which meant "battle ready", derived from the Germanic elements hild "battle" and funs "ready". This was the name of a 7th-century saint, an archbishop of Toledo.
name: ILDEFONSO

meaning: Possibly a form of HILDA. This name was borne by the last wife of Attila the Hun.
name: ILDIKÓ

meaning: Possibly a Romanian variant of ELENA. In Romanian folklore this is the name of a princess kidnapped by monsters and rescued by a heroic knight.
name: ILEANA

meaning: Variant of EILEEN, probably inspired by the spelling of Irene.
name: ILENE

meaning: Feminine form of ILIAS (Greek) or ILIYA (Bulgarian).
name: ILIANA

meaning: From the Greek Ειλειθυια (Eileithyia), which was derived from ειληλυθυια (eilelythyia) "the readycomer". This was the name of the Greek goddess of childbirth and midwifery.
name: ILITHYIA

meaning: Means "new moon" in Turkish, derived from ilk "first" and ay "moon".
name: İLKAY

meaning: Derived from Finnish ilma "air". Ilmarinen is an immortal smith in Finnish mythology, the creator of the sky and the magic mill known as the Sampo. He is one of the main characters in the Finnish epic the 'Kalevala'.
name: ILMARINEN

meaning: Meaning uncertain, possibly a Hungarian form of HELEN.
name: ILONA
origin: [Hungarian, German, Finnish, Latvian, Lithuanian, Polish, Czech]

meaning: From Sino-Korean 日 (il) meaning "sun, day" and 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded". Other hanja character combinations are possible. A notable bearer was Kim Il-sung (1912-1994), the first leader of North Korea.
name: IL-SEONG

meaning: Means "faith", derived from Arabic امن (amuna) "to be faithful".
name: IMAN

meaning: Short form of names beginning with the Germanic element ermen "whole, universal".
name: IME  (2)

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of IRMHILD. The Blessed Imelda was a young 14th-century nun from Bologna.
name: IMELDA

meaning: Means "he comes in peace" in Egyptian. This was the name of the architect, priest, physician and chief minister to the pharaoh Djoser. Imhotep apparently designed the step pyramid at Saqqara, near Memphis.
name: IMHOTEP

meaning: Short form of IMMACOLATA or IMMACULADA.
name: IMMA

meaning: Form of EMMANUEL used in most translations of the Old Testament. Immanuel Kant (1724-1804) was a German philosopher who held that duty was of highest importance.
name: IMMANUEL

meaning: Hungarian form of EMMERICH. This was the name of an 11th-century Hungarian saint, the son of Saint Istvan. He is also known as Emeric.
name: IMRE

meaning: Means "protector of Indra" from the name of the god INDRA combined with Sanskrit पाल (pala) meaning "protector".
name: INDERPAL

meaning: From the name of the American state, which means "land of the Indians". This is the name of the hero in the 'Indiana Jones' series of movies, starring Harrison Ford.
name: INDIANA

meaning: Means "beauty" in Sanskrit. This is another name of Lakshmi, the wife of the Hindu god Vishnu. A notable bearer was India's first female prime minister, Indira Gandhi (1917-1984).
name: INDIRA

meaning: Means "conqueror of Indra" from the name of the god INDRA combined with Sanskrit जिति (jiti) meaning "victory, conquering". In Hindu legend this is another name of Meghanada, the son of Ravana, the king of Sri Lanka. He was given this name by Brahma after he defeated Indra.
name: INDRAJIT

meaning: From the Germanic *Ingwaz, possibly meaning "ancestor". This was the name of an obscure old Germanic fertility god who was considered the ancestor of the tribe the Ingaevones. It is possible he was an earlier incarnation of the god Freyr.
name: ING

meaning: Short form of Scandinavian and German names beginning with the element ing, which refers to the Germanic god ING. In Sweden and Norway this is primarily a masculine name, elsewhere it is usually feminine.
name: INGE

meaning: From the Old Norse name Ingibjörg, which was derived from the name of the Germanic god ING combined with björg meaning "help, save, rescue".
name: INGEBORG

meaning: From the Old Norse name Ingimárr, derived from the name of the Germanic god ING combined with mærr "famous".
name: INGEMAR

meaning: Variant of INGEMAR. This name was borne by the Swedish film director Ingmar Bergman (1918-2007).
name: INGMAR

meaning: From the Old Norse name Ingólfr, which was derived from the name of the Germanic god ING combined with úlfr meaning "wolf".
name: INGOLF

meaning: From the Old Norse name Ingríðr meaning "Ing is beautiful", derived from the name of the Germanic god ING combined with fríðr "beautiful". A famous bearer was the Swedish actress Ingrid Bergman (1915-1982).
name: INGRID

meaning: From the Old Norse name Yngvildr, derived from the name of the Norse god YNGVI combined with hildr "battle".
name: INGVILD

meaning: Medieval Spanish form of ENEKO. This was the birth name of Saint Ignatius of Loyola, who changed it in honour of Saint Ignatius of Antioch. As such, this name is sometimes regarded as a form of IGNATIUS.
name: ÍÑIGO

meaning: Frisian and Finnish feminine form of INGE, and a German variant.
name: INKA

meaning: Means "immaculate" in Spanish. This name is given to commemorate the Immaculate Conception of the Virgin Mary.
name: INMACULADA

meaning: Anglicized form of AONGHUS, also used as a feminine name.
name: INNES

meaning: Meaning unknown. In Greek mythology Io was a princess loved by Zeus, who changed her into a heifer in order to hide her from Hera. A moon of Jupiter bears this name in her honour.
name: IO

meaning: Romanian and Welsh form of JOHN. This is also a variant transcription of the Bulgarian name YOAN.
name: IOAN

meaning: Modern Greek transcription of Ioannes (see JOHN).
name: IOANNIS

meaning: Form of JOB used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: IOB

meaning: Form of JOEL used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: IOEL

meaning: Italian, Portuguese and Romanian form of YOLANDA.
name: IOLANDA

meaning: Means "violet" in Greek. In Greek mythology she was a woman beloved by Herakles.
name: IOLE

meaning: Of unknown etymology, possibly pre-Greek. According to Greek mythology he was a son of Creusa and Xuthus (or alternatively the god Apollo). He was said to be the ancestor of the Greek tribe of the Ionians.
name: ION  (2)

meaning: Form of JONAH used in the Latin Old Testament, as well as the Russian and Georgian form.
name: IONA  (2)

meaning: From Greek ιον (ion) meaning "violet flower". This was the name of a sea nymph in Greek mythology. It has been used as a given name in the English-speaking world since the 19th century, though perhaps based on the Greek place name Ionia, a region on the west coast of Asia Minor.
name: IONE

meaning: Form of JORAM used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: IORAM

meaning: Means "handsome lord" from Welsh ior "lord" and berth "handsome". This name is used in the Mabinogion, a collection of tales from Welsh myth, where it belongs to a son of Maredudd. This name is sometimes used as a Welsh form of EDWARD.
name: IORWERTH

meaning: Form of JOSIAH used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: IOSIAS

meaning: Old Slavic form of Ioseph (see JOSEPH).
name: IOSIFU

meaning: Form of JUNIA used in the Greek New Testament.
name: IOUNIA

meaning: Turkish form of Arabic إرَم (Iram), the name of a beautiful city mentioned in sura Al-Fajr of the Qur'an.
name: İREM
IRENA
origin: [Polish, Czech, Slovene, Croatian, Serbian, Bulgarian, Dutch, Lithuanian]

meaning: Possibly a Portuguese and Galician form of IRENE. This was the name of a 7th-century saint (also known as Irene) from Tomar in Portugal. This is also the name of an ancient town in Galicia (now a district of Padrón).
name: IRIA

meaning: Portuguese and Icelandic form of IRIS.
name: ÍRIS

meaning: Means "asphodel" in Hebrew (an asphodel is a type of flower).
name: IRIT

meaning: German short form of names beginning with the Germanic element ermen, which meant "whole, universal". It is thus related to EMMA. It began to be regularly used in the English-speaking world in the 19th century.
name: IRMA
origin: [German, English, Dutch, Finnish, Spanish, Italian, Georgian, Lithuanian, Hungarian (Rare), Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements ermen "whole, universal" and hild "battle".
name: IRMHILD

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from the Old English given name EOFORWINE.
name: IRWIN

meaning: From the Hebrew name יִצְחָק (Yitzchaq) meaning "he will laugh, he will rejoice", derived from צָחַק (tzachaq) meaning "to laugh". The Old Testament explains this meaning, by recounting that Abraham laughed when God told him that his aged wife Sarah would become pregnant with Isaac (see Genesis 17:17). When Isaac was a boy, God tested Abraham's faith by ordering him to sacrifice his son, though an angel prevented the act at the last moment. Isaac went on to become the father of Esau and Jacob with his wife Rebecca.... [more]
name: ISAAC

meaning: Medieval Occitan form of ELIZABETH. It spread throughout Spain, Portugal and France, becoming common among the royalty by the 12th century. It grew popular in England in the 13th century after Isabella of Angoulême married the English king John, and it was subsequently bolstered when Isabella of France married Edward II the following century.... [more]
name: ISABEL

meaning: Variant of ISIDORA. A famous bearer was the American dancer Isadora Duncan (1877-1927).
name: ISADORA

meaning: Late Latin form of ISAIAH used in some versions of the Bible.
name: ISAIAS

meaning: From Japanese 勇 (isamu) meaning "brave" or other kanji having the same pronunciation.
name: ISAMU

meaning: Germanic name, a hypothetical early form of ISOLDE.
name: ISHILD

meaning: From the Hebrew name יִשְׁמָעֵאל (Yishma'el) meaning "God will hear". In the Old Testament this is the name of a son of Abraham. He is the traditional ancestor of the Arab people. Also in the Old Testament, it is borne by a man who assassinates Gedaliah the governor of Judah. The author Herman Melville later used this name for the narrator in his novel 'Moby-Dick' (1851).
name: ISHMAEL

meaning: Meaning unknown. Ishtar was the Babylonian and Assyrian mother goddess who presided over love, war and fertility. She was called Ashtoreth by the Phoenicians, and she was also identified with the Sumerian goddess Inanna.
name: ISHTAR

meaning: Feminine form of ISIDORE. This was the name of a 4th-century Egyptian saint and hermitess.
name: ISIDORA
origin: [Serbian, Macedonian, Spanish, Portuguese, Russian (Rare), Italian (Rare), English (Rare), Ancient Greek]

meaning: Spanish and Italian form of ISIDORE.
name: ISIDORO

meaning: Arabic, Indonesian and Malay form of ALEXANDER.
name: ISKANDAR

meaning: From a South Slavic word meaning "spark".
name: ISKRA

meaning: Derived from Islam, the name of the religion (ultimately from Arabic إسلام), combined with the Turkish military title beg meaning "chieftain, master".
name: ISLAMBEK

meaning: From the name of a mountain in Wales which means "below the grove" from Welsh is "below" and llwyn "grove".
name: ISLWYN

meaning: Form of ISHMAEL used in the Latin Old Testament.
name: ISMAHEL

meaning: The origins of this name are uncertain, though some Celtic roots have been suggested. It is possible that the name is ultimately Germanic, perhaps from a hypothetic name like Ishild, composed of the elements is "ice, iron" and hild "battle".... [more]
name: ISOLDE

meaning: Means "nocturnal journey", derived from Arabic سرى (sara) "to travel at night".
name: ISRA

meaning: From the Hebrew name יִשְׂרָאֵל (Yisra'el) meaning "God contended". In the Old Testament Israel (who was formerly named Jacob; see Genesis 32:28) wrestles with an angel. The ancient and modern states of Israel took their names from him.
name: ISRAEL

meaning: Form of ISRAEL used in the Latin Old Testament.
name: ISRAHEL

meaning: Hungarian form of STEPHEN. This was the name of the first king of Hungary. Ruling in the 11th century, he encouraged the spread of Christianity among his subjects and is considered the patron saint of Hungary.
name: ISTVÁN

meaning: From the Italian name of the country of Italy, Italia (see ITALUS).
name: ITALIA

meaning: Means "of Italy" in Latin. In Roman legend Italus was the father of Romulus and Remus, the founders of Rome. He supposedly gave his name to the region known as Italia or Italy (in fact the region may have gotten its name from Oscan Víteliú meaning "land of bulls").
name: ITALUS

meaning: From a Hebrew name spelled variously אִתַּי ('Ittay) or אִיתַי ('Itay) meaning "with me". In the Old Testament this is the name of one of King David's mighty men.
name: ITHAI

meaning: Means "generous lord" from the Welsh elements udd "lord, prince" and hael "generous".
name: ITHEL

meaning: Probably derived from Old Norse ið "again" and unna "to love". In Norse mythology Iðunn was the goddess of spring and immortality whose responsibility it was to guard the gods' apples of youth.
name: IÐUNN

meaning: From Japanese 樹 (itsuki) meaning "tree", using the kanji's nanori reading. Other kanji or kanji combinations can also form this name.
name: ITSUKI

meaning: Ancient Roman and Romanian form of JULIA.
name: IULIA

meaning: Ancient Roman and Romanian form of JULIANA.
name: IULIANA
INGA
origin: [Swedish, Danish, Norwegian, Icelandic, Latvian, Lithuanian, German, Russian, Ancient Scandinavian, Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Norwegian and Danish variant of INGEBORG.
name: INGEBJØRG

meaning: From the Old Norse name Ingigerðr, which was derived from the name of the Germanic god ING combined with garðr meaning "enclosure".
name: INGEGERD

meaning: Old Norse and Icelandic form of INGEBORG.
name: INGIBJÖRG

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from the Norman French given name ENGUERRAND.
name: INGRAM

meaning: From the Old Norse name Yngvarr, which was derived from the name of the Germanic god YNGVI combined with arr meaning "warrior".
name: INGVAR

meaning: English form of ÍÑIGO. It became well-known in Britain due to the 17th-century English architect Inigo Jones. He was named after his father, a Catholic who was named for Saint Ignatius of Loyola.
name: INIGO

meaning: Meaning unknown. This was the name of an early Scythian saint and martyr, a male, supposedly a disiciple of Saint Andrew.
name: INNA

meaning: From the Late Latin name Innocentius which was derived from innocens "innocent". This was the name of several early saints. It was also borne by 13 popes including Innocent III, a politically powerful ruler and organizer of the Fourth Crusade.
name: INNOCENT

meaning: Greek and Latin form of JOAB.

meaning: Invented name, probably based on JARED and DARREN.
name: JARON  (2)

meaning: Czech and Slovak form of JAROSŁAW.
name: JAROSLAV

meaning: From a surname which was a variant of GARRETT.
name: JARRETT

meaning: From a surname which was derived from the given name GERVAIS.
name: JARVIS

meaning: From the English word for the climbing plant with fragrant flowers which is used for making perfumes. It is derived from Persian یاسمن (yasamen) (which is also a Persian name).
name: JASMINE

meaning: Derived from South Slavic jasno meaning "clear, sharp".
name: JASNA

meaning: Means "treasurer" in Persian. This name was traditionally assigned to one of the wise men (also known as the Magi, or three kings) who were said to have visited the newborn Jesus. It has occasionally been used in the English-speaking world since the Middle Ages. The name can also be given in reference to the English word for the gemstone.
name: JASPER

meaning: From Sanskrit यशस् (yashas) meaning "fame, praise, glory" combined with the name of the Hindu god INDRA.
name: JASWINDER

meaning: Means "Greece" in Hebrew, possibly related to ION  (2). In the Old Testament this is the name of a grandson of Noah and the ancestor of the Greek peoples.
name: JAVAN

meaning: Means "goodness, excellence", derived from Arabic جاد (jada) "to be excellent".
name: JAWDAT

meaning: Modern (northern Indian) masculine form of JAYA.
name: JAY  (2)

meaning: Means "lord of victory" from Sanskrit जय (jaya) meaning "victory" combined with the name of the god INDRA, used here to mean "lord".
name: JAYENDRA

meaning: Combination of JAY  (1) and the popular name suffix la.
name: JAYLA

meaning: Variant of JALEN. It can also be a feminine elaboration of JAY  (1).
name: JAYLEN

meaning: Variant of JALEN. It can also be a feminine elaboration of JAY  (1).
name: JAYLIN

meaning: Feminine elaboration of JAY  (1) using the popular suffix lyn.
name: JAYLYN

meaning: Modern name, a combination of the popular name elements Jaz and lyn.
name: JAZLYN

meaning: Medieval English variant of Jehanne (see JANE). It was common in England and Scotland during the Middle Ages, but eventually became rare in England. It was reintroduced to the English-speaking world from Scotland in the 19th century.
name: JEAN  (2)

meaning: Combination of JEAN  (1) and BAPTISTE, referring to Saint John the Baptist.
name: JEAN-BAPTISTE

meaning: Sometimes a diminutive of JACOB. This name may have also resulted from a nickname of James Ewell Brown Stuart (1833-1864), a Confederate general in the American Civil War, which was formed from the initial letters of his three given names.
name: JEB

meaning: Means "beloved of YAHWEH" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is a name given to Solomon by Nathan.
name: JEDIDIAH

meaning: Old French form of Iohannes (see JOHN).
name: JEHAN

meaning: Means "God lives" in Hebrew. This is the name of several people in the Old Testament, including one of King David's lute players.
name: JEHIEL

meaning: From the Hebrew name Yehochanan, an extended form of Yochanan (see JOHN). It is borne by a few minor characters in the English Old Testament.
name: JEHOHANAN

meaning: Means "raised by YAHWEH" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of a king of Judah. He lived in the 7th century BC, and was the son of Josiah and the father of Jehoiachin.
name: JEHOIAKIM

meaning: From the Hebrew name יְהוֹנָתָן (Yehonatan), the full form of JONATHAN. This is the name of a few minor characters in the Old Testament.
name: JEHONATHAN

meaning: Means "YAHWEH has judged" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament he is the fourth king of Judah, noted for having a generally peaceful and prosperous reign.
name: JEHOSHAPHAT

meaning: Means "YAHWEH is he" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of a king of Israel. He ruled in the 9th century BC, coming to power by overthrowing Jehoram. This was also the name of a prophet during the reign of the king Baasha.
name: JEHU

meaning: Form of YELENA. In Serbia, Croatia and Slovenia it is also associated with the South Slavic words jelen meaning "deer, stag" and jela meaning "fir tree".
name: JELENA

meaning: Originally a Frisian short form of Germanic names beginning with the element gild "sacrifice, value". It can also be a Dutch diminutive of WILLEM.
name: JELLE

meaning: Means "dove" in Hebrew. This was the oldest of the three daughters of Job in the Old Testament. As an English name, Jemima first became common during the Puritan era.
name: JEMIMA

meaning: Diminutive of JEREMY (and formerly of JAMES).
name: JEMMY

meaning: Combination of JEN and the popular name suffix elle.
name: JENELLE

meaning: Variant of JENNY. Use of the name was popularized in the 1980s by the character Jenna Wade on the television series 'Dallas'.
name: JENNA

meaning: From a Cornish form of the Welsh name Gwenhwyfar (see GUINEVERE). This name has only been common outside of Cornwall since the beginning of the 20th century, after it was featured in George Bernard Shaw's play 'The Doctor's Dilemma' (1906).
name: JENNIFER

meaning: Originally a medieval English diminutive of JANE. Since the middle of the 20th century it has been primarily considered a diminutive of JENNIFER.
name: JENNY

meaning: From the name of an ancient Hungarian tribe. Since the 19th century it has been used as a Hungarian form of EUGENE.
name: JENŐ

meaning: From Sino-Korean 靜 (jeong) meaning "quiet, still, gentle" or 貞 (jeong) meaning "virtuous, chaste, loyal", as well as other characters which are pronounced similarly. It usually occurs in combination with another character, though it is sometimes used as a stand-alone name.
name: JEONG

meaning: From Sino-Korean 正 (jeong) meaning "right, proper, correct" or 靜 (jeong) meaning "quiet, still, gentle" combined with 姬 (hui) meaning "beauty" or 熙 (hui) meaning "bright, splendid, glorious". Other combinations of hanja characters can form this name as well.
name: JEONG-HUI

meaning: From Sino-Korean 貞 (jeong) meaning "virtuous, chaste, loyal" or 正 (jeong) meaning "right, proper, correct" combined with 淑 (suk) meaning "good, pure, virtuous, charming". Other hanja combinations are possible.
name: JEONG-SUK

meaning: Medieval English form of JEREMIAH, and the form used in some English versions of the New Testament.
name: JEREMY

meaning: Means "taught by YAHWEH" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament, Jeriah is a descendant of Hebron.
name: JERIAH

meaning: From the Hebrew name יָרָבְעָם (Yarav'am) meaning "the people contend". According to the Old Testament, this was the name of the leader of the revolt against King Rehoboam of Israel. The kingdom was split into Judah in the south and Israel in the north, with Jeroboam becoming the first king of the latter.
name: JEROBOAM

meaning: From the Greek name ‘Ιερωνυμος (Hieronymos) meaning "sacred name", derived from ‘ιερος (hieros) "sacred" and ονομα (onoma) "name". Saint Jerome was responsible for the creation of the Vulgate, the Latin translation of the Bible, in the 5th century. He is regarded as a Doctor of the Church. The name was used in his honour in the Middle Ages, especially in Italy and France, and has been used in England since the 12th century.
name: JEROME

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of JEROME.
name: JERÓNIMO

meaning: Means "possession" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament she is the wife of King Uzziah of Judah and the mother of Jotham.
name: JERUSHA

meaning: Short form of JESSE or JESSICA.
name: JESS

meaning: Combination of JESSIE  (1) and the popular name suffix lyn.
name: JESSALYN

meaning: This name was first used in this form by Shakespeare in his play 'The Merchant of Venice' (1596), where it belongs to the daughter of Shylock. Shakespeare probably based it on the biblical name ISCAH, which would have been spelled Jescha in his time. It was not commonly used as a given name until the middle of the 20th century. Notable bearers include actresses Jessica Tandy (1909-1994) and Jessica Lange (1949-).
name: JESSICA
origin: [English, French, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Italian, Spanish]

meaning: English form of Ιησους (Iesous), which was the Greek form of the Aramaic name יֵשׁוּעַ (Yeshu'a). Yeshu'a is itself a contracted form of Yehoshu'a (see JOSHUA). Yeshua ben Yoseph, better known as Jesus Christ, was the central figure of the New Testament and the source of the Christian religion. The four gospels state that he was the son of God and the Virgin Mary who fulfilled the Old Testament prophecies of the Messiah. He preached for three years before being crucified in Jerusalem.
name: JESUS

meaning: Short form of HENRIËTTE or MARIËTTE.
name: JET

meaning: From the English word jet, which denotes either a jet aircraft or an intense black colour (the words derive from different sources).
name: JETT

meaning: From the Hebrew אִיזֶבֶל ('Izevel) which probably means "where is the prince?", a ritual question spoken in ceremonies honouring Baal. Alternatively, it may mean "not exalted". In the Old Testament Jezebel is the evil wife of Ahab, king of Israel. After she was thrown from a window to her death her body was eaten by dogs, fulfilling Elijah's prophecy.
name: JEZEBEL

meaning: From Sino-Korean 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" or other hanja characters with the same pronunciation. Although it does appear rarely as a single-character name, it is more often used in combination with another character.
name: JI

meaning: From Chinese 家 (jiā) meaning "home, family" combined with 豪 (háo) meaning "brave, heroic, chivalrous". This name can be formed from other character combinations as well.
name: JIAHAO

meaning: From Chinese 江 (jiāng) meaning "river, Yangtze", as well as other characters with a similar pronunciation.
name: JIANG

meaning: From Sino-Korean 枝 (ji) meaning "branch, limb", 知 (ji) meaning "know, perceive, comprehend" or 志 (ji) meaning "will, purpose, ambition" combined with 恩 (eun) meaning "kindness, mercy, charity". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: JI-EUN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" combined with 厚 (hu) meaning "thick". Other combinations of hanja characters can form this name as well.
name: JI-HU

meaning: From a Sino-Korean compound meaning "wisdom", formed of the hanja characters 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" and 慧 (hye) meaning "bright, intelligent". This name can also be formed from other character combinations.
name: JI-HYE

meaning: Diminutive of JAMES. A famous bearer was the rock musician Jimi Hendrix (1942-1970).
name: JIMI

meaning: Diminutive or feminine form of JAMES.
name: JIMMIE

meaning: From Chinese 静 (jìng) meaning "quiet, still, gentle", 精 (jīng) meaning "essence, spirit", 晶 (jīng) meaning "clear, crystal" or 京 (jīng) meaning "capital city". Other characters can also form this name.
name: JING

meaning: Variant of JITENDRA used by Sikhs.
name: JITENDER

meaning: Short form of JOAN  (1), JOANNA, JOSEPHINE, or other names that begin with Jo. It is primarily masculine in German and Dutch, short for JOHANNES or JOSEF.
name: JO

meaning: Contracted form of JEHOIACHIN or JEHOIAKIM. According to the apocryphal Gospel of James, Saint Joachim was the husband of Saint Anne and the father of the Virgin Mary. Due to his popularity in the Middle Ages, the name came into general use in Christian Europe (though it was never common in England).
name: JOACHIM

meaning: Medieval English form of Johanne, an Old French form of Iohanna (see JOANNA). This was the usual English feminine form of John in the Middle Ages, but it was surpassed in popularity by Jane in the 17th century.... [more]
name: JOAN  (1)

meaning: Portuguese and Catalan form of Iohanna (see JOANNA).
name: JOANA

meaning: Latinized form of Greek Ιοκαστη (Iokaste), which is of unknown meaning. In Greek mythology she was the mother Oedipus by the Theban king Laius. In a case of tragic mistaken identity, she married her own son.
name: JOCASTA

meaning: French feminine form of Joscelin (see JOCELYN).
name: JOCELINE

meaning: French feminine form of Joscelin (see JOCELYN).
name: JOCELYNE

meaning: From the Greek name Ιασων (Iason), which was derived from Greek ιασθαι (iasthai) "to heal". In Greek mythology Jason was the leader of the Argonauts. After his uncle Pelias overthrew his father Aeson as king of Iolcos, Jason went in search of the Golden Fleece in order to win back the throne. During his journeys he married the sorceress Medea, who helped him gain the fleece and kill his uncle, but who later turned against him when he fell in love with another woman.... [more]
name: JASON

meaning: Means "jewels" in Arabic, ultimately from Persian گوهر (gohar) "jewel, essence".
name: JAWAHIR

meaning: Short form of names beginning with the sound J, such as JAMES or JASON. It was originally used in America in honour of founding father John Jay (1749-1825), whose surname was derived from the jaybird.
name: JAY  (1)

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit जय (jaya) meaning "victory". This is a transcription of both the feminine form जया (an epithet of the Hindu goddess Durga) and the masculine form जय (borne by several characters in Hindu texts). As a modern personal name, this transcription is both feminine and masculine in southern India, but typically only feminine in the north.
name: JAYA

meaning: Means "divine victory" from Sanskrit जय (jaya) meaning "victory" and देव (deva) meaning "god". This was the name of a 13th-century Indian poet.
name: JAYADEVA

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit जयन्त (jayanta) meaning "victorious". This is the name of a son of the Hindu god Indra, as well as other figures in Hindu mythology.
name: JAYANTA

meaning: Feminine form of JAYANTA. This is another name of the Hindu goddess Durga.
name: JAYANTI

meaning: Means "lord of victory" from Sanskrit जय (jaya) meaning "victory, conquest" and ईश (isha) meaning "lord, ruler".
name: JAYESH

meaning: Feminine elaboration of JAY  (1) using the popular suffix lene.
name: JAYLENE

meaning: French form of Jehan, the Old French form of Iohannes (see JOHN). The French philosophers Jean-Jacques Rousseau (1712-1778) and Jean Paul Sartre (1905-1980) were two well-known bearers of this name. It was also borne by the German-French Dadaist artist Jean Arp (1886-1966).
name: JEAN  (1)

meaning: Modern French form of Jehanne, an Old French feminine form of Iohannes (see JOHN). Joan of Arc is known as Jeanne d'Arc in France.
name: JEANNE

meaning: Means "established by YAHWEH" in Hebrew. This is another name (with the same meaning) of the Judean king Jehoiachin.
name: JECONIAH

meaning: Means "beloved" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of the wife of King Amon of Judah and the mother of Josiah.
name: JEDIDAH

meaning: An old Polish form of ANDREW.
name: JĘDRZEJ

meaning: From an English surname meaning "son of JEFFREY". It is usually given in honour of Thomas Jefferson (1743-1826), the third president of the United States and the primary author of the Declaration of Independence.
name: JEFFERSON

meaning: Medieval variant of GEOFFREY. In America, Jeffrey has been more common than Geoffrey, though this is not true in Britain.
name: JEFFREY

meaning: Serbian form of EUPHEMIA. This name was adopted by a 14th-century Serbian poet (born Jelena Mrnjavčević).
name: JEFIMIJA

meaning: Old French feminine form of Iohannes (see JOHN).
name: JEHANNE

meaning: From the Hebrew name יְהוֹאָשׁ (Yeho'ash), an extended form of יוֹאָשׁ (see JOASH). According to the Old Testament, this was the name of a king of Israel. He probably reigned in the 8th century BC.
name: JEHOASH

meaning: Means "established by YAHWEH" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of a king of Judah. Also known as Jeconiah, he was imprisoned in Babylon by Nebuchadnezzar after a brief reign in the early 6th century BC.
name: JEHOIACHIN

meaning: From the Hebrew name יְהוֹרָם (Yehoram) which meant "exalted by YAHWEH". In the Old Testament this is the name of a king of Judah and a king of Israel, both of whom ruled at about the same time in the 9th century BC.
name: JEHORAM

meaning: Form of YAHWEH used in older translations of the Bible, produced by blending the letters of the tetragrammaton with the vowels from ADONAI.
name: JEHOVAH

meaning: Means "Jew" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of a servant of king Jehoiakim.
name: JEHUDI

meaning: Short form of JELENA or JELISAVETA. It also means "fir tree" in Serbian and Croatian.
name: JELA

meaning: Diminutive of JELENA. It also means "fir tree" in Slovene.
name: JELKA

meaning: Diminutive of JEREMY (and formerly of JAMES).
name: JEM

meaning: Combination of JEN and the popular name suffix essa.
name: JENESSA

meaning: Variant of JENNY. Before the 20th century this spelling was more common.
name: JENNIE

meaning: From Sino-Korean 正 (jeong) meaning "right, proper, correct" combined with 好 (ho) meaning "good, excellent" or 浩 (ho) meaning "great, numerous, vast". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: JEONG-HO

meaning: From Sino-Korean 正 (jeong) meaning "right, proper, correct" and 勛 (hun) meaning "meritorious deed, rank", as well as other hanja character combinations.
name: JEONG-HUN

meaning: Means "he opens" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this name belongs to a ruling judge. He successfully defended Israel from the Ammonites, but was then obliged to sacrifice his daughter because of a vow he had made.
name: JEPHTHAH

meaning: From an English surname which meant "son of JEP".
name: JEPSON

meaning: From the Hebrew name יִרְמְיָהוּ (Yirmiyahu) which meant "YAHWEH has uplifted". This is the name of one of the major prophets of the Old Testament, the author of the Book of Jeremiah and the Book of Lamentations (supposedly). He lived to see the Babylonian destruction of Jerusalem in the 6th century BC.... [more]
name: JEREMIAH

meaning: German, Portuguese and Finnish form of JEREMIAH.
name: JEREMIAS

meaning: Means "God uplifts" in Hebrew. Jeremiel is named as an archangel in the apocryphal books of Esdras and Enoch in the Old Testament.
name: JEREMIEL

meaning: From the name of a city in Israel which is mentioned several times in the Old Testament. The meaning of the city's name is uncertain, but it may be related to the Hebrew word יָרֵחַ (yareach) meaning "moon", or otherwise to the Hebrew word רֵיחַ (reyach) meaning "fragrant".
name: JERICHO

meaning: Variant of GERMAIN. The name was popularized in the 1970s by Jermaine Jackson (1954-), a member of the singing group The Jackson 5.
name: JERMAINE

meaning: Diminutive of JEREMY, JEROME, GERALD, GERALDINE, and other names beginning with the same sound.
name: JERRY

meaning: From a surname which was a variant of JARVIS.
name: JERVIS

meaning: Form of ISCAH found in the medieval Wycliffe Bible. This name was probably the basis for Shakespeare's created name Jessica.
name: JESCHA

meaning: From a variant spelling of the English word jasmine (see JASMINE), used also to refer to flowering plants in the cestrum family.
name: JESSAMINE

meaning: From the Hebrew name יִשַׁי (Yishay) which possibly means "gift". In the Old Testament Jesse is the father of King David. It began to be used as an English given name after the Protestant Reformation. A famous bearer was Jesse James (1847-1882), an American outlaw who held up banks and stagecoaches. He was eventually shot by a fellow gang member for a reward. Another famous bearer was the American athlete Jesse Owens (1913-1980), whose real name was James Cleveland (or J. C.) Owens.
name: JESSE

meaning: Originally a Scottish diminutive of JEAN  (2). In modern times it is also used as a diminutive of JESSICA.
name: JESSIE  (1)

meaning: German and English variant of JESSICA.
name: JESSIKA

meaning: Spanish form of JESUS, used as a personal name.
name: JESÚS

meaning: From the Hebrew name יִתְרוֹ (Yitro), which was derived from the Hebrew word יֶתֶר (yeter) meaning "abundance". According to the Old Testament, Jethro was a Midianite priest who sheltered Moses when he fled Egypt. He was the father of Zipporah, who became Moses's wife. A famous bearer of the name was Jethro Tull (1674-1741), an English inventor and agriculturist.
name: JETHRO

meaning: Means "youth" in French. It is not used as a given name in France itself.
name: JEUNESSE

meaning: In part from the English word jewel, a precious stone, derived from Old French jouel, which was possibly related to jeu "game". It is also in part from the surname Jewel or Jewell (a derivative of the Breton name JUDICAËL), which was sometimes used in honour of the 16th-century bishop of Salisbury John Jewel. It has been in use as a given name since the 19th century.
name: JEWEL

meaning: From Chinese 佳 (jiā) meaning "good, auspicious, beautiful", 家 (jiā) meaning "home, family", or other characters which are pronounced similarly.
name: JIA

meaning: From Chinese 建 (jiàn) meaning "build, establish", 健 (jiàn) meaning "strong, healthy", or other characters which are pronounced in a similar fashion.
name: JIAN

meaning: From Chinese 健 (jiàn) meaning "build, establish" combined with 宏 (hóng) meaning "wide, spacious, great, vast". This name can also be formed from other character combinations.
name: JIANHONG

meaning: From Chinese 杰 (jié) meaning "heroic, outstanding" or other characters which are pronounced similarly.
name: JIE

meaning: From Sino-Korean 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" or 志 (ji) meaning "will, purpose, ambition" combined with 勛 (hun) meaning "meritorious deed, rank". This name can be formed by other hanja character combinations as well.
name: JI-HUN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 志 (ji) meaning "will, purpose, ambition" or 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" combined with 旼 (min) meaning "gentle, affable", 敏 (min) meaning "quick, clever, sharp" or 珉 (min) meaning "jade, stone resembling jade". Other hanja character combinations are possible.
name: JI-MIN

meaning: Means "divine warrior", from Japanese 神 (jin) meaning "god" and 武 (mu) meaning "military, martial". In Japanese legend this was the name of the founder of Japan and the first emperor, supposedly ruling in the 7th century BC.
name: JIMMU

meaning: From Chinese 金 (jīn) meaning "gold, metal, money", 锦 (jǐn) meaning "tapestry, brocade, embroidered" or 津 (jīn) meaning "ferry". Other Chinese characters can form this name as well.
name: JIN

meaning: From Chinese 静 (jìng) meaning "quiet, still, gentle" combined with 怡 (yí) meaning "joy, harmony". Other character combinations are possible as well.
name: JINGYI

meaning: From Japanese 二 (ji) meaning "two" and 郎 (rou) meaning "son". This was traditionally a name given to the second son. Other combinations of kanji characters can also be possible.
name: JIROU

meaning: Means "conqueror of Indra" from Sanskrit जिति (jiti) meaning "victory, conquering" combined with the name of the god INDRA.
name: JITENDRA

meaning: From Sino-Korean 芝 (ji) meaning "sesame" or 志 (ji) meaning "will, purpose, ambition" combined with 雨 (u) meaning "rain" or 宇 (u) meaning "house, eaves, universe". Other combinations of hanja characters can form this name as well.
name: JI-U

meaning: From Sino-Korean 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" or 知 (ji) meaning "know, perceive, comprehend" combined with 英 (yeong) meaning "flower, petal, brave, hero" or 榮 (yeong) meaning "glory, honour, flourish, prosper". Many other hanja character combinations are possible.
name: JI-YEONG

meaning: From Sino-Korean 智 (ji) meaning "wisdom, intellect" and 裕 (yu) meaning "abundant, rich, plentiful". Other combinations of hanja characters can form this name as well.
name: JI-YU

meaning: Means "YAHWEH is father" in Hebrew. According to the Old Testament, he was the commander of King David's army. In separate incidents he killed both Abner and Absalom. When Solomon came to power he was executed.
name: JOAB

meaning: Scandinavian, Macedonian and Serbian form of JOACHIM.
name: JOAKIM

meaning: Catalan and Occitan form of Iohannes (see JOHN).
name: JOAN  (2)

meaning: English and Polish form of Latin Iohanna, which was derived from Greek Ιωαννα (Ioanna), the feminine form of Ioannes (see JOHN). This is the spelling used in the English New Testament, where it belongs to a follower of Jesus who is regarded as a saint. In the Middle Ages in England it was used as a Latinized form of Joan (the usual feminine form of John) and it became common as a given name in the 19th century.
name: JOANNA

meaning: Portuguese and Catalan form of JOACHIM.
name: JOAQUIM

meaning: From the Hebrew name יוֹאָשׁ (Yo'ash) which possibly meant either "fire of YAHWEH" or "YAHWEH has given". In the Old Testament this name was borne by several characters including the father of Gideon, a king of Judah, and a son of King Ahab of Israel.
name: JOASH

meaning: From the Hebrew name אִיּוֹב ('Iyyov) which means "persecuted, hated". In the Book of Job in the Old Testament he is a righteous man who is tested by God, enduring many tragedies and hardships while struggling to remain faithful.
name: JOB

meaning: From a Germanic masculine name, variously written as Gaudelenus, Gautselin, Gauzlin, along with many other spellings. It was derived from the Germanic element Gaut, which was from the name of the Germanic tribe the Gauts, combined with a Latin diminutive suffix. The Normans brought this name to England in the form Goscelin or Joscelin, and it was common until the 14th century. It was revived in the 20th century primarily as a feminine name, perhaps an adaptation of the surname Jocelyn (a medieval derivative of the given name). In France this is a masculine name only.
name: JOCELYN

meaning: From the Hebrew name יוֹכֶבֶד (Yokheved) which meant "YAHWEH is glory". In the Old Testament this is the name of the mother of Miriam, Aaron and Moses.
name: JOCHEBED

meaning: Medieval variant of JOYCE, influenced by the Latin word iocosus or jocosus "merry, playful".
name: JOCOSA

meaning: Probably either a variant of JUDY or a diminutive of JOSEPH. It was popularized by the young hero in Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings' novel 'The Yearling' (1938) and the subsequent film adaptation (1946).
name: JODY

meaning: French and Dutch form of JOEL.
name: JOËL

meaning: Diminutive of JOSEPH. It is occasionally used as a feminine diminutive of JOSEPHINE or JOHANNA.
name: JOEY

meaning: Scandinavian and Dutch form of Iohannes (see JOHN).
name: JOHAN

meaning: Form of Yochanan (see JOHN) used in the English Old Testament. It was the name of a military leader in the time of the prophet Jeremiah.
name: JOHANAN

meaning: German form of Iohannes (see JOHN). Famous bearers include German composer Johann Sebastian Bach (1685-1750), German novelist and poet Johann Goethe (1749-1832), and Austrian composers Johann Strauss the Elder (1804-1849) and his son Johann Strauss the Younger (1825-1899).
name: JOHANN
JOHANNA
origin: [German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Dutch, Hungarian, Finnish, Estonian, English, Late Roman]

meaning: Latin form of Ioannes (see JOHN). Notable bearers include the inventor of the printing press Johannes Gutenberg (1398-1468), astronomer Johannes Kepler (1571-1630) and composer Johannes Brahms (1833-1897).

meaning: English form of Iohannes, the Latin form of the Greek name Ιωαννης (Ioannes), itself derived from the Hebrew name יוֹחָנָן (Yochanan) meaning "YAHWEH is gracious". The Hebrew form occurs in the Old Testament (spelled Johanan or Jehohanan in the English version), but this name owes its popularity to two New Testament characters, both highly revered saints. The first is John the Baptist, a Jewish ascetic who is considered the forerunner of Jesus. He baptized Jesus and was later executed by Herod Antipas. The second is the apostle John, who is traditionally regarded as the author of the fourth gospel and Revelation. With the apostles Peter and James (his brother), he was part of the inner circle of Jesus.... [more]
name: JOHN

meaning: From the name of the river which flows between the countries of Jordan and Israel. The river's name in Hebrew is יַרְדֵן (Yarden), and it is derived from יָרַד (yarad) meaning "descend" or "flow down". In the New Testament John the Baptist baptizes Jesus Christ in its waters, and it was adopted as a personal name in Europe after crusaders brought water back from the river to baptize their children. There may have been some influence from the Germanic name JORDANES, notably borne by a 6th-century Gothic historian.... [more]

This name has been used in England since the Middle Ages, at which time it was also a feminine name (from Juliana, eventually becoming Gillian).

In the Old Testament Joseph is the eleventh son of Jacob and the first with his wife Rachel. Because he was the favourite of his father, his older brothers sent him to Egypt and told their father that he had died. In Egypt, Joseph became an advisor to the pharaoh, and was eventually reconciled with his brothers when they came to Egypt during a famine. This name also occurs in the New Testament, belonging to Saint Joseph the husband of Mary, and to Joseph of Arimathea.... [more]

After Moses died Joshua succeeded him as leader of the Israelites and he led the conquest of Canaan. His original name was Hoshea.... [more]

meaning: From the medieval masculine name Josse, which was derived from the earlier Iudocus, which was a Latinized form of the Breton name Judoc meaning "lord". The name belonged to a 7th-century Breton saint, and Breton settlers introduced it to England after the Norman conquest. It became rare after the 14th century, but was later revived as a feminine name, perhaps because of similarity to the Middle English word joise "to rejoice". This given name also formed the basis for a surname, as in the case of the Irish novelist James Joyce (1882-1941).

An explanation for his name is given in Genesis 29:35. His tribe eventually formed the Kingdom of Judah in the south of Israel. King David and Jesus were among the descendants of him and his wife Tamar. This name was also borne by Judah Maccabee, the Jewish priest who revolted against Seleucid rule in the 2nd century BC, as told in the Books of Maccabees.... [more]

The name was also borne by a 20th-century queen of the Netherlands. In England, this form has been in use since the 18th century, alongside the older form Gillian.

meaning: From a Roman family name which was possibly derived from Greek ιουλος (ioulos) meaning "downy-bearded". Alternatively, it could be related to the name of the Roman god JUPITER. This was a prominent patrician family of Rome, who claimed descent from the mythological Julus, son of Aeneas. Its most notable member was Gaius Julius Caesar, who gained renown as a military leader for his clever conquest of Gaul. After a civil war he became the dictator of the Roman Republic, but was eventually stabbed to death in the senate.... [more]

meaning: Roman family name which was possibly derived from the name of the Roman goddess JUNO. It was borne by Lucius Junius Brutus, the founder of the Roman Republic in the 6th century BC. It was also borne by the 1st-century BC Roman politician Marcus Junius Brutus, commonly known as Brutus, who was one of the assassins of Julius Caesar.
name: JUNIUS

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly related to an Indo-European root meaning "youth", or possibly of Etruscan origin. In Roman mythology Juno was the wife of Jupiter and the queen of the heavens. She was the protectress of marriage and women, and was also the goddess of finance.

Jupiter was the supreme god in Roman mythology. He presided over the heavens and light, and was responsible for the protection and laws of the Roman state. This is also the name of the fifth and largest planet in the solar system.

meaning: From the Latin name Iustinus, which was derived from JUSTUS. As an English name, it has occasionally been used since the late Middle Ages, though it did not become common until the 20th century. Famous modern bearers include pop stars Justin Timberlake (1981-) and Justin Bieber (1994-).
