meaning: From Japanese 凛 (rin) meaning "dignified, severe, cold" or other kanji which are pronounced the same way.
name: RIN

meaning: From Japanese 莉 (ri) meaning "white jasmine" or 里 (ri) meaning "village" combined with 奈 (na), a phonetic character, or 菜 (na) meaning "vegetables, greens". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: RINA  (4)

meaning: Tatar and Bashkir form of RENAT.
name: RINAT  (1)

meaning: Diminutive of MARINUS, MARINA or CATHARINA.
name: RINI

meaning: Means "river" in Spanish or Portuguese. A city in Brazil bears this name. Its full name is Rio de Janeiro, which means "river of January", so named because the first explorers came to the harbour in January and mistakenly thought it was a river mouth.
name: RIO  (1)

meaning: Derived from Irish ríoghan meaning "queen". In Irish legend this was a wife of the Irish king Niall.
name: RÍOGHNACH

meaning: Either a variant of RÍOGHNACH or a short form of CATRIONA.
name: RÍONA

meaning: Means "sage, poet" in Sanskrit, perhaps ultimately deriving from a root meaning "to see".
name: RISHI

meaning: Derived from Irish rath "grace, prosperity" combined with a diminutive suffix.
name: RATHNAIT

meaning: Means "rest, pleasure" in Sanskrit. This is the name of the wife of the Hindu god of love Kama.
name: RATI

meaning: Diminutive of names beginning with the Slavic element rati meaning "war, battle".
name: RATKO

meaning: From the name of a variety of jasmine flower, the night jasmine, ultimately from a poetic word meaning "night".
name: RATREE

meaning: Either an elaboration of RAVEN, or else from the name of the city of Ravenna in Italy.
name: RAVENNA

meaning: Variant of RAVINDRA used by Sikhs.
name: RAVINDER

meaning: Means "storyteller", derived from Arabic روى (rawa) "to relate".
name: RAWIYA

meaning: Short form of RAYMOND, often used as an independent name. It coincides with an English word meaning "beam of light". Science-fiction author Ray Bradbury (1920-2012) and musician Ray Charles (1930-2004) are two notable bearers of the name.
name: RAY

meaning: Means "basil" in Arabic. This was the name of a wife of the Prophet Muhammad.
name: RAYHANA

meaning: Combination of RAY and the popular name suffix lene.
name: RAYLENE

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of RAYMOND.
name: RAYMUNDO

meaning: From the Germanic name Raganhar, composed of the elements ragin "advice" and hari "army". The Normans brought this name to England where it came into general use, though it was rare by the end of the Middle Ages.
name: RAYNER

meaning: Means "watered, luxuriant" in Arabic. According to Islamic tradition this is the name of one of the gates of paradise.
name: RAYYAN

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly related to the name RADOVAN. Alternatively it may have been brought to Romania from India by Gypsies, and may mean something like "bringer of good news".
name: RĂZVAN

meaning: From a surname which was a variant of REED.
name: READ

meaning: Cognate of REBECCA. It is also the form used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: REBEKKA
origin: [German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Icelandic, Faroese, Finnish, Biblical Greek]

meaning: From the English word, ultimately derived from Old English read. It was originally a nickname given to a person with red hair or a ruddy complexion.
name: RED

meaning: Elaboration of REGAN, influenced by REGINA.
name: REGANA

meaning: Means "queen" in Latin (or Italian). It was in use as a Christian name from early times, and was borne by a 2nd-century saint. In England it was used during the Middle Ages in honour of the Virgin Mary, and it was later revived in the 19th century. A city in Canada bears this name, in honour of Queen Victoria.
name: REGINA
origin: [English, German, Italian, Spanish, Portuguese, Lithuanian, Polish, Czech, Hungarian, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Late Roman]

meaning: From a surname meaning "ruler" in Occitan. This name is often given in honour of Saint Jean-François Régis, a 17th-century French Jesuit priest.
name: RÉGIS

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of REGULUS.
name: RÉGULO

meaning: From a surname which is a Scots variant of REED.
name: REID

meaning: From the Old Norse name Hreiðunn which was derived from the elements hreiðr "nest, home" and unnr "to wave, to billow".
name: REIDUN

meaning: From an Irish surname which was derived from the given name Raghailleach, meaning unknown.
name: REILLY

meaning: From a Germanic name which was composed of the elements ragin "advice" and brand "sword". This name belonged to the 17th-century Dutch painter Rembrandt van Rijn.
name: REMBRANDT

meaning: Means "remedy" in Catalan, a Catalan equivalent of REMEDIOS.
name: REMEI

meaning: Means "mercy of God" in Hebrew. The Book of Enoch names him as one of the seven archangels.
name: REMIEL

meaning: French form of the Latin name Remigius, which was derived from Latin remigis "oarsman". Saint Rémy was a 5th-century bishop who converted and baptized Clovis, king of the Franks.
name: RÉMY

meaning: French form of REYNARD. Because of the medieval character Reynard the Fox, renard became a French word meaning "fox".
name: RENARD

meaning: Hungarian, Czech and Slovak feminine form of RENATUS.
name: RENÁTA

meaning: German, Dutch and Norwegian feminine form of RENATUS.
name: RENATE

meaning: English form of RENÉ or RENÉE.
name: RENE

meaning: Short form of LAURENS or EMERENS.
name: RENS

meaning: Means "silk", from Hindi रेशम (Resham) and Bengali রেশম (Resham), ultimately of Persian origin.
name: RESHMI

meaning: Means "of Rhaetia". Rhaetia is a region in eastern Switzerland that got its name from the Rhaeti, a Celtic tribe who originally inhabited the area.
name: RETO

meaning: Means "friend of God" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is another name for Jethro. The fantasy author John Ronald Reuel Tolkien (1892-1973) was a famous bearer.
name: REUEL

meaning: Possibly of Persian origin meaning "wealthy, successful".
name: REVAZ

meaning: From Latin rex "king". It has been used as a given name since the 19th century.
name: REX

meaning: Variant of ROXANE influenced by REX.
name: REXANNE

meaning: Turkish and Uyghur form of RAYHANA.
name: REYHAN

meaning: From the Germanic name Raginhard, composed of the elements ragin "advice" and hard "brave, hardy". The Normans brought it to England in the form Reinard, though it never became very common there. In medieval fables the name was borne by the sly hero Reynard the Fox (with the result that renard has become a French word meaning "fox").
name: REYNARD

meaning: From the Germanic name Raginald, composed of the elements ragin "advice" and wald "rule". The Normans (who used forms like Reinald or Reinold) brought the name to Britain, where it reinforced rare Old English and Norse cognates already in existence. It was common during the Middle Ages, but became more rare after the 15th century.
name: REYNOLD

meaning: Possibly derived from the name of the Hebridean island Rona, which means "rough island" in Gaelic.
name: RHONA

meaning: Means either "fair spear" or "fair hair" in Welsh. The first element is either rhon "spear" or rhawn "(coarse) hair", and the second element is gwen "fair, white, blessed".
name: RHONWEN

meaning: Means "reddish brown" in Welsh. It is sometimes used as a Welsh form of RODERICK.
name: RHYDDERCH

meaning: Means "praise, verse, sacred text" in Sanskrit.
name: RICHA

meaning: Means "brave power", derived from the Germanic elements ric "power, rule" and hard "brave, hardy". The Normans introduced this name to Britain, and it has been very common there since that time. It was borne by three kings of England including Richard I the Lionheart, one of the leaders of the Third Crusade in the 12th century.... [more]
name: RICHARD
origin: [English, French, German, Czech, Slovak, Dutch, Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Feminine form of RICHARD using the popular suffix elle, probably influenced by the sound of MICHELLE.
name: RICHELLE

meaning: Meaning uncertain, possibly a combination of RICHARD and MARY. This name has been used since at least the late 18th century, mainly confined to the town of Bury in Lancashire.
name: RICHMAL

meaning: Means "satisfaction, contentment" in Arabic. This name was borne by Ali Musi al-Ridha, a 9th-century Shia imam.
name: RIDHA

meaning: Reconstructed old Celtic form of RHIANNON.
name: RIGANTONA

meaning: Derived from Arabic الرجل (al-Rijl) meaning "foot". This is the name of the star that forms the left foot of the constellation Orion.
name: RIGEL

meaning: Finnish short form of FREDRIKA, HENRIIKKA and other names ending in rika.
name: RIIKKA

meaning: Short form of FREDRIKA, HENRIKA, and other names ending in rika.
name: RIKA

meaning: German short form of FRIEDERIKE, HENRIKE, and other names ending in rike.
name: RIKE

meaning: From Japanese 莉 (ri) meaning "white jasmine" or 理 (ri) meaning "reason, logic" combined with 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: RIKO

meaning: From Japanese 陸 (riku) meaning "land" or different kanji which are pronounced the same way.
name: RIKU  (2)

meaning: From a surname which comes from two distinct sources. As an Irish surname it is a variant of REILLY. As an English surname it is derived from a place name meaning "rye clearing" in Old English.
name: RILEY

meaning: Short form of CATERINA or CATHARINA as well as other names ending in rina.
name: RINA  (1)

meaning: Italian form of REYNOLD. This is the Italian name of the hero Renaud, a character in several Renaissance epics.
name: RINALDO

meaning: Short form of names ending in rino.
name: RINO

meaning: Diminutive of MARINUS, MARINA or CATHARINA.
name: RINY

meaning: From Japanese 莉 (ri) meaning "white jasmine" or 里 (ri) meaning "village" combined with 央 (o) meaning "center", 緒 (o) meaning "thread" or 桜 (o) meaning "cherry blossom". Other kanji combinations are also possible.
name: RIO  (2)

meaning: From Irish rí "king" combined with a diminutive suffix.
name: RÍOGHNÁN

meaning: From a surname which originally came from a place name that meant "strip clearing" in Old English.
name: RIPLEY

meaning: Finnish and Macedonian short form of CHRISTOPHER.
name: RISTO

meaning: Urdu form and variant Arabic transcription of RIDWANA.
name: RIZWANA

meaning: From the Germanic name Hrodebert meaning "bright fame", derived from the Germanic elements hrod "fame" and beraht "bright". The Normans introduced this name to Britain, where it replaced the Old English cognate Hreodbeorht. It has been a very common English name since that time.... [more]
name: ROBERT
origin: [English, French, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, German, Dutch, Czech, Polish, Russian, Slovene, Croatian, Romanian, Ancient Germanic]

meaning: Medieval diminutive of ROBERT. Robin Hood was a legendary hero and archer of medieval England who stole from the rich to give to the poor. In modern times it has also been used as a feminine name, and it may sometimes be given in reference to the red-breasted bird.
name: ROBIN

meaning: Germanic name derived from the element hrok meaning "rest". This was the name of a 14th-century French saint who nursed victims of the plague but eventually contracted the disease himself. He is the patron saint of the sick.
name: ROCCO

meaning: From the name of the French city La Rochelle, meaning "little rock". It first became commonly used as a given name in America in the 1930s, probably due to the fame of actress Rochelle Hudson (1914-1972) and because of the similarity to the name Rachel.
name: ROCHELLE

meaning: Means "dew" in Spanish. It is taken from the title of the Virgin Mary María del Rocío meaning "Mary of the Dew".
name: ROCÍO

meaning: Short form of RODERICK or RODNEY.
name: ROD

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of RUDOLF. This is the name of the hero in Puccini's opera 'La Bohème' (1896).
name: RODOLFO

meaning: Short form of ROELAND or ROELOF.
name: ROEL

meaning: Spanish form of the Late Latin name Rogelius, which was possibly derived from the name Rogatus, which was itself derived from Latin rogatus "request".
name: ROGELIO

meaning: From the novel 'The Lord of the Rings' (1954) by J. R. R. Tolkien, where it is a place name meaning "horse country" in Sindarin.
name: ROHAN  (2)

meaning: Latinized form of the medieval name Rohese (see ROSE).
name: ROHESIA

meaning: Russian and Polish form of ROXANA.
name: ROKSANA

meaning: From Japanese 六 (roku) meaning "six" and 郎 (rou) meaning "son". This name was traditionally given to the sixth son. Other combinations of kanji characters can be possible.
name: ROKUROU

meaning: From the Germanic name Hrolf (or its Old Norse cognate Hrólfr), a contracted form of Hrodulf (see RUDOLF). The Normans introduced this name to England but it soon became rare. In the modern era it has occasionally been used in the English-speaking world as a German import.
name: ROLF

meaning: Latinized form of Roul, the Old French form of ROLF. Rollo (or Rolf) the Ganger was an exiled Viking who, in the 10th century, became the first Duke of Normandy. It has been used as a given name in the English-speaking world since the 19th century.
name: ROLLO

meaning: Hungarian feminine form of Romanus (see ROMAN).
name: ROMÁNA

meaning: French feminine form of Romanus (see ROMAN).
name: ROMANE

meaning: Italian form of the Late Latin name Romaeus meaning "a pilgrim to Rome". Romeo is best known as the lover of Juliet in Shakespeare's tragedy 'Romeo and Juliet' (1596).
name: ROMEO

meaning: Means "famous battle" from the Germanic elements hrom "fame" and hild "battle".
name: ROMILDA

meaning: Means "of Rome" in Latin. In Roman legend Romulus and Remus were the founders of the city of Rome.
name: ROMULUS

meaning: Scottish form of RAGNVALDR, a name introduced to Scotland by Scandinavian settlers and invaders. It became popular outside Scotland during the 20th century. A famous bearer was American actor and president Ronald Reagan (1911-2004).
name: RONALD

meaning: Portuguese form of RONALD. A notable bearer is the retired Brazilian soccer player Ronaldo Luís Nazário de Lima (1976-), who is commonly known only by his first name.
name: RONALDO

meaning: From Chinese 荣 (róng) meaning "glory, honour, flourish, prosper", 融 (róng) meaning "fuse, harmonize" or 容 (róng) meaning "appearance, form" (which is usually only feminine). Other Chinese characters can form this name as well.
name: RONG

meaning: Invented by Swedish children's author Astrid Lindgren, who based it on the middle portion of Juronjaure, the name of a lake in Sweden. Lindgren used it in her book 'Ronia the Robber's Daughter' (Ronia is the English translation).
name: RONJA

meaning: From a Dutch surname meaning "rose field". This name is often given in honour of American presidents Theodore Roosevelt (1858-1919) or Franklin D. Roosevelt (1882-1945).
name: ROOSEVELT

meaning: From the older Irish name Ríoghbhardán, which meant "little poet king" from Irish Gaelic ríogh "king" combined with bard "poet" and a diminutive suffix.
name: RÓRDÁN

meaning: Generally this can be considered a Latin form of ROSE, though originally it may have come from the Germanic name ROZA  (2). This was the name of a 13th-century saint from Viterbo in Italy. In the English-speaking world it was first used in the 19th century. A famous bearer was civil rights activist Rosa Parks (1913-2005).
name: ROSA  (1)
origin: [Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Dutch, German, English]

meaning: Combination of ROSA  (1) and the popular name suffix bel. It was created in the 18th century.
name: ROSABEL

meaning: Variant of ROSALINE. James Clarence Mangan used it as a translation for RÓISÍN in his poem 'Dark Rosaleen' (1846).
name: ROSALEEN

meaning: Spanish and Galician form of ROSALIA.
name: ROSALÍA

meaning: French, German and Dutch form of ROSALIA. In the English-speaking this name received a boost after the release of the movie 'Rosalie' (1938), which was based on an earlier musical.
name: ROSALIE

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements hros "horse" and mund "protection". The Normans introduced this name to England. It was subsequently influenced by the Latin phrase rosa munda "pure rose". This was the name of the mistress of Henry II, the king of England in the 12th century. She was possibly murdered by his wife, Eleanor of Aquitaine.
name: ROSAMUND

meaning: Means "rosary", and is taken from the Spanish title of the Virgin Mary Nuestra Señora del Rosario meaning "Our Lady of the Rosary". This name is feminine in Spanish and masculine in Italian.
name: ROSARIO

meaning: Originally a Norman form of a Germanic name, which was composed of the elements hrod "fame" and heid "kind, sort, type". The Normans introduced it to England in the forms Roese and Rohese. From an early date it was associated with the word for the fragrant flower rose (derived from Latin rosa). When the name was revived in the 19th century, it was probably with the flower in mind.
name: ROSE

meaning: Spanish form of a Visigothic name composed of the Germanic elements hrod "fame" and sinths "path". This was the name of a 10th-century Galician saint, also known as Rudesind.
name: ROSENDO

meaning: Possibly means "light of the assembly" in Persian. This was the name of a daughter of the 17th-century Mughal emperor Shah Jahan.
name: ROSHANARA

meaning: From Hindi and Marathi रौशनी (raushani) meaning "light, brightness", ultimately of Persian origin.
name: ROSHNI

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements rasti "growth" and slava "glory".
name: ROSTISLAV

meaning: From a surname which was derived from an Old English place name meaning "horse spring".
name: ROSWELL

meaning: From an Irish surname, an Anglicized form of Ó Ruadháin meaning "descendant of RUADHÁN". This name can also be given in reference to the rowan tree.
name: ROWAN

meaning: Meaning uncertain, possibly a Latinized form of a Germanic name derived from the elements hrod "fame" and wunn "joy, bliss". According to the 12th-century chronicler Geoffrey of Monmouth, this was the name of a daughter of the Saxon chief Hengist. It was popularized by Sir Walter Scott, who used it for a character in his novel 'Ivanhoe' (1819).
name: ROWENA

meaning: Latin form of Ρωξανη (Roxane), the Greek form of the Persian or Bactrian name روشنک (Roshanak) which meant "bright" or "dawn". This was the name of Alexander the Great's first wife, a daughter of the Bactrian nobleman Oxyartes. In the modern era it came into use during the 17th century. In the English-speaking world it was popularized by Daniel Defoe, who used it in his novel 'Roxana' (1724).
name: ROXANA

meaning: From a Turkish nickname meaning "Ruthenian". This referred to the region of Ruthenia, covering Belarus, Ukraine and western Russia. Roxelana (1502-1558), also known by the name Hürrem, was a slave and then concubine of Süleyman the Magnificent, sultan of the Ottoman Empire. She eventually became his wife and produced his heir, Selim II.
name: ROXELANA

meaning: From the English word royal, derived (via Old French) from Latin regalis, a derivative of rex "king". It was first used as a given name in the 19th century.
name: ROYAL

meaning: From a surname which was derived from the medieval given name Royse, a variant of ROSE.
name: ROYCE

meaning: From a surname which was derived from a place name meaning "rye hill" from Old English ryge "rye" and hyll "hill".
name: ROYLE

meaning: From a surname which was originally taken from an Old English place name meaning "town of Royse". The given name Royse was a medieval variant of ROSE.
name: ROYSTON

meaning: Means "rose" in Polish. It is a cognate of ROSA  (1).
name: RÓŻA

meaning: Means "rose" in some Slavic languages. It is a cognate of ROSA  (1).
name: ROZA  (1)

meaning: Polish and Romanian form of ROSALIA.
name: ROZALIA

meaning: Means "rose" in Lithuanian. It is a cognate of ROSA  (1).
name: ROŽĖ

meaning: Gaelic byname meaning "red", often a nickname for one with red hair. This was the nickname of the Scottish outlaw Raibeart Ruadh MacGregor (1671-1734), known as Rob Roy in English.
name: RUADH

meaning: Means "red king" from Irish ruadh "red" combined with rí "king". This was the name of the last high king of Ireland, reigning in the 12th century.
name: RUAIDHRÍ

meaning: Probably an Irish form of HRŒREKR, introduced by Scandinavian settlers and invaders. Alternatively it may be derived from Irish ruarc "squall, rainstorm".
name: RUARC

meaning: Scandinavian, Dutch, French and Armenian form of REUBEN. This was the name of an 11th-century Armenian ruler of Cilicia.
name: RUBEN
origin: [Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Dutch, French, Armenian, Biblical Latin]

meaning: Brazilian Portuguese variant form of REUBEN.
name: RUBENS

meaning: Diminutive of RÚBEN, RUBEM or RUBENS.
name: RUBINHO

meaning: From the Germanic name Hrodulf, which was derived from the elements hrod "fame" and wulf "wolf". It was borne by three kings of Burgundy, as well as several Habsburg rulers of the Holy Roman Empire and Austria. Anthony Hope used this name for the hero in his popular novel 'The Prisoner of Zenda' (1894).
name: RUDOLF
origin: [German, Dutch, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Polish, Czech, Hungarian, Slovene, Croatian, Russian, Armenian]

meaning: Short form of MARGHERITA and other names ending in rita. A famous bearer was American actress Rita Hayworth (1918-1987).
name: RITA
origin: [Italian, English, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, German, Hungarian, Spanish, Portuguese]

meaning: Means either "movement, stream" or "brass" in Sanskrit.
name: RITIKA

meaning: From the English word that denotes a flowing body of water. The word is ultimately derived (via Old French) from Latin ripa "riverbank".
name: RIVER

meaning: Urdu form and variant Arabic transcription of RIDWAN.
name: RIZWAN

meaning: Modern form of the Old Norse name Hróðvaldr or Hróaldr, composed of the elements hróðr "fame" and valdr "ruler". This name was borne by the children's author Roald Dahl (1916-1990).
name: ROALD

meaning: Hungarian and Icelandic form of ROBERT.
name: RÓBERT

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of ROBERT. Saint Roberto Bellarmine was a 16th-century cardinal who is regarded as a Doctor of the Church. Another famous bearer was Roberto de Nobili, a Jesuit missionary to India in the 17th century.
name: ROBERTO

meaning: Feminine form of ROBIN. It originated in Scotland in the 17th century.
name: ROBINA

meaning: French and Polish form of ROCCO.
name: ROCH

meaning: Latinized form of ROCCO, used in occasionally German and Dutch.
name: ROCHUS

meaning: Diminutive of ROCCO or other names beginning with a similar sound, or else a nickname referring to a tough person. This is the name of a boxer played by Sylvester Stallone in the movie 'Rocky' (1976) and its five sequels.
name: ROCKY

meaning: Means "famous power" from the Germanic elements hrod "fame" and ric "power". This name was in use among the Visigoths; it was borne by their last king (also known as Rodrigo), who died fighting the Muslim invaders of Spain in the 8th century. It also had cognates in Old Norse and West Germanic, and Scandinavian settlers and Normans introduced it to England, though it died out after the Middle Ages. It was revived in the English-speaking world by Sir Walter Scott's poem 'The Vision of Don Roderick' (1811).
name: RODERICK

meaning: From a surname, originally derived from a place name, which meant "Hroda's island" in Old English (where Hroda is a Germanic given name meaning "fame"). It was first used as a given name in honour of the British admiral Lord Rodney (1719-1792).
name: RODNEY

meaning: Spanish, Portuguese and Italian form of RODERICK. A notable bearer was Rodrigo Díaz de Vivar, also known as El Cid, an 11th-century Spanish military commander.
name: RODRIGO

meaning: Means "famous spear" from the Germanic elements hrod "fame" and ger "spear". The Normans brought this name to England, where it replaced the Old English cognate Hroðgar (the name of the Danish king in the Anglo-Saxon epic 'Beowulf'). It was a common name in England during the Middle Ages. By the 18th century it was rare, but it was revived in following years. The name was borne by the Norman lords Roger I, who conquered Sicily in the 11th century, and his son Roger II, who ruled Sicily as a king.
name: ROGER
origin: [English, French, Catalan, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, German, Dutch]

name: ROHIT
origin: [Indian, Hindi, Marathi, Bengali, Odia, Gujarati, Kannada, Telugu, Nepali]

meaning: From the Germanic elements hrod meaning "fame" and land meaning "land", though some theories hold that the second element was originally nand meaning "brave". Roland was a semi-legendary French hero whose story is told in the medieval epic 'La Chanson de Roland', in which he is a nephew of Charlemagne killed in battle with the Saracens. The Normans introduced this name to England.
name: ROLAND
origin: [English, French, German, Swedish, Dutch, Hungarian, Medieval French]

meaning: Spanish, Italian and Portuguese form of ROLAND.
name: ROLANDO

meaning: From the name of the Italian city, commonly called Rome in English.
name: ROMA  (2)

meaning: French feminine form of Romanus (see ROMAN).
name: ROMAINE

meaning: From the Late Latin name Romanus which meant "Roman".
name: ROMAN
origin: [Russian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Ukrainian, Slovene, Croatian, German]

name: ROMANA
origin: [Italian, Polish, Slovene, Croatian, Czech, Slovak, Late Roman]

meaning: Means "little seal", derived from Irish rón "seal" combined with a diminutive suffix.
name: RÓNÁN

meaning: Derived from Hebrew רוֹן (ron) meaning "song, joy".
name: RONEN

meaning: Means "my joy" or "my song" in Hebrew.
name: RONI  (1)

meaning: Frisian short form of Germanic names beginning with the element hraban meaning "raven".
name: RONNE

meaning: Dutch vernacular form of ROSA  (1), meaning "rose" in Dutch.
name: ROOS

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of ROCCO.
name: ROQUE

meaning: Short form of ROSALIND, ROSAMUND, and other names beginning with Ros.
name: ROS

meaning: Italian name meaning "white rose", derived from Latin rosa "rose" and alba "white". A famous bearer was the Venetian painter Rosalba Carriera (1675-1757).
name: ROSALBA

meaning: Late Latin name derived from rosa "rose". This was the name of a 12th-century Sicilian saint.
name: ROSALIA

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements hros "horse" and linde "soft, tender". The Normans introduced this name to England, though it was not common. During the Middle Ages its spelling was influenced by the Latin phrase rosa linda "beautiful rose". The name was popularized by Edmund Spencer, who used it in his poetry, and by William Shakespeare, who used it for the heroine in his comedy 'As You Like It' (1599).
name: ROSALIND

meaning: Medieval variant of ROSALIND. This is the name of characters in Shakespeare's 'Love's Labour's Lost' (1594) and 'Romeo and Juliet' (1596).
name: ROSALINE

meaning: Variant of ROSALINE using the popular name suffix lyn.
name: ROSALYN

meaning: Variant of ROSAMUND, in use since the Middle Ages.
name: ROSAMOND

meaning: From an English surname, originally derived from a place name, which meant "doe wood" in Old Norse.
name: ROSCOE

meaning: Combination of ROSE and MARY. This name can also be given in reference to the herb, which gets its name from Latin ros marinus meaning "dew of the sea". It came into use as a given name in the 19th century.
name: ROSEMARY

meaning: Italian diminutive of ROSA  (1). This is the name of a character in Rossini's opera 'The Barber of Seville' (1816).
name: ROSINA

meaning: From a Scottish and English surname which originally indicated a person from a place called Ross (such as the region of Ross in northern Scotland), derived from Gaelic ros meaning "promontory, headland". name: SAYYID

meaning: From a surname which denoted a person who sold or made clothes made of scarlet (a kind of cloth, ultimately derived from Persian سقرلاط (saghrilat)). Margaret Mitchell used this name for Scarlett O'Hara, the main character in her novel 'Gone with the Wind' (1936). Scarlett's name came from her grandmother's maiden name.
name: SCARLETT

meaning: From the English word scout meaning "one who gathers information covertly", which is derived from Old French escouter "to listen". Harper Lee used this name in her novel 'To Kill a Mockingbird' (1960).
name: SCOUT

meaning: From the Latin name Sebastianus which meant "from Sebaste". Sebaste was the name a town in Asia Minor, its name deriving from Greek σεβαστος (sebastos) "venerable" (a translation of Latin Augustus, the title of the Roman emperors). According to Christian tradition, Saint Sebastian was a 3rd-century Roman soldier martyred during the persecutions of the emperor Diocletian. After he was discovered to be a Christian, he was tied to a stake and shot with arrows. This however did not kill him. Saint Irene of Rome healed him and he returned to personally admonish Diocletian, whereupon the emperor had him beaten to death.... [more]
name: SEBASTIAN
origin: [German, English, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Polish, Finnish, Romanian]

meaning: French feminine form of Sebastianus (see SEBASTIAN).
name: SÉBASTIENNE

meaning: Roman praenomen, or given name, which meant "second" in Latin.
name: SECUNDUS

meaning: Tamil form of SITA. The name of the mythological figures is சீதை, while சீதா is the spelling used for people.
name: SEETHA

meaning: From a surname which was derived from a place name meaning "town in the rushes" in Old English.
name: SEFTON

meaning: Possibly a French form of SIEGLINDE.
name: SÉGOLÈNE

meaning: Derived from Finnish seijas meaning "tranquil, serene".
name: SEIJA

meaning: Means "rock" in Hebrew. This was the name of a city, the capital of Edom, in the Old Testament.
name: SELA

meaning: From an English surname which was from a place name meaning "willow farm" in Old Norse.
name: SELBY

meaning: Mythology, GreekMeans "moon" in Greek. This was the name of a Greek goddess of the moon, sometimes identified with the goddess Artemis.
name: SELENE

meaning: Turkish form of SALIM. This was the name of three Ottoman sultans, including the father of Süleyman the Magnificent.
name: SELİM

meaning: Possibly a variant of CÉLINE or SELENE. As an English name, it first came into use in the 17th century.
name: SELINA

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from an Old English given name, which was formed of the elements sele "manor" and wine "friend".
name: SELWYN

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly of Phrygian origin. In Greek mythology she was one of the many lovers of Zeus. Hera, being jealous, tricked Semele into asking Zeus to display himself in all his splendour as the god of thunder. When he did, Semele was struck by lightning and died, but not before giving birth to Dionysos.
name: SEMELE

meaning: Sometimes explained as an anagram of AGNES, but more likely derived from Gaelic seang "slender".
name: SENGA

meaning: From Sino-Korean 瑞 (seo) meaning "felicitous omen, auspicious" combined with 賢 (hyeon) meaning "virtuous, worthy, able". Other combinations of hanja characters can form this name as well.
name: SEO-HYEON

meaning: From Sino-Korean 瑞 (seo) meaning "felicitous omen, auspicious" or 舒 (seo) meaning "open up, unfold, comfortable, easy" combined with 俊 (jun) meaning "talented, handsome". This name can also be formed from other character combinations.
name: SEO-JUN

meaning: Anglicized form of SEONAG or SEÒNAID.
name: SEONA

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded" or 盛 (seong) meaning "abundant, flourishing" combined with 鎬 (ho) meaning "stove, bright" or 晧 (ho) meaning "daybreak, bright". Many other hanja character combinations are possible.
name: SEONG-HO

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded" combined with 鉉 (hyeon), which refers to a device used to lift a tripod cauldron. Other hanja character combinations are possible.
name: SEONG-HYEON

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded" or 性 (seong) meaning "nature, character, sex" combined with 敏 (min) meaning "quick, clever, sharp" or 旻 (min) meaning "quick, clever, sharp". Many other hanja character combinations are possible.
name: SEONG-MIN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 瑞 (seo) meaning "felicitous omen, auspicious" and 潤 (yun) meaning "soft, sleek", as well as other hanja character combinations.
name: SEO-YUN

meaning: Finnish diminutive of SEPPO  (1) or SEBASTIAN.
name: SEPI

meaning: Derived from Finnish seppä "smith". Seppo Ilmarinen ("the smith Ilmarinen") was the name of a master craftsman in the Finnish epic the 'Kalevala'.
name: SEPPO  (1)

meaning: From the name of the ninth month (though it means "seventh month" in Latin, since it was originally the seventh month of the Roman year), which is sometimes used as a given name for someone born in September.
name: SEPTEMBER

meaning: Roman family name which was derived from SEPTIMUS.
name: SEPTIMIUS

meaning: From the name of huge trees that grow in California. The tree got its name from the Cherokee scholar Sequoya (also known as George Guess), the inventor of the Cherokee alphabet.
name: SEQUOIA

meaning: Russian and Macedonian form of SERAPHINA.
name: SERAFIMA

meaning: Italian, Portuguese, Spanish and Polish form of SERAPHINA.
name: SERAFINA

meaning: Means "YAHWEH is ruler" in Hebrew. This is the name of several minor characters in the Old Testament, including the father of Ezra.
name: SERAIAH

meaning: Feminine form of the Late Latin name Seraphinus, derived from the biblical word seraphim which was Hebrew in origin and meant "fiery ones". The seraphim were an order of angels, described by Isaiah in the Bible as having six wings each. This was the name of a 13th-century Italian saint who made clothes for the poor. As an English name, it has never been common.
name: SERAPHINA

meaning: From the English word meaning "serenity, tranquility", ultimately from Latin serenus meaning "clear, calm".
name: SERENITY

meaning: Russian and Bulgarian form of SERGIUS.
name: SERGEY

meaning: Means "leader, chief" from Turkish ser "head, top" and kan "blood".
name: SERKAN

meaning: Dutch form of the Late Latin name Servatius, derived from servatus "saved, redeemed". This was the name of a 4th-century saint who helped spread Christianity to the Low Countries.
name: SERVAAS

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit संजीव (sanjiva) meaning "living, reviving".
name: SANJIV
origin: [Indian, Hindi, Marathi, Gujarati, Punjabi, Telugu, Kannada]

meaning: Short form of SUSANNA. It can also be derived from Swedish sann meaning "true".
name: SANNA

meaning: Means "saint" in Italian, ultimately from Latin sanctus.
name: SANTO

meaning: Form of SAUL used in the Greek Old Testament.
name: SAOUL

meaning: From the name of the gemstone, the blue birthstone of September, which is derived from Greek σαπφειρος (sappheiros), ultimately from the Hebrew word סַפִּיר (sappir).
name: SAPPHIRE
SARA
origin: [Greek, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Catalan, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Icelandic, Finnish, German, French, Dutch, Slovene, Croatian, Serbian, Macedonian, Polish, English, Arabic, Persian, Bosnian]

meaning: Means "my princess" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament, this was Sarah's name before God changed it (see Genesis 17:15).
name: SARAI

meaning: Means "possessing water" from Sanskrit सरस् (saras) meaning "fluid, water, lake" and वती (vati) meaning "having". This is the name of a Hindu river goddess, also associated with learning and the arts, who is the wife of Brahma.
name: SARASWATI

meaning: From a title meaning "chief, leader", derived from Persian sar "head, authority" and dar "possessor".
name: SARDAR

meaning: From the Akkadian name Sharru-kinu meaning "true king". This was the name (or title) of the first emperor of Akkad (23rd century BC). It was also borne by the 7th-century BC Assyrian king Sargon II, who named himself after the first Sargon.
name: SARGON

meaning: Possibly from an alternate reading of Hebrew שׂריה (see SERAIAH). In the Book of Mormon this is the name of Lehi's wife.
name: SARIAH

meaning: From a Sanskrit word referring to a type of thrush (species Turdus salica) or myna bird (species Gracula religiosa).
name: SARIKA

meaning: Biblical Greek and Latin form of SARAH.
name: SARRA
origin: [Biblical Greek, Biblical Latin, Old Church Slavic]

meaning: Croatian, Serbian and Slovene diminutive of ALEKSANDER or ALEKSANDRA.
name: SAŠA

meaning: Russian and Ukrainian diminutive of ALEKSANDR or ALEKSANDRA.
name: SASHA

meaning: Macedonian and Bulgarian diminutive of ALEKSANDRA.
name: SASHKA

meaning: Means "the moon" in Thai (a poetic word).
name: SASITHORN

meaning: Derived from Hebrew שָׂטָן (satan) meaning "adversary". This is the Hebrew name of the enemy of the Judeo-Christian god. In the New Testament he is also known by the title Devil (Diabolos in Greek).
name: SATAN

meaning: Means "truthful" in Sanskrit. In Hindu belief this was the name of a goddess, a wife of Shiva. After her death she was reborn as the goddess Parvati.
name: SATI

meaning: Means "lord of Sati" from the name of the Hindu goddess SATI combined with ईश (isha) meaning "ruler". This is another name for the Hindu god Shiva.
name: SATISHA

meaning: Feminine form of SATURNINUS. This was the name of a legendary saint who was supposedly martyred in northern France.
name: SATURNINA

meaning: Roman cognomen derived from the name of the Roman god Saturnus (see SATURN). This was the name of several early saints.
name: SATURNINUS

meaning: Masculine form of SAULĖ. This is also the Lithuanian form of SAUL.
name: SAULIUS

meaning: Serbian and Bulgarian form of SABAS.
name: SAVA

meaning: From the English word for the large grassy plain, ultimately deriving from the Taino (Native American) word zabana. It came into use as a given name in America in the 19th century. It was revived in the 1980s by the movie 'Savannah Smiles' (1982).
name: SAVANNAH

meaning: Means "relating to the sun" in Sanskrit. This is the name of a hymn dedicated to Savitr, a Hindu sun god, and it is also the name of his daughter. It is borne by several other characters in Hindu epics, including a wife of Brahma, a wife of Shiva, and a daughter of Daksha. In the Hindu epic the 'Mahabharata' it is borne by King Satyavan's wife, who successfully pleas with Yama, the god of death, to restore her husband to life.
name: SAVITRI

meaning: From a surname meaning "sawer of wood" in Middle English. Mark Twain used it for the hero in his novel 'The Adventures of Tom Sawyer' (1876).
name: SAWYER

meaning: From Japanese 沙 (sa) meaning "sand" or 紗 (sa) meaning "thread, silk" with 也 (ya) meaning "also" or 耶 (ya), an interjection, combined with 香 (ka) meaning "fragrance" or 加 (ka) meaning "increase". This name can also be composed of other kanji combinations. It is often written さやか using the hiragana writing system.
name: SAYAKA

meaning: From Japanese 小 (sa) meaning "small" and 百合 (yuri) meaning "lily". This name can also be composed of other kanji combinations.
name: SAYURI

meaning: Either a variant of SCARLETT or else from the English word for the red colour. The word is derived (via Old French and medieval Latin) from Persian سقرلاط (saghrilat), the name of a type of cloth.
name: SCARLET

meaning: Italian form of the Roman cognomen Scaevola, which was derived from Latin scaevus "left-handed". The first bearer of this name was Gaius Mucius Scaevola, who acquired it, according to legend, after he thrust his right hand into a blazing fire in order to intimidate the Etruscan king Porsenna, who was blockading the city of Rome.
name: SCEVOLA

meaning: From a Late Latin name which was derived from scholasticus meaning "rhetorician, orator". Saint Scholastica was a 6th-century Benedictine abbess, the sister of Saint Benedict of Nursia.
name: SCHOLASTICA

meaning: From a Dutch surname meaning "scholar". Dutch settlers brought the surname to America, where it was subsequently adopted as a given name in honour of the American general and senator Philip Schuyler (1733-1804).
name: SCHUYLER

meaning: Short form of PRISCILLA. This is also the Italian word for the squill flower (genus Scilla).
name: SCILLA

meaning: From an English and Scottish surname which referred to a person from Scotland or a person who spoke Scottish Gaelic. It is derived from Latin Scoti meaning "Gaelic speaker", with the ultimate origin uncertain.
name: SCOTT

meaning: Possibly an Irish form of SECUNDINUS. This was the name of a 5th-century Irish saint, also known as Secundinus.
name: SEACHNALL

meaning: Italian feminine form of Sebastianus (see SEBASTIAN).
name: SEBASTIANA

meaning: Slovene and Croatian form of Sebastianus (see SEBASTIAN).
name: SEBASTIJAN

meaning: Roman family name derived from the praenomen SECUNDUS. Saint Secundinus, also known as Seachnall, was a 5th-century assistant to Saint Patrick who became the first bishop of Dunshaughlin.
name: SECUNDINUS

meaning: Meaning unknown. This is the name of the Inuit goddess of the sea, sea animals and the underworld. According to some legends Sedna was originally a beautiful woman thrown into the ocean by her father.
name: SEDNA

meaning: Means "sword" in Swahili, ultimately from Arabic سيف (sayf).
name: SEFU

meaning: Telugu and Bengali form of SHEKHAR.
name: SEKHAR

meaning: From a Hebrew musical term which occurs many times in the Old Testament Psalms. It was probably meant to indicate a musical pause.
name: SELAH

meaning: Latinized form of SELENE. This name was borne by popular Mexican-American singer Selena Quintanilla (1971-1995), who was known simply as Selena.
name: SELENA

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Σελευκος (Seleukos), of unknown meaning. This was the name of one of Alexander the Great's generals, who established the Seleucid Empire in Western Asia after Alexander's death.
name: SELEUCUS

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly a short form of ANSELMA. It could also have been inspired by James Macpherson's 18th-century poems, in which it is the name of Ossian's castle.
name: SELMA
origin: [English, German, Dutch, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Icelandic]

meaning: Form of SHEM used in the Greek and Latin Old Testament.
name: SEM

meaning: Ukrainian form of SIMON, as well as a variant transcription of Russian SEMYON.
name: SEMEN

meaning: Means "little old person", derived from Old Irish sen "old" combined with a diminutive suffix. Saint Senán was a 6th-century monk from Munster, Ireland.
name: SENÁN

meaning: From a Roman cognomen which meant "old" from Latin senectus. This was the name of both a Roman orator (born in Spain) and also of his son, a philosopher and statesman. This name also coincides with that of the Seneca, a Native American tribe that lived near the Great Lakes, whose name meant "place of stones".
name: SENECA

meaning: From Sino-Korean 石 (seok) meaning "stone" or 錫 (seok) meaning "tin", as well as other characters which are pronounced the same way.
name: SEOK

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded", as well as other hanja characters with the same pronunciation. Although it does appear as a single-character name, it is more often used in combination with another character.
name: SEONG

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded" combined with 勛 (hun) meaning "meritorious deed, rank". Other hanja character combinations can form this name as well.
name: SEONG-HUN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded" or 星 (seong) meaning "star, planet" combined with 鎭 (jin) meaning "town, marketplace" or 震 (jin) meaning "shake, tremor, excite". Other hanja character combinations are also possible.
name: SEONG-JIN

meaning: From Sino-Korean 成 (seong) meaning "completed, finished, succeeded" or 聖 (seong) meaning "holy, sacred" combined with 洙 (su), which refers to a river in China. Many other hanja character combinations are possible.
name: SEONG-SU

meaning: From Sino-Korean 瑞 (seo) meaning "felicitous omen, auspicious" and 姢 (yeon) meaning "beautiful, graceful", besides other hanja character combinations.
name: SEO-YEON

meaning: Roman praenomen, or given name, which meant "seventh" in Latin.
name: SEPTIMUS

meaning: Either a variant of SARAH or a short form of SERAPHINA.
name: SERA

meaning: Russian, Romanian and Macedonian form of Seraphinus (see SERAPHINA).
name: SERAFIM

meaning: From a Late Latin name which was derived from Latin serenus meaning "clear, tranquil, serene". This name was borne by an obscure early saint. Edmund Spenser also used it in his poem 'The Faerie Queene' (1590).
name: SERENA

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of SERGIUS.
name: SERGIO

meaning: Roman family name, possibly meaning "servant" in Latin but most likely of unknown Etruscan origin. Saint Sergius was a 4th-century Roman officer who was martyred in Syria with his companion Bacchus. They are the patron saints of Christian desert nomads. Another saint by this name (in the Russian form Sergey) was a 14th-century Russian spiritual leader. The name was also borne by four popes.
name: SERGIUS

meaning: Derived from Turkish ser "head, top" and han, which is from the title khan meaning "leader".
name: SERHAN

meaning: Roman praenomen, or given name, meaning "to preserve" from Latin servo.
name: SERVIUS

meaning: Means "placed" or "appointed" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament he is the third named son of Adam and Eve. In England this name came into use after the Protestant Reformation.
name: SETH  (1)

meaning: Means "loyal friend", from Indonesian setia kawan.
name: SETIAWAN

meaning: Italian form of the Roman family name Septimius, which was derived from SEPTIMUS. Septimius Severus was an early 3rd-century Roman emperor. This was also the name of a 4th-century saint and martyr.
name: SETTIMIO

meaning: From Sino-Korean 昇 (seung) meaning "rise, ascent", 勝 (seung) meaning "victory, excel" or 承 (seung) meaning "inherit", as well as other characters which are pronounced similarly.
name: SEUNG

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of the Roman cognomen Severianus, which was derived from SEVERUS.
name: SEVERIANO

meaning: Roman family name which was derived from SEVERUS. Severinus was the name of many early saints, including a 6th-century Roman philosopher martyred by the Ostrogothic king Theodoric. It was also borne by a pope.
name: SEVERINUS

meaning: Roman family name meaning "stern" in Latin. This name was borne by several early saints.
name: SEVERUS

meaning: From a surname which was itself derived from the Old English given name SIGEWEARD.
name: SEWARD

meaning: Roman praenomen, or given name, which meant "sixth" in Latin. It was traditionally given to the sixth child.
name: SEXTUS

meaning: From a Norman surname which originally belonged to a person coming from the French town of Saint Maur (which means "Saint MAURUS").
name: SEYMOUR

meaning: Means "command of Aku" in Akkadian, Aku being the name of the Babylonian god of the moon. In the Old Testament Shadrach is the Babylonian name of Hananiah, one of the three men cast into a fiery furnace but saved by God.
name: SHADRACH

meaning: Means "witness" in Arabic. In Islamic tradition الشاهد (al-Shahid) is one of the 99 names of Allah.
name: SHAHID

meaning: Means "pride of the king" from the Persian elements شاه (shah) "king" and ناز (naz) "pride".
name: SHAHNAZ

meaning: Means "free city" from the Persian elements شهر (shahr) "city" and آزاد (azad) "free". This is the name of the fictional storyteller in 'The 1001 Nights'. She tells a story to her husband the king every night for 1001 nights in order to delay her execution.
name: SHAHRAZAD

meaning: Modern Persian form of Avestan Kshathra Vairya meaning "desirable power". In Zoroastrianism this was the name of a god of metal and a protector of the weak. This is also the name of the sixth month of the Iranian calendar.
name: SHAHRIVAR

meaning: Urdu and Hindi form of SHAHROKH. A notable bearer is Indian actor Shahrukh Khan (1965-).
name: SHAHRUKH

meaning: Means "prince, son of the king" in Persian.
name: SHAHZAD

meaning: Means "daughter of the mountain" in Sanskrit, from शैल (shaila) meaning "mountain" and ज (ja) meaning "born". This is another name of the Hindu goddess Parvati.
name: SHAILAJA

meaning: Means "power" in Sanskrit. In Hinduism a shakti is the female counterpart of a god. The name Shakti is used in particular to refer to the female counterpart of Shiva, also known as Parvati among many other names.
name: SHAKTI

meaning: Means "thankful" in Arabic. In Islamic tradition الشكور (al-Shakur) is one of the 99 names of Allah.
name: SHAKUR

meaning: Elaboration of the popular name element Shan.
name: SHANAE

meaning: Anglicized form of SEÁN. It came into general use in America after the release of the western movie 'Shane' (1953).
name: SHANE

meaning: Combination of the popular name elements Shan and ene.
name: SHANENE

meaning: From the Sanskrit name of the planet Saturn. This is the name of a celestial Hindu god.
name: SHANI  (2)

meaning: Combination of the popular name elements Shan and ice.
name: SHANICE

meaning: Combination of the popular name elements Shan and qua.
name: SHANIQUA

meaning: Derived from the Sanskrit elements शम् (sham) meaning "auspicious, lucky" and कर (kara) meaning "maker". This is another name of the Hindu god Shiva. This was also the name of a 9th-century Indian religious philosopher also known as Shankaracharya.
name: SHANKARA

meaning: From the name of the River Shannon, the longest river in Ireland, called Abha na tSionainn in Irish. It is associated with the goddess Sionann and is sometimes said to be named for her. However it is more likely the goddess was named after the river, which may be related to Old Irish sen "old, ancient". As a given name, it first became common in America after the 1940s.
name: SHANNON

meaning: Means "pacified, calm" in Sanskrit. In the Hindu epic the 'Ramayana' this is the name of a daughter of King Dasharatha.
name: SHANTA

meaning: Means "wholesome" in Sanskrit. In the Hindu epic the 'Mahabharata' this is the name of a king of Hastinapura.
name: SHANTANU

meaning: Means "divine law, noble law" in Arabic, ultimately from an old Arabic word meaning "pathway".
name: SHARIAH

meaning: Means "southern people" in the Algonquin language. The Shawnee were an Algonquin tribe who originally lived in the Ohio valley.
name: SHAWNEE

meaning: Variant of SHEILA, influenced by the spelling and sound of KAYLA  (1).
name: SHAYLA

meaning: Possibly means "to look out" in Arabic.
name: SHAYMA

meaning: Means "oath" in Hebrew. This is the name of several characters in the Old Testament. Also in the Bible, this is a place name, referring to a region in Ethiopia. The queen of Sheba visited Solomon after hearing of his wisdom.
name: SHEBA

meaning: Means "petition" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of both a grandson of Shem and a son of Judah.
name: SHELAH

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "valley with steep sides" in Old English. Sheldon is the name of several locations in England.
name: SHELDON

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "clearing on a bank" in Old English. Two famous bearers of the surname were Percy Bysshe Shelley (1792-1822), a romantic poet whose works include 'Adonais' and 'Ozymandias', and Mary Shelley (1797-1851), his wife, the author of the horror story 'Frankenstein'. As a feminine given name, it came into general use after the 1940s.
name: SHELLEY

meaning: Means "name" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament, Shem is one of Noah's three sons (along with Japheth and Ham) and the ancestor of the Semitic peoples.
name: SHEM

meaning: Variant of SHERRY. This particular spelling was popularized by American actress Sheree North (1932-2005), who was born Dawn Shirley Crang.
name: SHEREE

meaning: Used by Scottish author Sir Arthur Conan Doyle for his character Sherlock Holmes, who was a detective in Doyle's mystery stories beginning in 1887. The character's name was from an English surname meaning "shear lock", originally referring to a person with closely cut hair.
name: SHERLOCK

meaning: Before the 20th century this was probably from the Irish surname Ó Searraigh meaning "descendant of Searrach" (a name meaning "foal" in Gaelic). Later it may have been reinforced by the French word chérie meaning "darling", or the English word sherry, a type of fortified wine named from the Spanish town of Jerez. This name came into popular use during the 1920s, inspired by other similar-sounding names and by Collette's novels 'Chéri' (1920, English translation 1929) and 'The Last of Chéri' (1926, English translation 1932), in which it is a masculine name.
name: SHERRY

meaning: From Japanese 七 (shichi) meaning "seven" and 郎 (rou) meaning "son". This was traditionally a name given to the seventh son. Other kanji combinations can be possible.
name: SHICHIROU

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit शील (shila) meaning "conduct, disposition, character".
name: SHILA

meaning: Means "beautiful" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of one of the midwives who disobeys the Pharaoh's order to kill any Hebrew boys they deliver.
name: SHIPHRAH

meaning: Means "sweet" in Persian. This was the name of a character in Persian and Turkish legend.
name: SHIRIN

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "bright clearing" in Old English. This is the name of the main character in Charlotte Brontë's semi-autobiographical novel 'Shirley' (1849). The child actress Shirley Temple (1928-2014) helped to popularize this name.
name: SHIRLEY

meaning: From Japanese 四 (shi) meaning "four" and 郎 (rou) meaning "son". This was traditionally a name for the fourth son. Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: SHIROU

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit शिव (shiva) meaning "benign, kind, auspicious". Shiva is the Hindu god of destruction and restoration, the husband of the mother goddess Parvati. His aspect is usually terrifying, but it can also be gentle.
name: SHIVA  (1)
origin: [Hinduism, Indian, Telugu, Tamil, Kannada, Malayalam, Nepali]

meaning: Means "beloved of SHIVA  (1)" in Sanskrit. This is another name of the Hindu goddess Parvati.
name: SHIVALI

meaning: Probably a blend of SHONA and RHONDA.
name: SHONDA

meaning: From Japanese 翔 (shou) meaning "soar, glide" or 奨 (shou) meaning "prize, reward". Other kanji with identical pronunciations can also form this name.
name: SHOU

meaning: From Japanese 翔 (shou) meaning "soar, glide" and 太 (ta) meaning "thick, big". Other combinations of kanji are also possible.
name: SHOUTA

meaning: Possibly a Yiddish form of ESPERANZA.
name: SHPRINTZA

meaning: Possibly a Yiddish diminutive of ESPERANZA.
name: SHPRINTZEL

meaning: From the name of the Hindu goddess SHRI combined with Sanskrit देवी (devi) meaning "goddess". This is another name of Lakshmi.
name: SHRIDEVI

meaning: Means "husband of Shri" from the name of the Hindu goddess SHRI combined with Sanskrit पति (pati) meaning "husband, lord". This is another name of the Hindu god Vishnu.
name: SHRIPATI

meaning: From Σεθ (Seth), the Greek form of Egyptian Swtkh (reconstructed as Sutekh), which possibly means "pillar" or "dazzle". Seth was the Egyptian god of chaos and the desert, the slayer of Osiris. Orisis' son Horus eventually defeats Seth and has him banished to the desert.
name: SETH  (2)

meaning: Means "of SETH  (2)" in Egyptian. This was the name of two pharaohs of the 19th dynasty.
name: SETI

meaning: From Japanese 節 (setsu) meaning "section, period, verse, melody" and 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other kanji combinations can also be possible.
name: SETSUKO

Sigurd was the hero of the Norse legend the 'Volsungasaga', which tells how his foster-father Regin sent him to recover a hoard of gold guarded by the dragon Fafnir. After slaying the dragon Sigurd tasted some of its blood, enabling him to understand the language of birds, who told him that Regin was planning to betray him. In a later adventure, Sigurd disguised himself as Gunnar (his wife Gudrun's brother) and rescued the maiden Brynhildr from a ring of fire, with the result that Gunnar and Brynhildr were married. When the truth eventually came out, Brynhildr took revenge upon Sigurd. The stories of the German hero Siegfried were in part based on him.

meaning: From Greek Σιβυλλα (Sibylla), meaning "prophetess, sibyl". In Greek and Roman legend the sibyls were ten female prophets who practiced at different holy sites in the ancient world. In later Christian theology, the sibyls were thought to have divine knowledge and were revered in much the same way as the Old Testament prophets. Because of this, the name came into general use in the Christian world during the Middle Ages. The Normans brought it to England, where it was spelled both Sibyl and Sybil. It became rare after the Protestant Reformation, but it was revived in the 19th century, perhaps helped by Benjamin Disraeli's novel 'Sybil' (1845).

He secretly helped the Burgundian king Günther overcome the challenges set out by the Icelandic queen Brünhild so that Günther might win her hand. In exchange, Günther consented to the marriage of Siegfried and his sister Kriemhild. Years later, after a dispute between Brünhild and Kriemhild, Siegfried was murdered by Hagen with Günther's consent. He was stabbed in his one vulnerable spot on the small of his back, which had been covered by a leaf while he bathed in dragon's blood. His adventures were largely based on those of the Norse hero Sigurd. The story was later adapted by Richard Wagner to form part of his opera 'The Ring of the Nibelung' (1876).
name: SIEGFRIED

meaning: Derived from the Germanic elements sigu "victory" and hild "battle".

name: SYLVESTER

meaning: Norwegian and Swedish variant of SOLVEIG. It is also used as a short form of SYLVIA.
name: SYLVI

meaning: Simply from the English word, ultimately deriving from Greek συμφωνος (symphonos) "concordant in sound".
name: SYMPHONY

meaning: Ancient Greek name meaning "common fate". This is the name of a woman mentioned in Paul's epistle to the Philippians in the New Testament.
name: SYNTYCHE

meaning: Means "lucky, successful, happy" in Polish, a vernacular form of Felix.
name: SZCZĘSNY

meaning: Derived from Latin tace meaning "be silent". It was in use from the 16th century, though it died out two centuries later.
name: TACEY

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of TACITUS.
name: TACITO

meaning: Czech and Slovak form of THADDEUS.
name: TADEÁŠ

meaning: Means "poet" in Irish. This was the name of an 11th-century king of Connacht.
name: TADHG

meaning: From the Arabic letters ط (called ta) and ه (called ha). These letters begin the 20th chapter of the Qur'an (sura Ta Ha).
name: TAHA

meaning: From Japanese 太 (ta) meaning "thick, big" and 一 (ichi) meaning "one", in addition to other combinations of kanji which are pronounced the same way.
name: TAICHI

meaning: Derived from Croatian and Serbian tajiti "to keep secret".
name: TAJANA

meaning: Combination of the prefix Ta with the name JUANA.
name: TAJUANA

meaning: From Japanese 孝 (taka) meaning "filial piety" and 子 (ko) meaning "child", as well as other combinations of kanji characters.
name: TAKAKO

meaning: From Japanese 孝 (takashi) meaning "filial piety", 隆 (takashi) meaning "noble, prosperous" or 崇 (takashi) meaning "esteem, honour, venerate", as well as other kanji or kanji combinations which result in the same pronunciation.
name: TAKASHI

meaning: From Japanese 武 (takeshi) meaning "military, martial" or other kanji having the same reading.
name: TAKESHI

meaning: From Japanese 拓 (taku) meaning "expand, open, support" and 真 (ma) meaning "real, genuine". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: TAKUMA

meaning: From Japanese 拓 (taku) meaning "expand, open, support" combined with 也 (ya) meaning "also" or 哉 (ya), an exclamation. This name can be formed with other kanji combinations as well.
name: TAKUYA

meaning: From a Welsh place name meaning "high hill", derived from Welsh tal "high" and bryn "hill".
name: TALFRYN

meaning: From the name of a town in South Australia, perhaps meaning "near water" in an Australian Aboriginal language.
name: TALIA  (2)

meaning: From the name of an Armenian town (meaning unknown) which is home to a famous 7th-century cathedral.
name: TALIN

meaning: Portuguese form of TALITHA, popular in Brazil.
name: TALITA

meaning: Means "furrowed" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this name is borne by both a giant and also the father of King David's wife Maacah.
name: TALMAI

meaning: From the Gaelic name Tuilelaith, which was derived from Irish tuile "abundance" and flaith "princess".
name: TALULLA

meaning: Means "wish, desire" in Hindi, ultimately from Persian تمنّا (tamanna).
name: TAMANNA

meaning: Russian form of TAMAR. Russian performers such as Tamara Karsavina (1885-1978), Tamara Drasin (1905-1943), Tamara Geva (1907-1997) and Tamara Toumanova (1919-1996) introduced it to the English-speaking world. It was also borne by the Polish cubist painter Tamara de Lempicka (1898-1980).
name: TAMARA
origin: [Russian, Ukrainian, Czech, Slovak, Polish, Slovene, Croatian, Serbian, Macedonian, Hungarian, English, Dutch, Spanish, Italian]

meaning: Probably a combination of TAMARA and PAMELA. It first arose in the 1950s.
name: TAMELA

meaning: Westernized form of Timur i Leng (see TIMUR).
name: TAMERLANE

meaning: From Japanese 多 (ta) meaning "many", 美 (mi) meaning "beautiful" and 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other kanji combinations are also possible.
name: TAMIKO

meaning: Short form of TAMARA and other names beginning with Tam.
name: TAMMY

meaning: Contracted form of THOMASINA. It was traditionally used in Cornwall.
name: TAMSIN

meaning: Italian form of TANCRED. Gioachino Rossini used this name in his opera 'Tancredi' (1813).
name: TANCREDI

meaning: From the name of the season, ultimately from Old English sumor. It has been in use as a given name since the 1970s.
name: SUMMER

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit सुन्दर (sundara) meaning "beautiful". This is the name of several minor characters in Hindu texts, and is also another name of the Hindu god Krishna.
name: SUNDARA

meaning: From Sanskrit सु (su) meaning "good, very" combined with नील (nila) meaning "dark blue".
name: SUNIL
origin: [Indian, Hindi, Marathi, Bengali, Assamese, Gujarati, Punjabi, Telugu, Tamil, Kannada, Malayalam, Nepali]

meaning: Scandinavian form of the Old English name Sunngifu, which meant "sun gift" from the Old English elements sunne "sun" and giefu "gift". This was the name of a legendary English saint who was shipwrecked in Norway and killed by the inhabitants.
name: SUNNIVA

meaning: From the English word, ultimately from Old English sunne "sun" and scinan "shine".
name: SUNSHINE

meaning: Means "sun" in several northern Indian languages, derived from Sanskrit सूर्य (surya).
name: SURAJ
SURESH
origin: [Indian, Hindi, Marathi, Tamil, Telugu, Malayalam, Kannada, Nepali]

meaning: Variant of SURENDRA used by Sikhs.
name: SURINDER

meaning: Means "sun" in Sanskrit. This is the name of the Hindu god of the sun.
name: SURYA
origin: [Hinduism, Indian, Telugu, Kannada, Tamil, Malayalam, Hindi, Marathi, Nepali, Indonesian]

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of SUSANNA.
name: SUSANA

meaning: German and Scandinavian short form of SUSANNE.
name: SUSANN

meaning: Form of SUSANNA found in some versions of the Old Testament.
name: SUSANNAH

meaning: From Japanese 進 (susumu) meaning "advance, make progress", as well as other kanji or kanji combinations having the same pronunciation.
name: SUSUMU

meaning: From Japanese 鈴 (suzu) meaning "bell" or other kanji having the same pronunciation.
name: SUZU

meaning: Derived from the Slavic element svetu meaning "blessed, holy".
name: SVATAVA

meaning: From a personification of the country of Sweden, in use since the 17th century. It is a derivative of Svear, the Swedish name for the ancient Germanic tribe the Swedes. The Swedish name of the country of Sweden is Sverige, a newer form of Svear rike meaning "the realm of the Svear".
name: SVEA

meaning: From the Old Norse name Sverrir which meant "wild, swinging, spinning".
name: SVERRE

meaning: Derived from Slavic svet meaning "light, world". It was popularized by the poem 'Svetlana' (1813) by the Russian poet Vasily Zhukovsky. It is sometimes used as a translation of Photine.
name: SVETLANA

meaning: Possible medieval Slavic form of SVYATOPOLK.
name: SVETOPOLK

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements svetu "blessed, holy" and vidu "sight, view". This was the name of a four-headed Slavic god of war and light.
name: SVETOVID

meaning: Means "blessed people" from the Slavic elements svetu "blessed, holy" and pulku "people, host, army".
name: SVYATOPOLK

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit स्वपन (svapana) meaning "sleeping, dreaming".
name: SWAPAN

meaning: Derived from Sanskrit स्वप्न (svapna) meaning "sleep, dream".
name: SWAPNIL

meaning: Means "good colour" or "golden", a contraction of the Sanskrit prefix सु (su) meaning "good" and वर्ण (varna) meaning "colour". This is a transcription of both the masculine form स्वर्ण and the feminine form स्वर्णा.
name: SWARNA

meaning: From the Indian name of the third brightest star in the night sky, called Arcturus in the western world.
name: SWATI

meaning: Derived from the Slavic elements svetu "blessed, holy" and miru "peace, world".
name: ŚWIĘTOMIERZ

meaning: From the Old English name Swiðhun or Swiþhun, derived from swiþ "strong" and perhaps hun "bear cub". Saint Swithin was a 9th-century bishop of Winchester.
name: SWITHIN

meaning: Variant of SIBYL. This spelling variation has existed since the Middle Ages.
name: SYBIL

meaning: German and French form of SIBYL.
name: SYBILLE

meaning: Variant of SILVIA. This has been the most common English spelling since the 19th century.
name: SYLVIA

meaning: Old Testament Greek (though occurring rarely in the New Testament) and Latin form of SIMEON.
name: SYMEON

meaning: Ukrainian form of SIMON (mostly ecclesiastical usage).
name: SYMON

meaning: Meaning unknown, possibly from a Slavic word meaning "marten". It was borne by a leader of the Magyars at the time of Árpád. This is now the name of a region in Hungary.
name: SZABOLCS

meaning: Means "solid, firm" in Hungarian, also used as a Hungarian vernacular form of Constantine.
name: SZILÁRD

meaning: Estonian and Finnish form of DAVID.
name: TAAVI

meaning: German short form of TABITHA. This form was used in earlier editions of the Luther Bible.
name: TABEA

meaning: Means "gazelle" in Aramaic. Tabitha in the New Testament was a woman restored to life by Saint Peter. Her name is translated into Greek as Dorcas (see Acts 9:36). As an English name, Tabitha became common after the Protestant Reformation. It was popularized in the 1960s by the television show 'Bewitched', in which Tabitha (sometimes spelled Tabatha) is the daughter of the main character.
name: TABITHA

meaning: Roman cognomen which meant "silent, mute" in Latin. This was the name of a 1st-century Roman historian.
name: TACITUS

meaning: Means "we have been blessed" in Chewa.
name: TADALA

meaning: Possibly means "he who inspires awe" in Amharic. This name was borne by Lij Tafari Makonnen (1892-1975), also known as Haile Selassie, the last emperor of Ethiopia. Rastafarians (Ras Tafari meaning "king Tafari") revere him as the earthly incarnation of God.
name: TAFARI

meaning: Variant of TAHIRA. This was the title of Fatimah Baraghani, a 19th-century Persian poet, theologian and reformer.
name: TÁHIRIH

meaning: Persian form of the Avestan name Takhmaspa, which was derived from takhma "strong, brave, valiant" and aspa "horse". This name was borne by two Safavid shahs of Persia.
name: TAHMASP

meaning: Persian form of Avestan Takhma Urupi meaning "strong body". Takhma Urupi is a hero from the Avesta who later appears in the 11th-century Persian epic the 'Shahnameh'.
name: TAHMURAS

meaning: From Chinese 太 (tài) meaning "very, extreme" or other characters pronounced in a similar way.
name: TAI

meaning: From Japanese 大 (tai) meaning "big, great" and 輝 (ki) meaning "brightness" or 樹 (ki) meaning "tree". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: TAIKI

meaning: Possibly a Russian form of THAÏS.
name: TAISIYA

meaning: From Japanese 貴 (taka) meaning "valuable" or 孝 (taka) meaning "filial piety" combined with 大 (hiro) meaning "big, great" or 浩 (hiro) meaning "prosperous". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: TAKAHIRO

meaning: From Japanese 宝 (takara) meaning "treasure, jewel", as well as other kanji or kanji combinations with the same pronunciation.
name: TAKARA

meaning: From Japanese 武 (take) meaning "military, martial" or 竹 (take) meaning "bamboo" combined with 彦 (hiko) meaning "boy, prince". Other kanji combinations are also possible.
name: TAKEHIKO

meaning: From Japanese 匠 (takumi) meaning "artisan" or 巧 (takumi) meaning "skillful". It can also come from 拓 (taku) meaning "expand, open, support" combined with 海 (mi) meaning "sea, ocean" or 実 (mi) meaning "fruit, good result, truth". This name can also be formed of other kanji combinations.
name: TAKUMI

meaning: From a surname which was perhaps derived from a Germanic given name composed of the elements tal "to destroy" and bod "message".
name: TALBOT

meaning: Kazakh and Tatar form of TAL'AT.
name: TALGAT

meaning: Means "seeker of knowledge, student" in Arabic. Abu Talib was an uncle of Muhammad who raised him after his parents and grandparents died. His name was in fact a kunya (a nickname) formed using Abu; his real name may have been Imran.
name: TALIB

meaning: Means "shining brow", derived from Welsh tal "brow" and iesin "shining". This was the name of a 6th-century Welsh poet and bard. In later Welsh legends he is portrayed as a wizard and prophet, or as a companion of King Arthur.
name: TALIESIN

meaning: Combination of the popular name prefix Ta and LISHA.
name: TALISHA

meaning: Means "little girl" in Aramaic. The name is taken from the phrase talitha cumi meaning "little girl arise" spoken by Jesus in order to restore a young girl to life (see Mark 5:41).
name: TALITHA

meaning: Popularly claimed to mean "leaping waters" in the Choctaw language, it may actually mean "town" in the Creek language. This is the name of waterfalls in Georgia. It was borne by American actress Tallulah Bankhead (1902-1968), who was named after her grandmother, who may have been named after the waterfalls.
name: TALLULAH

meaning: From the English meaning "talon, claw", ultimately derived (via Norman French) from Latin talus "anklebone".
name: TALON

meaning: Means "palm tree" in Hebrew. According to the Old Testament Tamar was the daughter-in-law of Judah and later his wife. This was also the name of a daughter of King David. She was raped by her half-brother Amnon, leading to his murder by her brother Absalom. The name was borne by a 12th-century ruling queen of Georgia who presided over the kingdom at the peak of its power.
name: TAMAR

meaning: Elaborated form of the popular name syllable Tam, from names such as TAMARA or TAMIKA. It was popularized by Canadian singer Tamia Hill (1975-), who is known simply as Tamia.
name: TAMIA

meaning: Variant of TAMIKO, inspired by the American jazz singer Tamiko Jones (1945-) or the American movie 'A Girl Named Tamiko' (1963).
name: TAMIKA

meaning: Italian form of the Germanic name Thancmar, which was composed of the elements thank "thought" and meri "famous".
name: TAMMARO

meaning: Norman form of a Germanic name meaning "thought and counsel", derived from the elements thank "thought" and rad "counsel". This was the name of a leader of the First Crusade, described by Torquato Tasso in his epic poem 'Jerusalem Delivered' (1580).
name: TANCRED

meaning: Means "man" in Maori. In Maori and other Polynesian mythology Tane was the god of forests and light. He was the son of the sky god Rangi and the earth goddess Papa, who were locked in an embrace and finally separated by their son. He created the tui bird and, by some accounts, man.
name: TANE

meaning: Combination of the popular name element Tan (from names such as TANYA) and the common name suffix qua.
name: TANIQUA

meaning: Combination of the popular name element Tan (from names such as TANYA) and the common name suffix sha.
name: TANISHA

meaning: Derived from Semitic roots meaning "serpent lady". This was the name of the Phoenician goddess of love, fertility, the moon and the stars.
name: TANITH

meaning: From an English surname meaning "one who tans hides".
name: TANNER

meaning: Russian diminutive of TATIANA. It began to be used in the English-speaking world during the 1930s.
name: TANYA

meaning: From Chinese 涛 (tāo) meaning "large waves", as well as other characters with a similar pronunciation.
name: TAO

meaning: Means "star" in Sanskrit. Tara is the name of a Hindu astral goddess, the wife of Brhaspati. She was abducted by Soma, a god of the moon, leading to a great war that was only ended when Brahma intervened and released her. This is also the name of a Buddhist deity (a female Buddha).
name: TARA  (2)

meaning: Ukrainian and Russian form of the Greek name Ταρασιος (Tarasios), which possibly means "from Taras". Taras was an Italian city, now called Taranto, which was founded by Greek colonists in the 8th century BC and was named for the Greek mythological figure Taras, a son of Poseidon. Saint Tarasios was an 8th-century bishop of Constantinople. It was also borne by the Ukrainian writer and artist Taras Shevchenko (1814-1861).
name: TARAS

meaning: Turkish form of TARIQ. This name is spelled with a Turkish dotless i, as Tarık.
name: TARIK

meaning: Perhaps an elaborated form of TARA  (1).
name: TARINA

meaning: Means "vigour, energy, drive" in Estonian and Finnish.
name: TARMO

meaning: From Japanese 太 (ta) meaning "thick, big" and 郎 (rou) meaning "son". Other kanji combinations are possible.
name: TAROU

meaning: Probably a feminine form of TYRONE. Actors Tyrone Power and Linda Christian created it for their daughter Taryn Power (1953-).
name: TARYN

meaning: From an English surname which was derived from the Old English given name Tata, of unknown origin.
name: TATE

meaning: Feminine form of the Roman name Tatianus, a derivative of the Roman name TATIUS. This was the name of a 3rd-century saint who was martyred in Rome under the emperor Alexander Severus. She was especially venerated in Orthodox Christianity, and the name has been common in Russia and Eastern Europe. It was not regularly used in the English-speaking world until the 1980s.
name: TATIANA
origin: [Russian, Slovak, Bulgarian, Romanian, Polish, Greek, Georgian, Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, Finnish, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, German, Dutch, English, Ancient Roman]

meaning: Roman cognomen which was derived from TATIUS.
name: TATIANUS

meaning: Roman family name of unknown meaning, possibly of Sabine origin. According to Roman legend, Titus Tatius was an 8th-century BC king of the Sabines who came to jointly rule over the Romans and Sabines with the Roman king Romulus.
name: TATIUS

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "Tata's town" in Old English.
name: TATTON

meaning: From a surname which was originally derived from a place name meaning "Tata's homestead" in Old English.
name: TATUM

meaning: Anglicized form of Thàmhais, vocative case of TÀMHAS. Alternatively it could be taken from the Scottish surname MacTavish, Anglicized form of Mac Tàmhais, meaning "son of Thomas".
name: TAVISH

meaning: From the English word, ultimately deriving from Old French tané, which means "light brown".
name: TAWNY

meaning: Probably a feminine form of TAYLOR influenced by similar-sounding names such as KAYLA  (1).
name: TAYLA

meaning: From an Irish surname, an Anglicized form of Ó Tadhgáin meaning "descendant of Tadhgán". The given name Tadhgán is a diminutive of TADHG.
name: TEAGAN

meaning: From the English word for the type of duck or the greenish-blue colour.
name: TEAL

meaning: Scottish form of TOIRDHEALBHACH. This name is also used as a Scottish form of CHARLES.
name: TEÀRLACH

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of THEKLA.
name: TECLA

meaning: Short form of EDWARD or THEODORE. A famous bearer was the American baseball player Ted Williams (1918-2002), who was born as Theodore.
name: TED

meaning: Derived from the Welsh elements teg "fair" and gwen "blessed".
name: TEGWEN

meaning: Possibly means either "stockade" or "horn, trumpet" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of a both a city and a son of Ashhur.
name: TEKOA

meaning: French form of the Greek name Τελεσφορος (Telesphoros) which means "bringing fulfillment" or "bearing fruit". Saint Telesphorus was a 2nd-century pope and martyr.
name: TÉLESPHORE

meaning: Latinized form of the Greek name Telesphoros (see TÉLESPHORE).
name: TELESPHORUS

meaning: Either a Portuguese form of THELMA or a feminine form of TELMO.
name: TELMA

meaning: Means "right hand" or "south" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament this is the name of a grandson of Esau for whom the town of Teman in Edom was named.
name: TEMAN

meaning: From the English word meaning "storm". It appears in the title of William Shakespeare's play 'The Tempest' (1611).
name: TEMPEST

meaning: Derived from Turkic tengiz meaning "sea, ocean".
name: TENGIZ

meaning: From an English surname which meant "son of Tenney", Tenney being a medieval form of DENIS. A notable bearer of the surname was British poet Alfred Lord Tennyson (1809-1892).
name: TENNYSON

meaning: From Tibetan བསྟན་འཛིན (bstan-'dzin) which means "upholder of teachings". This is one of the given names of the current Dalai Lama, Tenzin Gyatso (1935-).
name: TENZIN

meaning: Short form of TEODORO and other names that begin with Teo.
name: TÉO

meaning: Spanish, Portuguese and Italian form of THEOBALD.
name: TEOBALDO

meaning: Italian, Spanish and Portuguese form of Theodoros (see THEODORE).
name: TEODORO

meaning: Serbian and Macedonian form of THEODOSIA.
name: TEODOSIJA

meaning: Italian and Spanish form of THEODOSIUS.
name: TEODOSIO

meaning: Spanish and Portuguese form of THEOPHILUS.
name: TEÓFILO

meaning: Possibly means "station" in Hebrew. In the Old Testament Terah is the father of Abraham. He led his people out of Ur and towards Canaan, but died along the way.
name: TERAH

meaning: Means "third" in Spanish. This name was traditionally given to the third child born.
name: TERCERO

meaning: Georgian form of Terentius (see TERENCE). It is also a Russian variant transcription of TERENTIY.
name: TERENTI

meaning: Cognate of THERESA. Saint Teresa of Ávila was a 16th-century Spanish nun who reformed the Carmelite monasteries and wrote several spiritual books. It was also borne by the beatified Albanian missionary Mother Teresa (1910-1997), who worked with the poor in Calcutta. She adopted the name in honour of the French saint Thérèse de Lisieux, who is the patron of missionaries.
name: TERESA
origin: [Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, Polish, Finnish, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, English]

meaning: Czech, Portuguese, Bulgarian and Romanian form of THERESA.
name: TEREZA

meaning: Means "limit, boundary, end" in Latin. This was the name of the Roman god of boundaries.
name: TERMINUS

meaning: Means "enjoying the dance" from Greek τερψις (terpsis) "delight" and χορος (choros) "dance". In Greek mythology she was the goddess of dance and dramatic chorus, one of the nine Muses.
name: TERPSICHORE

meaning: Either a strictly feminine form of TERRY  (1) or a diminutive of THERESA.
name: TERRIE

meaning: Diminutive of TERENCE or THERESA. A famous bearer was Terry Fox (1958-1981), a young man with an artificial leg who attempted to run across Canada to raise money for cancer research. He died of the disease before crossing the country.
name: TERRY  (2)

meaning: Means "warmth from the sun" in Welsh.
